<HEADLINE>LEISURE Euro Disney makes first profit</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Nicola Reeves</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975355978</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EURO Disney has made a profit, one year ahead of schedule. In the year to
September 30 the group which operates the Disneyland Paris theme park made a
profit of #15m compared with a loss last year of more than #230m.
This is the first profit since the park opened three years ago. A 20% increase
in attendances to 10.7 million following the decision to lower prices by around
20% helped, as did improved operating cashflow. But the major factor in the
turnaround was last year's financial restructuring package.
Steve Burke, chief operating officer, said the results laid to rest the debate
over whether Paris was the right location for a Disney theme park. ``We have
broken the negative spiral that was in place 18 months ago.'' He added that in
1996 and 1997 the company would move from being troubled to solidly profitable.
During the year, revenues from the theme park rose by 8%, while hotel revenues
grew by 16%. Occupancy levels increased by 8% to 68%, out-performing the
general Parisian market.
The introduction of new rides, such as Space Mountain, helped to attract more
visitors. Since opening in 1992, 6% of all Europeans have visited Euro Disney.
British vistors make up around 10% of the total at 1.1 million.
In future, other off-park leisure activities, such as a multiplex cinema
showing some Disney films, a Planet Hollywood burger bar and convention centre,
are expected to add to the off-peak attraction of the site.
Park admissions account for just over a quarter of the group's revenues, with
hotels and other activities making up the remainder.
Other developments are being contemplated including all-inclusive tours and a
designated Disney train travelling from Waterloo Station in London via the
Channel Tunnel. The company's prime objectives are to encourage repeat visits
and increase the spend per visitor. The Spanish and Germans are the biggest
spenders.
Despite the encouraging results, City analysts still consider the shares
overvalued. Euro Disney will have to make substantially more money to warrant
its stock market price. Many analysts remain concerned about the debt charges
facing it after its debt and management fee holiday is phased out. It still has
a debt mountain of #2000m.
In volatile trading the shares closed in London down 21p at 194p.
</TEXT>
