<TEXT>
Prison hunger
strike record
A PRISONER today will pass the record for the longest jail hunger strike -
after going without food for 386 days.
Idris Belaifa, 42, who blew up his own grocery store in a bungled insurance
fiddle, has amazed doctors by refusing to eat solid food since he was sent to
Walton Jail in Liverpool on October 26 last year. The previous longest recorded
hunger strike was 385 days by Denis Goodwin at Wakefield prison from June 28,
1972 to July 18, 1973.
Argyll honour
SIR Fitzroy Maclean, 84, is to be given the Freedom of Argyll. Argyll and Bute
District Council agreed to bestow the honour on the wartime hero at a meeting
in Lochgilphead yesterday.
Royal birthday
THE Princess Royal's son, Peter Phillips, yesterday celebrated his 18th
birthday with an afternoon of firefighting drills at Gordonstoun School. Staff
said there were no plans for a birthday party.
Driving ban
A FOOTBALLER who admitted drinking and driving was fined #500 at Perth Sheriff
Court yesterday. St Johnstone midfielder Gary Farquhar, 24, was also banned for
15 months.
Ear survey
A MAJOR survey is to be conducted to gauge the success of treatment for ear
problems among children. A postal questionnaire is to be sent to the parents of
1000 youngsters who have recently attended hospital as out-patients or
undergone operations in Scotland.
Fast growth
BRITAIN'S only supplier of genetically altered trees yesterday announced that
it is to create 19 jobs in an #400,000 expansion. Christie Elite Nurseries in
Forres, Moray, sells specially bred Sitka Spruce, which are taller, stronger,
and faster growing than the wild trees.
Whale of a time
CHILDREN at Bressay primary school, Shetland, had an extra nature-study lesson
yesterday when a 40ft minke whale cruised into Lerwick Harbour and spouted a
few hundred yards offshore. Whales are seen rarely in the busy harbour, used by
more than 5000 ships a year.
Bullock on loose
A RAMPAGING bullock brought parts of Edinburgh to a standstill and delayed rail
services between Edinburgh and Glasgow for nearly two hours yesterday. The
animal escaped at about 10.30am from the Gorgie cattle complex and ran amok on
roads in the area, before clambering on to the Edinburgh to Glasgow and Fife
railway. Police marksmen shot it dead.
Deathtrap flat
A MAN who turned his home into an electrified fortress and mounted a spying
campaign on social security officials was sent to a mental hospital for an
indefinite period yesterday. John Commins went 20 years without receiving badly
needed treatment after slipping through the mental health safety net. His
behaviour became increasingly bizarre, culminating in his ``deathtrap'' flat
and an unprovoked stabbing of a supermarket security guard. Snaresbrook Crown
Court in East London heard that Commins, 46, wired each door of his flat to the
power supply.
Phone clue
A BUNGLING thief who left his home number on a farmer's answerphone before
turning up and helping steal his caravan was sentenced to 160 hours community
service at Stirling Sheriff Court yesterday . Mark Charles, 25, of Petershill
Road, Glasgow, phoned Drum Farm at Carronbridge, Stirlingshire after seeing an
advert for the caravan. A few days later, he turned up with a friend and
badgered a farm worker into allowing them to test the van by hitching it to the
back of their car. Then they drove off.
</TEXT>
