<HEADLINE>Euro-MPs back demands for consumer action Support grows for Shell boycott</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MURRAY RITCHIE European Editorr</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975355980</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A WORLDWIDE boycott of Shell products was in prospect last night.
Euro-MPs from the major parties threw their support behind a call by Ken Wiwa,
journalist son of the executed Nigerian human-rights campaigner Ken Saro-Wiwa,
for consumer action.
Mr Wiwa said in Strasbourg yesterday: ``I would urge consumers to make an
intelligent decision on whether or not to purchase Shell products.
``I will continue to boycott these products as I have done for the past five
years.''
The European Parliament tonight is expected to back sanctions against the
Nigerian regime which receives more Third World aid from Europe than any other
country.
Euro-MPs will be voting on a series of proposed sanctions but they failed
yesterday to agree on a written demand for a consumer boycott or even an oil
embargo.
Party differences proved too strong and led to a weak-worded compromise stating
only that an oil embargo would be ``one of the most effective methods'' of
pressuring Nigeria's military junta. A consumer boycott did not even rate a
formal mention.
However, many senior Euro-MPs said in private they accepted the need for an oil
embargo and expressed their belief that a consumer boycott was now inevitable.
Oil accounts for an estimated 98% of Nigeria's income.
As the assembly debated sanctions against Nigeria, EU ambassadors to Brussels,
including the new British permanent representative, Mr Stephen Wall, were
gathered to plot the freezing out of Nigeria from aid and trade. They were also
expected to stop short of recommending an oil embargo.
Mr Malcolm Rifkind, Foreign Secretary, will discuss EU action with foreign
ministers in Brussels on Monday.
Nigeria receives #84m a year from the EU under the Lome convention, the world's
biggest trade-aid package, which is worth #12bn over a decade to African,
Caribbean, and Pacific states.
Mr Wiwa, looking exhausted, told reporters he wanted a boycott of Shell as well
as an oil embargo. He urged shoppers, before they decided to buy Shell
products, to consider the fate of his father and eight other human-rights
campaigners hanged by the junta.
He described as ``extraordinary insensitivity'' the decision by Shell to press
ahead in Nigeria with its planned investment in a #2700m liquefied natural gas
project which Labour Euro-MP Mrs Glenys Kinnock described as the biggest
investment in Africa.
``I am absolutely amazed and flabbergasted,'' he said. ``This company does not
care about people.''
Shell is the technical leader of the project which also involves the Nigerian
National Petroleum Corporation, Agip of Italy, and Elf of France. The World
Bank's International Financial Corporation arm pulled out last week.
Mr Wiwa's remarks received strong cross-party sympathy as Euro-MPs debated the
executions amid a rising clamour for a total oil embargo and consumer action.
Even British Tories, including Mr Edward McMillan-Scott (York), said they
believed in a consumer boycott.
Mr McMillan-Scott said a boycott would take place on a world-wide scale. ``I
will not be buying Shell products until there is democracy in Nigeria,'' he
said.
However, Lord Plumb, Conservative Euro-leader, was careful to say only that the
issue was worth considering. He ruled out the Tories formally signing a
compromise demanding a boycott but added: ``There will be a strong call for a
boycott of Shell products - there is no doubt about that.''
Mrs Kinnock, who was leading a European campaign to save Mr Saro-Wiwa's life
when news of the hangings broke last week, added: ``I say yes to a boycott of
Shell. It is entirely appropriate for citizens of the European Union to take
this kind of action.''
The European Commission has said it believes EU action against Nigeria should
form part of an international effort under the banner of the United Nations.
Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali, UN Secretary General, told Euro-MPs this week he
favoured an arms embargo but considered a trade embargo too complicated to work.
The EU takes 39% of Nigeria's oil exports. The United States takes a further
40%.
</TEXT>
