<HEADLINE>Call for action on land-deal secrecy</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROSS Highland Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975355981</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS the purchasers of Knoydart Estate continued to keep their identity hidden
yesterday, the chairman of the new Highland Council's land and environment
committee called for greater openness in land deals in Scotland.
Dr Michael Foxley said: ``One idea we will examine is purchasers providing an
audit of their financial standing, to try and get away from the banks
bankrolling unsuitable purchasers. The local community and the local authority
should also be able to consider purchasers' intentions for their new
acquisition.''
Research into the Kinloch Investment Company Limited yesterday revealed the
identity of just one director, Mr Alistair Hall, the Blairgowrie solicitor
acting for the company. He said he would add nothing to a statement being
issued by the Edinburgh-based selling agents Strutt and Parker.
This confirmed that Kinloch's offer had been accepted and that the offer was in
the region of the #1.5m asking price.
The statement concluded: ``Kinloch Investment Company Limited is a company
registered in Scotland and owned by Scots. It is their intention to take over
the estate shortly before Christmas.
``At this early stage, it is their plan to continue to manage the estate along
traditional lines involving red deer stalking, forestry, and other rural
Highland estate enterprises.''
Solicitors acting for the sellers, Jute company Titaghur, travelled to
Blairgowrie to meet Mr Hall yesterday.
</TEXT>
