<HEADLINE>Nurturing the roots through car boots</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>John Beattie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>38</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>diary </FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975355982</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NEVER ones to miss a trick, the rugby authorities in Glasgow have now ensured
the rapid promotion of the game in Maryhill with a simple piece of planning.
Scott Kerr, one of the rugby promotion chappies in the area, left his car
unattended and paid the price. It was stolen.
In the boot had been a stock of rugby balls, which were subsequently changing
hands at #1 a time in the bars of Maryhill. ``Ssshhh . . . want a stereo and a
Gilbert size 5?''
Shade Munro was not too displeased at what had happened. ``It was unfortunate
that Scott had his car stolen,'' said the former international second row,
``but if they use the balls, then we are happy.''
The Diary firmly believes that there are vast areas of Scotland that would
benefit from this subterfuge - in fact, the whole of Glasgow for starters.
Leaving cars unattended with their boots crammed full of rugby balls might be
the way to promote the game at the grass roots of society in every country of
the world.
How come the SRU never thought of that then?
q SO Graham Ellis is to become seven-and-a-half grand richer on Saturday, when
he sits on the bench as reserve hooker for Scotland. Five grand retainer, the
balance an appearance fee. It has an odd feel to it, doesn't it?
Mind you, not half as odd as the tale that reached us from one of his
team-mates, which says that when he is staying with representative sides his
wife appears early in the morning to strap him up for the game ahead and then
analyses his play later in the day. At least, that's what she says she's doing.
And I bet Kevin McKenzie, who would probably have been playing, is pretty
scunnered with it all. McKenzie had the medial ligament of his right knee
stretched out of all recognition when Kevin Allan, the Melrose prop, kicked him
on the outside of the joint at the Greenyards on October 7.
The Diary hears that McKenzie will now not play until December, because of the
joint's instability. Now, if it were football.
q THE Diary understands that Peter Phillips was warned by the referee for
over-eager use of the boot on Saturday in Dundee. Was this just another royal
stamping his authority on society?
q THE current presenter of Rugby Special is Mark Souster. A little old lady
approached him at a game and asked where he had come from.
``I was at Sky,'' he said.
``Oh,'' said the old dear. ``Such a lovely place. And what part of Skye do you
come from then?''
q IT was Kenny Milne who pointed out how the crowd at Mansfield Park swells at
half-time. Watching the game on Sunday between Scotland A and Western Samoa,
Milne said: ``Just watch. They all get in free at half-time.''
Sure enough, we witnessed the Mansfield Park crowd grow. Perhaps they had been
nicking rugby balls out the back of cars.
q CONGRATULATIONS to Alec McDougall of Glasgow Southern, who is playing his
500th game for the club on Sunday, an event which will be celebrated with a
dinner on Monday night.
Like many a player, he has graduated from the back row to the middle row, to
the front row. He must be old. I played against him.
</TEXT>
