<HEADLINE>The success message is on the bottle</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975355983</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TOM Gibson has a mission and he hopes that the message for success is on a
bottle, for he plans to sell whisky galore to the Chinese.
It is the first time anyone has bottled it with a label in their own language -
and in their own country.
The characters on the label, Mei Jing Li mean barley or malt, gold, and
profits, and the first bottle had just rolled off his new plant in Beijing.
Glasgow-based Cathay Atlantic is probably the first Scottish firm to set up a
joint venture company with the Chinese Government.
q A single bottle of late nineteenth century Craigellachie Rare Reserve fetched
#2070 - more than twice that expected - at a Christie's whisky sale in Glasgow
yesterday.
The bottle of Old Highland Malt was bought by United Distillers.A bottle of
Very Fine Glen Grant, ``specially selected and bottled for Mrs Grant of
Lossiemouth'', made #1265.
</TEXT>
