<DOCNO>GH951116-000006</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000006</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Buggins' turn comes to an end</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUG GILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>38</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975355984</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POSTS in Scottish athletics have all too frequently been filled on the Buggins'
turn principle, with occasional maverick inadequates, incompetents, or simply
unsuitable people in key roles.
Athletes are no angels, but the frequency of outbursts against officialdom, and
even refusal to compete for their country, highlights a problem.
That should end, however, under new proposals likely to be adopted next year,
which call for senior office-bearers - including president, treasurer, and
secretary - to be interviewed.
But the Scottish Athletics Federation anticipated approval yesterday by
revealing that applicants for the job of international team manager will have
to submit a curriculum vitae, and be grilled in competitive interviews.
The job specification (applications close on December 15) demands they
demonstrate the ability, time, and commitment for the job, plus a range of
qualities.
Interviews will be held shortly before the appointment is made on January 17.
The key focus is the 1998 Commonwealth Games, and the successful applicant must
sign a contract with SAF, detailing how either party can terminate the
arrangement.
They must manage all aspects of preparation and finance, liase with the
national and other coaches, and attend a wide range of meetings, including
courses in management skills. The arrogance of some team managers who believed
attendance at these was unnecessary was remarked on in the report following
last year's Commonwealth event.
q A SCOTTISH University Select team will compete in the Barrs Edinburgh to
Glasgow relay on Sunday, the first time such a team has been included in the
eight-stage event. Greenock Glenpark and Irvine are the final teams invited to
complete the line-up, which was reduced to 21 teams following the withdrawal
yesterday of North District Select, victims of the number of veterans in their
line-up who have opted for a Home Countries match in Dublin on Saturday.
q ORGANISERS of the Ronnie Kane Memorial meeting wish to stress that Sunday's
event at King's Park, incorporating a women's league match, is female-only.
DOUG GILLON
</TEXT>
</DOC>
