<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Students are in capital form Edinburgh University 36, St Andrews University 0</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN lorimer</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>38</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975355985</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EDINBURGH recaptured the Scottish Universities title they last won three
seasons ago with victory in the final at Stirling yesterday, confirming also
that they have the skilful players to survive in the national league division
one, writes Alan Lorimer.
Andy Lucking dominated the lineout and the experienced back row recycled
quality second-phase possession and linked well with the backs. Edinburgh's
five tries were the result of a positive attitude to take the game to St
Andrews with the ball in hand.
Full back Richard Bailes set the tone with a long-range try and Rob Henley
rounded off a splendid passage of continuity rugby with a try converted by
centre James How.
With the wind, they extended their lead with a penalty by How, who converted a
fine try under the posts by centre Mark Mansour from a scissors move, and
further touchdowns by stand-off Piers McWhannel and Mansour.
Edinburgh - R Bailes; K Brennan, M Mansour, J How, captain, P Haslett; P
McWhannel, H Williams; T Cohn, S Roberts, W Mulhall, J Harte, A Lucking, S
Cadzow, R Henley, D Watt.
St Andrews - C Kerin; C Wakefield, P Ainsworth, J Acton, M von Hapsburg; A
Armstrong, M Rennie; D Primrose, N McLaren, captain, A Ravenscroft, N Christie,
P Anderson, M Pickles, P Sanderson, B Crosse.
Referee - N Flower (Strathclyde Police).
q SCOTT Welsh's ankle injury has forced him to withdraw from the South team to
play against Griqualand West at Netherdale tonight.
The selectors have replaced the Hawick stand-off by switching Selkirk's Scott
Nichol to fly-half and calling in Melrose's Jimmy Turnbull at centre.
Turnbull's place among the replacements has yet to be filled. Kick-off is at
7.15.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
