<DOCNO>GH951116-000008</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000008</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Challenge on defence considered</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE McKAIN Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975355986</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SPECIAL Bench of five judges will take time to consider whether a defence
lawyer's incompetence can provide a basis for challenging a conviction under
Scots law.
James Anderson, 43, was jailed for three years and nine months at the High
Court in Glasgow in February last year after being convicted of assault to
severe injury and permanent disfigurement.
He alleges that he suffered a miscarriage of justice because of the
inadequacies of the solicitor advocate who represented him at his trial.
Anderson will have to persuade the court to disapprove of a previous decision
by three judges in 1949 that lack of skill or diligence in the preparation or
conduct of a defence cannot be a ground for claiming a miscarriage of justice.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000009</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000009</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Coach in `cheating' row backed by club Sole not alone as SRU launch inquiry</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS Chief rugby writer</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>38</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975355987</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EDINBURGH Academicals yesterday underlined their ``absolute confidence'' in
coach David Sole, following the SRU's decision to conduct an investigation into
the former Scotland captain's remarks after their Premiership clash with
Melrose on Saturday.
Academicals were plunged deeper into relegation trouble after an injury-time
try by Melrose scrum half Bryan Redpath following a string of nine penalties
awarded by referee Colin Henderson.
Immediately afterwards, Sole declared that the referee's performance had been
``tantamount to cheating,'' and even 24 hours later the 1990 Grand Slam captain
considered that his side had been ``cheated of victory.''
On Monday, the SRU announced that they were conducting an inquiry. Chief
executive Bill Hogg said that he had written to the Academicals seeking an
explanation, adding that Sole's reported remarks were ``totally unacceptable.''
Hogg added that if action is taken against the former Scotland captain then it
would be under the catch-all term, ``bringing the game into disrepute.''
Yesterday, Academicals' spokesman, Edinburgh solicitor Magnus Moodie, declared
that the club's executive committee had met on Tuesday night and had considered
media reports that a letter would be arriving from the SRU. He said: ``Accies
will respectfully consider the letter when it arrives and, having given it due
consideration, will reply privately.
``The executive committee unanimously recorded their continuing absolute
confidence in David Sole as coach, and noted that they saw no reason why that
confidence should be diminished in future.''
Yesterday, Sole preferred to remain silent on the Henderson affair, and was
content to let matters take their course. However, with the backing of his
club, his hand has been strengthened in the event of a showdown with the SRU.
q THE SRU is now, apparently, denying that it is imposing a 72-hour media
silence on international players before and after Test match appearances. The
basis of the denial, reported in some newspapers yesterday, is the fact that
the media will have access to players at the open training session tomorrow
morning and immediately after the game against Western Samoa on Saturday.
This scenario, which indicates a partial return to the status quo, is at
variance with what The Herald, correctly, reported on Tuesday when SRU
marketing manager Laura Dick declared: ``The situation is that a player may not
speak to the media, without our permission, during the 72 hours before and
after a game.''
The conflict within Murrayfield as to what was indeed intended indicates that
wires have become crossed somewhere along the line, which is particularly
unfortunate as the SRU moves into a new era with a public relations company
hired last week to refresh its PR profile.
Yesterday, director of rugby Jim Telfer said that under the terms of the
players' contract - which still remain unsigned - he was keen that players
focused on the game and not be distracted by the media and, in particular, he
was concerned about players who were contracted to write newspaper columns.
``I'm not happy with players writing columns at all and I don't want that to be
part of the scene in the future,'' said Telfer. ``I don't want us to get to the
stage that exists in England, where the likes of Rob Andrew and Brian Moore
have criticised referees, the opposition and, in some cases, team-mates.''
Currently, Craig Chalmers, Rob Wainwright and The Herald's Kenny Logan, are
contracted newspaper columnists. Telfer said that the position of players who
wrote columns would be looked at again at the end of the season but, in the
meantime, he would be happier if columns did not appear on the Saturday of an
international match.
By mutual consent, and even though it contravenes the 72-hour post-match media
ban, Logan's column will appear on Monday, when he will deliver his big match
verdict.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000010</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000010</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>NO HEADING PRESENT</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Magaret Vaughan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975355988</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHAT more could they have done? Leah Betts wasn't a wee keelie left to run
wild. Nor was she a desolate scrap blotting out misery with the aid of
adulterated chemicals. She was just having fun.
Her parents spoke calmly with their four daughters about the dangers of drug
abuse. Paul Betts knew them from first-hand experience as a former drugs squad
officer. Jan Betts, a nurse, advised schools on drug abuse.
They were not unduly heavy nor cringingly liberal. On the night of her 18th
birthday party, when Leah swallowed the ecstasy tablet that left her comatose,
they were in the next room.
They were just ordinary parents who, like most of us, try to do their best in
the hope we can be good enough. And it's that I suspect which has had more
impact, even, than the terrible sight of Leah, hooked up to the tubes and wires
and tapes that keep her hovering this side of death.
Usually when we read reports of hard drugs claiming lives we can tolerate it
because it happens to someone who is other; we can dismiss it, maybe
compassionately, more often now resignedly, as another in the deadly toll of
life in the underclass. Who identifies with the image of someone else's son or
daughter huddled in a tenement stairhead, life snuffed out by an overdose?
Here, though, it happened to the Betts, an ordinary family, living ordinary
lives. Is that why the reaction to one more victim of the drugs culture is so
extraordinary?
Part of me questions the ethics of what has become the ritual of parading
profoundly distressed relatives for the cameras, even when they agree to do it.
The usual nebulous justification from police is that it is done to help solve
crimes through emotional pressure on the perpetrators or those who shield them.
In this case, though, another part of me, a small, frightened part, accepts
that the sense of unease in watching the Betts had more to do with thoughts
about the fragility of life, and the knowledge that one small banal act is all
that stands between my family and your family and what has befallen the Betts.
Ecstasy is an established part of the youth culture of this country. Somewhere
around one million tablets are swallowed every week. Leah bought one for #10 on
her way home from a Saturday job.
It is cheap to mass produce and the raw materials are readily available. So is
the market. Leah's friends who were with her when she collapsed blowing out the
candles on her birthday cake have said it was a birthday party, not a drugs
party.
The difficulty with the message that Leah Bett's fate gives is that while it
may strike fear into the heart of every ordinary parent, it's not clear that it
will do any such thing among those who pop it. For those who use chemicals for
pleasure, one pill does not constitute a drugs binge.
There is an old advertising adage which says that you have to win the
credibility of the people you want to influence. Parading the dangers may shock
but ultimately it does not deter. To be taken seriously any message about the
dangers has to tell the truth. Even if that means telling uncomfortable truths.
There is no point, then, in denying that young people get pleasure from the
drugs. It will be felt as an insult to the intelligence to deny that stark
fact. Ecstasy does not cause death because it's mixed with dog-worming tablets
or baking soda. In some individuals it triggers a serious allergic reaction.
Others are hypersensitive so that a dose is like an overdose. No-one knows when
they take the first tablet how they will react.
Others who take it may not know that allergic reactions can occur without
warning. Others will die from more preventable effects, such as overheating and
dehydration. Many of the 50 young people who have died after taking ecstasy
were, literally, burned out.
Joseph Conrad came near the truth when he wrote that youth was a time when he
felt he could last forever, outlast the sea, the earth, and all men; the
deceitful feeling that lures us on to perils. If we're to have any hope of
helping them avoid the perils we have to make sure the clamour of our own fears
doesn't swamp the messages they hear.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
