<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Campaigning budget expected from Clarke Will the Budget put business on hold? Gary McFetridge, senior tax manager at KPMG in Glasgow, looks at the odds</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Gary McFetridge</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<FLAG>inside line</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975355989</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TRYING to second guess the Chancellor, Kenneth Clarke, is difficult at the best
of times. Trying to do so as he puts the final touches to what is likely to be
the last truly effective Budget before a General Election is doubly difficult.
On a personal level we may expect adjustments to tax allowances and thresholds
but Mr Clarke may well go for broke with a 1p reduction on the basic rate, to
be financed by expenditure cuts, other tax increases or a combination of both.
We will know for sure on November 28.
That said, what is he likely to do for business? Or can business expect to take
second place in a budget designed for the hustings?
Small and medium-sized businesses now play a pre-eminent role in economic
growth and job creation. Various measures have been introduced to encourage
investment in smaller companies, including venture capital trusts, the
enterprise investment scheme and capital gains tax reinvestment relief. We
should expect this theme to continue.
Deregulation is another area under scrutiny. Proportionately it places a much
greater burden on smaller companies. Some progress has been made in aligning
the rules on PAYE and National Insurance. This is welcome and should continue.
We have also seen measures to simplify VAT for smaller companies. Again, more
of this can be expected.
Small businesses would also benefit from measures to assist the financing of
investment from their own earnings. One possibility would be to give 100%
first-year allowances to the first tranche of annual expenditure on plant, say,
up to #200,000 per annum.
A reduction in the 33% standard rate of corporation tax would help the UK
competitively in the international markets but is unlikely. There have been
calls for a reduction in the 25% rate for small companies. But any reduction is
likely to be linked to the basic rate of income tax as the two are normally
kept in line.
There has been lobbying for fiscal incentives to boost innovation. However the
Government's view is that research and development is already assisted through
the tax system. One suggested change is to allow a scheme for R&amp;D tax losses to
be surrendered to the Treasury for payment. The Government appears set against
other incentives but there is a weight of opinion in favour and a change of
mind is possible.
The 10.2% rate of employers' National Insurance contributions is likely to be
reduced. The Chancellor has already promised that the proceeds of the new
landfill tax will be used to reduce employers' NIC.
There is speculation that benefits in kind will be brought within the NIC net.
Most at present are free of NIC and this change would make the regime
completely neutral between salary and benefits and further align the tax and
NIC rules.
However, this would place a considerable financial and compliance burden on
business and Mr Clarke will have to weigh this against the perceived benefits.
A 1% increase in the 17.5% rate of VAT would raise a substantial amount towards
other tax cuts but is likely to prove very unpopular. A widening of the VAT
base to the likes of passenger transport, books, newspapers and children's
clothing is also unlikely. The #46,000 VAT threshold is likely to be raised by
an inflationary factor.
Other technical VAT changes are likely, most notably further amendment to the
anti-avoidance provisions concerning the option to tax property transactions.
Changes introduced last year missed the mark and many innocent transactions
have been caught, particularly lease and leaseback transactions.
Further amendments are likely.
The 2.5% Insurance Premium introduced last year has yielded less than forecast
so an increase is likely. Variable rates are a possibility for different types
of insurance.
An increase in the air passenger duty introduced last year is also possible
with #2 going on the #5 charge on flights to Europe and #5 on the #10 charge on
flights elsewhere overseas.
The introduction of a landfill tax from October 1 has already been announced.
The rates should be announced in the Budget, possibly around #6-#8 a tonne and
#2-#3 for inert waste.
We can confidently expect an increase in road and fuel duties by 5% more than
inflation. This will add to the transport costs for Scottish businesses
shipping goods to markets in Europe and beyond.
In 1994 the Inland Revenue issued proposals to give formal rulings on the tax
treatment of transactions after they occurred. This will enable taxpayers to
obtain comfort on the tax treatment of transactions they have undertaken and
this is seen as an essential element of the new self-assessment regime.
It is therefore likely to be implemented.
Proposals have also been made to extend this to pre transactions rulings -
meaning before the event - for a fee. At present statutory clearance procedures
are available in advance of undertaking certain transactions but in specific
areas. This proposal would widen that process.
Finally, share options. On July 17, Mr Clarke took swift action to withdraw
income tax reliefs on approved share options granted to directors and employees
following publication of the Greenbury Report. His action was more hasty than
swift and he later amended this so that reliefs continued to be available where
the options existed on July 17.
However, this still overlooked the fact that the change had the greatest impact
on lower-paid employees with share options who will not be able to shelter
gains against their annual capital gains tax exemption. For senior employees
with large options this is much less of an issue.
Further changes to the detail of the legislation are likely in the Budget. But
it remains to be seen whether the Chancellor will have a third go at the
fundamental issue, possibly by allowing income tax reliefs to continue but on
much lower amounts of options.
Overall the Budget will probably be primarily aimed at the man in the street.
However, the measures aimed at business will also be closely scrutinised on
November 28.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
