<HEADLINE>Dawson's recovery dampenedV</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Andrew Wilsonm</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Table</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975355991</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE unseasonal mild weather has severely damaged recovery
plans at textiles group Dawson International, writes ANDREW WILSON.
Chairman Derek Finlay yesterday warned that profits for the second half of the
year are unlikely to match those of the first six months.
Those showed a decline from #15.8m to #8.4m, or #9m after a reserve clawback,
the City has interpreted that as pointing to a full-year figure of perhaps
#14m. That contrasts with last year's #28.4m after adding back exceptional
costs, but the interim dividend has been held at 1.5p. However, the 3p total is
in no danger.  Dawson shares tumbled 8p to 111p at one point before recovering
to lose 5!sp at  113!sp where they yield 3.4%. There were profit declines in
all divisions with the high profile Pringle in  loss, dragging the UK apparel
operations into a #4.2m shortfall.
Dawson is now paying the price for having too wide a range of Pringle products,
the lack of a cold autumn has devastated demand for knitwear, retailers
remaining fully stocked.  The problem is being addressed by Dawson unexpectedly
selling its surplus into  Poland, Russia, Australia and South America at low
margins to help establish a
more solid pricing base by winter 1996.
A decision has been taken to stop pricing unbranded knitwear although that will
reduce overall volume from the Hawick operations by a third. Altogether the UK
workforce has dropped by 850 to leave a base of about 4500.
Cashmere products encountered very severe resistance to an attempted 25%
increase in retail prices which were required to meet the doubling in wool
costs in 1993 and 1994. That resulted in reduced profitability in the fibres
and yarns division.
The current six months will see a charge of perhaps #6m as surplus stock is
sold off at the Morgan thermal clothing subsidiary in the US. That too has been
hit by the warm autumn but Morgan will benefit from a new distribution centre
and advanced cutting methods. One bonus is that it has about #70m of tax losses
to carry forward which will hold the overall Dawson tax level well below
standard rates for the forseeable future.
There are no liquidity problems, with year-end gearing likely to decline
slightly to about 20%.
Mr Finlay, who was appointed chairman in March, emphasised that it would
probably take two years for Dawson to fully recover but the groundwork and
reorganisation has been put in place.
