<HEADLINE>Diehard remains a fan</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>39</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975355992</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FEW football teams can claim fans as diehard as Spain's Betis, which boasts a
late club member whose son has remained faithful to the man's final wishes and
takes his ashes to each game - in a used milk carton.
And although the man died last year, the son has also renewed his father's club
membership for this season, which entitles the milk carton containing the ashes
to a seat in the Benito Villamarin stadium, club director Jose Antonio Gonzalez
Flores said.
But not all has been a bed of roses for the dead man - whose identity and that
of the son have not been divulged.
According to the El Mundo newspaper, although the son had no problem renewing
the dead man's membership, he initially tried to take the ashes to games in a
glass container.
After several weeks, however, he was stopped by security officials who claimed
the container constituted a dangerous object and as such was prohibited.
It was then the son got the idea of placing the ashes in a one-litre, used milk
carton, a decision which met with the approval of security officials.
q REAL Madrid chairman Ramon Mendoza has made good recent threats and announced
he will resign next Monday after more than 11 years at the helm - but the
Spanish champions look no closer to ending their crisis.
The club have struggled to overcome a chronic deficit and Mendoza's troubles
came to a head when shareholders rejected the financial accounts last month.
``This board of directors is incapable of throwing me out,'' he said. ``I'm
leaving because I want to ... and because I think it is best for the running of
the club.''
There was no indication that Mendoza's departure might jeopardise Argentine
coach Jorge Valdano's future.
</TEXT>
