<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>McCoist has final ambitions</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES TRAYNOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>40</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975355994</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE pretenders, Eoin Jess and Scott Booth, both scored last night as Scotland
celebrated their qualification for the European Championship finals next
summer, but the old fellow, Ally McCoist, also found the net and later said he
was determined to be around for the big show.
Scotland's manager, Craig Brown, who is entitled to bask in a warming glow of
satisfaction, will not let up between now and the finals. His players, mostly
journeymen, have done him and the nation proud, but they now face a major test
of their ambitions.
``I think we have a job on our hands to get beyond the first stage in the
finals,'' said Brown. ``However, it was important that we qualified, because to
have failed to reach the finals of the World Cup and the European Championship
would have been bad for us all.''
Brown will not be satisfied until he knows his best striking formation. Booth
and Jess will be there at the final reckoning. So, too, might Duncan Ferguson,
but McCoist should not be discounted. ``I know the competition will be fierce,
but I would love the chance to be involved,'' he said.
One of the success of the evening was Scot Gemmill. Watched by his father,
former Scottish internationalist Archie, Gemmill Jr applied some subtle touches
in midfield and also drove forward with style.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
