<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>SWIMMING Florida doesn't interest Walker</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELSPETH BURNSIDE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>39</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975355996</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SWIMMING
COMMONWEALTH Games medallist Fraser Walker, dropped from the Scottish team in
the summer, has ignored the welcome back sign by turning down an invitation to
a two-week training camp in Fort Lauderdale in Florida in February.
The 22-year-old confirmed the selectors' folly when he won the 200 metres
medley at the British National Championships in July, and he further proved
that he is one of our few Olympic prospects with two medals and a Scottish
record at last weekend's Cumbernauld Meet.
But his rejection of a return to the fold is not so much a fit of pique, but
rather a reasoned assessment that the weeks before the Olympic Games trials in
Sheffield in March would be better spent in familiar surroundings.
``We went to Lanzarotte on a Scottish training camp at the start of this year
and a few of us picked up an infection,'' he explained.
``Risking illness at that time next year is just too big a risk. Anyway, I'd
rather take the money.''
Walker, who is training in Warrington, was pleased with his 400 metre medley
victory, and a close second to British team rival James Hickman in the 200m at
Cumbernauld, and reckons he is on course for the Olympics in Atlanta next
summer.
``But I'm certainly not complacent,'' he added.
``There are another four months of tough training to be put in before the
trials.''
Scotland's European Championship medallist Graeme Smith, who completed an
outstanding Cumbernauld Meet with a Scottish record in the 400m free-style,
will also be missing from the Fort Lauderdale camp.
He has opted out of the Scottish programme in recent years, and so did not
merit even an invitation.
However, the Stockport Metro 19-year-old will be heading to Florida at the end
of next month for a two-week training camp with his coach Dave Calleja.
ELSPETH BURNSIDE
</TEXT>
</DOC>
