<HEADLINE>Take-or-pay Deals hurts Britis Gas</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Table</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975355997</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FACT FILE
Nine months   1995             1994
Turnover  #5919m       #6378m
Net income   #155m  #269m
EPS              3.5p    6.2p
THE precipitous decline in British Gas's share of the industrial and
commercial
market came to a halt in the third quarter but the infamous ``take-or-pay''
contracts are starting to bite hard, writes CHRISTOPHER SIMS.
Current cost net losses rose from #222m to #274m in the quarter, which was
actually not as bad as feared. But the stock market was disappointed that no
progress had been made on renegotiating the take-or-pay deals.
These long-term arrangements oblige the group to pay for gas at fixed prices,
which are about double present levels, even if it is not needed. So far #83m
has been provided against the contracts and it expects to pay #520m in the
final quarter for supplies not required.
British Gas feels hard done by because half the deals were made before
privatisation and the oil companies needed these bedrock contracts to develop
gas fields. The prices were fixed at a time when British Gas thought it would
have a much longer domestic monopoly. The Government has since moved the
finish
date forward to 1998, with trials beginning next spring.
Because of all this, British Gas chief executive Cedric Brown is looking for
Government support when it comes to renegotiation.
The group said two months ago it wanted to renegotiate but nothing has
happened
yet and substantive talks are not expected before the New Year. The gas
producers are under no obligation to renegotiate and British Gas needs the
Government's support because it grants exploration licences.
Finance director Roy Gardner said: ``Once we get into detailed discussions and
negotiations with producers it may be necessary to seek the aid of the
Minister.''
Once British Gas was able to compete on equal terms to supply the industrial
and commercial market it maintained its share at 35%. While declining share
was
no longer a factor in the third quarter, warm weather was. Excluding this,
chairman Richard Giordano said underlying profitability was marginally ahead
over the first nine months of the year. Actual profits were an eighth lower.
With the mild weather continuing into the final quarter, Mr Giordano expects
full-year earnings before exceptionals to be down on 1994.
British Gas shares slipped 4!sp to 241!sp but the considerable uncertainties
are already discounted given the yield of 7.4% and the shares are coming on to
brokers' buy lists.
</TEXT>
