<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Health scare stops work at factory for second day</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER REEKIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975355998</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Daks-Simpson plant at Polbeth, West Lothian, was closed for the second
successive day yesterday as health and safety officials continued to
investigate workers' complaints of feeling ill.
The workforce of 365, mainly women, had returned to work, but only for about an
hour, after having been sent home early on Tuesday when 12 people complained of
dizziness, nausea, and a rash.
Work resumed after a 7.30am meeting but after a later meeting, about half of
the employees left the premises.
The company decided it could not operate with a reduced workforce and all
employees were allowed to go home. They will return to work this morning.
Mr Kevin Johnson, Daks-Simpson managing director in Scotland, said no-one need
go back to work until they had been reassured by the medical team from the
company's sister plant at Larkhall, Lanarkshire.
The factory had been cleaned during Tuesday night and further cleaning and
testing would continue.
The incident at Polbeth came after the company's Larkhall plant was closed for
several days after 40 workers were taken to hospital complaining of
breathlessness and nausea. No reason has been found for the Larkhall outbreak.
The Polbeth plant makes up men's trousers from material handled by the 1700
workers at Larkhall.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000021</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000021</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Brown's bombers prove they're ready for a raid over the Border Jess right as Scots strikers show Hampden the high five</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER, CHIEF FOOTBALL WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>40</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975355999</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A GAME against San Marino would never have been the choice as the last fixture
for Scotland before the old South Stand at Hampden was torn down. And yet, the
fans who were there last night, all 30,306 of them, did see a Scottish team
score five goals, rack-up their fifth successive competitive victory and also
qualify finally for the European Championships in England next summer.
Indeed, the team did all that manager Craig Brown had hoped for.
Before the match, Brown had insisted that he wanted a performance from the
players which would convince the support that they would not be travelling to
the finals in England simply to make up the numbers. He got that.
He also wanted the players to deliver goals for the supporters who had come out
in numbers for the remaining matches, the vital games which had ensured
qualification. He got them.
Five of them, in fact - and two of these in the first half from the strike
force of Eoin Jess and Scott Booth, the men he had started the game with up
front.
Brown had moved Jess back to his original striking position, instead of the
role in which he has been employed by Aberdeen.
That paid off for him.
In fact, before the Pittodrie front player scored the opener after 30 minutes,
he had been close to snatching goals on three other occasions.
Yet, when the goal came, it was thought out, the kind of strike that Brown has
been trying to produce to his team's play.
Pat Nevin reached the byeline on the right, and with a classic cut-back, he
found Jess coming in on goal. The Aberdeen man went down as he shot, but he was
still able to steer the ball beyond the San Marino keeper and into the net.
Just before half-time, it was his Pittodrie partner Booth who struck for the
second goal.
This time, Scot Gemmill was the man who reached the byeline. He sent the ball
across goal, and there was Booth as Gemmill's cross came off the keeper. He
scored from close range, and by now the Scots' superiority had been turned into
the goals Brown had wanted.
Two minutes into the second half, Brown made his first change when skipper Gary
McAllister went off to be replaced by Ally McCoist.
Colin Hendry took over as skipper, and Jess dropped back to his club position
in midfield.
Within two minutes, McCoist had scored, coming on to one of his favourite
grounds and doing what he is so good at.
The Ibrox striker was at the far post to meet a deep cross from Pat Nevin and
headed into goal.
Following that, Billy McKinlay took over from an ineffective John Collins and
Darren Jackson took over from Scott Booth and the changes did not disturb the
fluency of Scotland's play.
In 71 minutes, a fourth goal arrived. A ball was played into the box, McCoist
moved it on, and when the goalkeeper fumbled the ball and sent it away from
goal, Nevin pounced to steer a shot beyond him and into the net.
Then, in the closing minute, a Nevin cross was turned past his own goalkeeper
by Fabio Fracini to complete the scoring.
Inevitably there will be those who point out that the five goals came against
San Marino. Equally, it must be remembered that no one can find it easy these
days to score goals against the minnows of European competitions.
Brown asked his players to entertain the fans, and they did so. He knows that
there are more severe tests to be faced next summer.
However, when you examine Scotland's qualifying record, there is a
professionalism about the performances which will not allow anyone to dismiss
their challenge easily.
Russia, who will be among the favourites to win the tournament, drew twice with
the Scots. The single defeat Brown's men suffered was against Greece in Athens
and that came from a penalty which was fiercely disputed at the time and became
even more controversial when the television re-runs were seen.
They won every other game.
Brown, of course, still seeks the striking partnership he wants up front, and
while Jess and Booth combined well in the first half, and helped themselves to
a goal apiece, he brought McCoist, and later, Darren Jackson, into play.
Before next summer, he will have other games - there is one against Denmark in
Copenhagen in March, and more will follow, and in that time, he must fashion a
strike force to threaten the stronger opposition Scotland will face in the
finals.
Last night, Scot Gemmill emerged as a potent force in midfield. Even though
Brown has stressed continually that the midfield area is his strongest, Gemmill
is now telling him that he deserves the opportunity to play in more important
games than this one.
There is no doubt he will be given that opportunity. He was outstanding against
San Marino, comfortable in possession, aggressive when necessary, and with
skills you could match with those of any other midfield player at Brown's
disposal.
