<HEADLINE>Justice served by final solution</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES McKILLOP</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975356000</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JUSTICE was served with the suicide in prison of Frederick West, and a jury
could acquit his wife Rosemary on 10 counts of murder with a clear conscience,
Winchester Crown Court was told yesterday.
Mr West's final solution had removed a great burden from the shoulders of the
jury, Mr Richard Ferguson QC, defending, declared in his final address.
Mrs West's acquittal would not mean that a series of killings had gone
unpunished and unresolved.
The families of the victims need not worry that these crimes had gone
unpunished, he told the depleted jury of seven men and four women.
The Crown, he said, had presented a case that relied totally on speculation,
conjecture, and prejudice.
However, while Mrs West might have been involved in sexual assaults and,
perhaps, might have been party to rape, that did not make her a murderess.
There was no evidence, he insisted, that Mrs West was linked with the deaths of
the young women and girls whose remains were recovered from 25 Cromwell Street
last year.
It was, he said, unfortunate that the Crown had continued to prosecute this
case against Mrs West after her husband hanged himself in his cell at Winson
Green Prison, Birmingham, on New Year's Day.
It had done so without a shred of evidence against the defendant.
There had been no eyewitnesses, no confession, nor fingerprint and forensic
evidence. There had been no corroboration to the prosecution allegations.
Without these pieces of evidence, the Crown, Mr Ferguson said, faced an uphill
struggle from the outset.
He urged the jury to ignore siren voices which had reached conclusions from
what was seen on television and read in newspapers.
The jurors alone had heard all of the evidence and they had taken an oath to
reach verdicts based only on the evidence.
He told them that, in doing so: ``You must come to the inevitable conclusion.
You must acquit.''
Mrs West denies murdering 10 girls and women, including her daughter Heather
and step-daughter Charmaine.
Mr Ferguson told members of the jury he was sure they would not allow any
feelings of shock, disgust, or revulsion to alter, in any way, their returned
verdicts.
It might never be known how any of these unfortunate girls met their deaths but
not a shred of reliable evidence had been produced in court to prove the
defendant was party to their killings.
``You are not being asked to acquit in the teeth of the evidence,'' Mr Ferguson
continued. ``You are being asked to acquit because there is no evidence.''
The jury had heard tapes of Frederick West in interviews with the police,
during which he exonerated his wife from any involvement in the killings.
If he told the truth during these taped conversations, then, said Mr Ferguson,
the jury must acquit. Even if it believed what he said might be the truth, then
it had to return verdicts of not guilty.
West, he declared, was a man devoid of compassion, was consumed by sexual lust,
and was a sadistic killer.
To suggest he would give up his life to protect Rosemary West was an insult to
intelligence, Mr Ferguson insisted.
When first arrested, West had insisted in taped interviews that Mrs West had
nothing to do with the killings.
It was only weeks later, on April 28, that he started to implicate her and many
others. He was preparing a defence whereby he was innocent and everyone else
was guilty, said Mr Ferguson.
The Crown had relied heavily on the evidence of Mrs Janet Leach, the woman
appointed as an ``appropriate adult'' for the interviews.
This was to support the prosecution claim that Mr West was covering up for
person or persons unnamed.
``She was meant to be the high water mark in the prosecution case,'' said Mr
Ferguson.
``She told lies to the police. She told lies to you in court.''
He asked the jury to consider whether, if West had not taken his life and was
standing trial, the Crown would be asking it to challenge his taped confessions.
``Surely not,'' Mr Ferguson continued. Nevertheless, the taped evidence had the
ring of truth.
It was eminently possible he killed those girls alone, without the consent and
participation of his wife.
The Crown contended: ``How could she not have noticed that there were blood
spots on his clothes? How could she not have known what was going on?''
West was a working man. He did not have to parade himself for inspection every
morning.
Witnesses had given evidence that they had been raped, sexually assaulted, and
stalked by West when acting alone.
On these occasions, Mrs West was not required to entice them into his car.
Had these girls been murdered and their remains uncovered 20 years later at 25
Cromwell Street, would the Crown be asking the jury to conclude Mrs West must
have been involved to entice them into his vehicle, Mr Ferguson asked.
Bindings were found with the remains of Ms Anne McFall, Scottish nanny of West
and his first wife Rena. At that stage, Mrs West was 13.
Prior to their marriage, West was capable of killing without her assistance.
If that was true, he was equally capable of murder without her help after their
wedding.
He told the jury he was confident that no form of puritanical censure would
adversely affect its judgment.
Mr Brian Leveson QC, for the prosecution, had been like a mountain guide
leading the jury to the summit, where the top of the mountain would mean
conviction.
Unfortunately, as he led them up the mountain path he came to a gap - a void,
said Mr Ferguson. He invited the jury to jump that void with him.
``Don't jump,'' Mr Ferguson advised.
``For you, as with all of us, this has been a demanding and at times harrowing
experience. The responsibility resting on your shoulders is immense.''
The trial judge will begin summing up to the jury today. It is expected to be
invited to retire to consider verdicts on Monday.
</TEXT>
