<TEXT>
Earnings slip at
Land Securities
BRITAIN'S biggest property group Land Securities experienced flat conditions in
the half-year to September with pre-tax profits emerging very slightly lower at
#118m on unchanged rental income of #198m. The interim dividend has been raised
3.6% to #7.1p.
LandSecs, which is also Scotland's largest private sector landlord, has now
embarked on phase two of the Almondvale Shopping Centre in Livingston as well
as refurbishing its office building in St Vincent Street, Glasgow.
Chief resigns
PETER Middleton has resigned as chief executive of Lloyd's of London to become
head of European operations of Salomon Brothers, the American securities house.
He will be succeeded by Ron Sandler, 43, who has been a key figure in the
Lloyd's reconstruction plan. Since May, Mr Sandler has been in charge of
implementing the plan. He joined the organisation last March as director,
special projects, having been chief executive of Exco, the moneybroker.
Enterprise boost
DUNBARTONSHIRE Enterprise has managed to promote #6.8m of new investment in the
area between Cumbernauld and Helensburgh over the last six months by putting in
just #50,000 of its own money. The new money poured into the local economy is
nearly three times more than its original target. It was shared by 11 companies
ranging from electronics firms to a packaging company and helped to create or
safeguard 312 jobs.
</TEXT>
