<HEADLINE>Malcolm still on hold CRICKETi</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>38</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356002</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ENGLAND are still keeping Devon Malcolm - and South Africa - guessing over
their first Test line-up.
The Derbyshire fast bowler has been named in the 13-man squad for today's
series opener at Centurion Park.
General opinion is Malcolm will be left out, with the tourists picking three
steadier pacemen - Angus Fraser, Dominic Cork, and Darren Gough - plus spinner
Richard Illingworth.
But England are clearly concerned about how the pitch will play and have also
included left-arm swing bowler Mark Ilott in the squad.
``We will keep a completely open mind until the morning,'' said manager Ray
Illingworth, who did, however, confirm England would play six specialist
batsmen.
Illingworth repeatedly drew attention to the fact the pitch was still being
watered less than 24 hours before start of play.
``I would have thought it was unusually late to be watering it,'' said the
manager. ``I presume the groundsman is a bit worried about it not lasting the
distance.
``I thought when I first saw it that it would definitely take spin. But it's up
to us to get the right team to play on whatever is prepared.''
Illingworth confirmed England would either go in with three pace bowlers plus a
spinner, or choose four quick men.
Meanwhile, South Africa seem to have made up their minds - and look set to
field an all-pace attack.
Their chairman of selectors, Peter Pollock, declared himself ``delighted'' with
the pitch, predicting it would have pace and bounce.
That almost certainly means Pollock's 22-year-old son Shaun will make his Test
debut, with left-arm spinner Clive Eksteen omitted.
But the real pre-match puzzle concerns Malcolm. England's fastest bowler
still believes he holds a psychological advantage over South Africa after his
nine for 57 against them at The Oval 15 months ago.
Now, with the pitch perhaps more suited to pace than spin, he could still get
his chance to repeat that demolition job.
England (from): Atherton, Stewart, Ramprakash, Thorpe, Hick, Smith, Russell,
Cork, Gough, Illingworth, Fraser, Malcolm, Ilott.
South Africa (from): Hudson, G Kirsten, Kronje, Cullinan, Rhodes, McMillan,
Richardson, Pollock, Matthews, Donald, Schultz, Eksteen.
NEW Zealand beat India by eight wickets in the first one-day international at
Jamshedpur yesterday.
Chasing India's total of 236 from 49.1 overs, New Zealand scored 237 for two
wickets in 47 overs. Scores:
India 236 (M Prabhakar 83, M Azharuddin 32, S Tendulkar 30); New Zealand 237
for two (M Crowe 107no, S Fleming 78no, M Greatbatch 31).
</TEXT>
