<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Little room for manoeuvre</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<FLAG>business comment</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975356003</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STERLING has been losing ground rapidly this month in response to mounting
speculation that an early cut in interest rates would be justified by the weak
state of the economy.
The dollar has been hit by the tussle for power in the US between the Democrat
President and Republican Congress over the federal budget, and this has rubbed
off on the pound.
But most of sterling's weakness reflects the increasing nervousness of the
foreign exchange markets that the Chancellor will go for broke, cutting taxes
in the Budget and subsequently pushing through a reduction in rates in
opposition to Bank of England advice.
Since the current upturn in inflationary pressures is in part a consequence of
the pound's fall from grace earlier in the year, Kenneth Clarke can hardly
afford to ignore the likely effect of his measures on sentiment in the foreign
exchange markets.
The latest cause for doubt about the so-called economic recovery was a poor set
of retail sales figures for last month. Widespread hopes of an increase in
sales volumes were not validated. Sales are no higher now than they were a year
ago.
There have been some signs of an upturn in consumer spending as the effects of
two years of fiscal stringency have begun to wear off, but retail sales remain
in the doldrums. Tax cuts, urged by the Retail Consortium, might help to
persuade people to dig a little deeper into their pockets, but they will not
show up in higher pay packets until April.
It is difficult to see how Mr Clarke could justify extensive reductions in tax
without frightening the City in general and the foreign exchange markets in
particular. His PSBR forecasts, already blown off course in the current year,
will be a crucial test for the markets.
Talk of a cut in rates without knowing the flavour of the Budget is premature.
One problem is that lower rates in the aftermath of a tax-cutting budget might
be damned by the markets.
Yet a cut in the New Year could coincide with a likely pick up in the economy.
At this stage it appears that Mr Clarke's room for manoeuvre on both fiscal and
monetary fronts is curtailed.
No recovery
GEORGE Wimpey's decision to follow Tarmac down the road of divesting parts of
the business in favour of focusing management effort and resources on just one
activity, could spark a bout of restructuring. Already BICC has tossed its
housing division into the ring.
The housing market has been in the doldrums for close to six years so it is not
surprising major players want to cut and run in the absence of any signs of
sustained recovery. Companies who have divested of their housing divisions will
be able to rebuild a business with more dependable earnings that is less
vulnerable to the abrupt swings of the housing market.
At the start of the year there were high hopes of a recovery in the housing
market coinciding with the upturn in the domestic economy. In the event,
economic growth has slowed down and with it has ebbed away any hope of a
recovery in either the new build or refurbishment housing market. There are
currently scant signs of revival with lower housing starts, falling prices and
fewer transactions.
At the end of September, total transactions were 9.1% lower than at the
equivalent time last year. The nadir for overall transactions was 1992, with
just 1.13 million. This year now looks as though it could produce a similarly
low figure.
Any hopes of special measures to boost the housing industry market in this
year's Budget are likely to be disappointed. The longer term prognosis for the
industry is good. Demographic trends towards an ageing population and increase
in the number of single households point to a need for greater housing volume.
Given the enlarged scale of its operations, Wimpey is better placed than many
of its rivals to capitalise on the eventual upturn in demand.
Lost appeal
THE long hot summer and what has so far been the mildest autumn for 25 years
were the last things Dawson International needed. The world seems awash with
cashmere jumpers and fairly drastic measures are being employed to clear
stocks, to try to establish a better market place for the 1996 winter season.
But there must be a question mark over cashmere's appeal as it is expensive in
the eyes of most customers. The price differential with top quality designer
woollen products such as those of John Smedley is probably not justified and
there is not the same fashion element - ``boring old cashmere'' was one comment
yesterday.
That apart, the new management team at Dawson does seem to know what it is
doing. It is reducing costs, improving work practices and continuing to clear
up past mistakes such as over-stocking in the US thermal business. It will cost
a significant amount, perhaps #6m, but it will give Dawson a better operation
in that territory for 1996.
Unfortunately, the downturn in demand and profits warning have postponed for
perhaps a couple of years any prospect of Dawson taking part in the necessary
restructuring of the UK textile industry. It has the balance sheet strength to
be a medium-sized player, but management simply is not available for anything
other than day-to-day operations.
Turning this on its head, no-one is likely to want to take over Dawson until
the Pringle problems are resolved, and these alone will take at least a year.
Altogether, it is not a happy picture. Investors and employees are still
bearing the pain caused by the indecision of the non-executive directors who
took far too long to change the previous top management. But all they can do is
grin and bear it until volume recovers.
</TEXT>
