<HEADLINE>Tourism welcomes film on Nessie, humps and all</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS HOLME</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356004</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EFFORTS will be made next year to promote tourism on the back, so to speak, of
one of its best and most elusive assets, the Loch Ness Monster.
Loch Ness, a film featuring Cheers star Ted Danson as a US scientist in search
of Nessie, is due for release in February.
Unfortunately, he first experiences a hideous parody of tartan kitsch, not
unlike the image portrayed by writer Jill Crawshaw in her recent Herald series:
appalling ceilidhs, tacky flashing lights, and a hotel keeper who rips him off.
Scottish Tourist Board officials who have been given a preview are taking it on
the chin. As the film progresses, Danson meets real people, and the abiding
impression is of positive endorsement of beautiful scenery, clean environment,
and friendly welcome.
They believe it will have even more international impact than Braveheart and
Rob Roy, which helped in the domestic tourism increase of 16% in the first six
months of this year.
Mr Graham Birse, STB director of public relations, said: ``It is a family film
in the traditional sense and has a charm all of its own. It will be a
significant boost for us in all markets, particularly the United States.''
q Danson is also shown as a man of taste and discernment: he is shown reading
The Herald over breakfast.
</TEXT>
