<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000027</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000027</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Els has yen for cheque with lots of noughts GOLFp</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>38</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356005</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ERNIE Els, the former US Open champion and double World Matchplay champion,
rarely deals in just four figures these days, but on his last outing, a skins
game in Taipei, he won a mere $6000, hardly even small change for the engaging
South African.
His globetrotting has now led him to Miyazaki in southern Japan, where he has a
yen to resume normal service in the Dunlop Phoenix tournament, which starts
today, and win one of those familiar cheques with lots of noughts on the end -
36,000,000 is the number of yen the winner will receive, about #1.3m.
Els, who won the title in 1993, looked a little flabby, despite a schedule that
has taken him from Wentworth to St Andrews to Tulsa to Atlanta to the Far East
in consecutive weeks.
Colin Montgomerie was to play here for the first time but his overworked left
wrist gave out at the Visa Taiheiyo Masters last week, and after opening the
odd supermarket in Tokyo, he flew home to give it a rest. Jose Maria Olazabal
and Ian Woosnam also are absent injured, but Philip Walton and Costantino
Rocca, two of the season's heroes, are here, along with Englishman Barry Lane
and Miguel Angel Jimenez, of Spain.
There are also a host of big-name Americans, all former major champions: Tom
Watson, Larry Nelson, Larry Mize, Craig Stadler, Scott Simpson, and Jeff Sluman.
Watson came tantalisingly close to beating Jumbo Ozaki last year - the Japanese
won the title by a shot - and it was, of course, on the greens that the
American failed.
</TEXT>
