<HEADLINE>Scargill hauled over coals for oil union advances</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS Industrial Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356006</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MINERS' president Arthur Scargill was reproached yesterday by leaders of
several of the main TUC unions for seeking to absorb the breakaway OILC North
Sea union into the National Union of Mineworkers.
He was summoned to Congress House where he was confronted by general secretary
John Monks and six North Sea unions.
These were the Amalgamated Engineering and Electrical Union; the General,
Municipal, and Boilermakers; the Manufacturing, Science, and Finance; the Rail,
Maritime, and Transport; the ships' officers' union, Numast, and the Transport
and General Workers'.
They left him in no doubt that they considered the North Sea as being their
sphere of influence.
After the two-hour meeting, Mr Monks wrote to Mr Scargill summarising how the
North Sea unions had reiterated their position that they regarded the OILC as a
breakaway organisation and therefore were totally opposed to any transfer of
engagements by the OILC to the NUM.
Unless the NUM agrees to abandon its proposed move into the North Sea sector it
could find itself the subject of a TUC disputes committee investigation and
ultimately, if it refused to abide by that committee's ruling, it could be
expelled from the TUC.
Mr Ronnie McDonald, OILC general secretary, who was not at yesterday's meeting,
told The Herald his organisation was still keen to link up with the NUM and/or
the Norwegian offshore oil industry union, OFS, possibly under the aegis of the
Paris-based International Energy and Mineworkers Organisation (president one
Arthur Scargill).
The OILC, which claims to have around 1800 members, was set up in the wake of
the 1988 Piper Alpha disaster.
The current row surfaced in June, when Mr Scargill announced that his union was
disposed to accept an OILC offer to transfer engagements to the NUM.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000029</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000029</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>CHANGING FORTUNES OF PARIS PARK</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Nicola REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356007</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Disneyland Paris theme park has finally become profitable, due in no small
part to the 1.1 million British visitors who have travelled there in the last
12 months.
n  The #4600m park opened on a 170-acre site near Paris in April 1992.
n More than 2000 British workers helped construct the site, with some earning
as much as #30 an hour.
n Despite welcoming two million UK visitors in the opening summer season, the
park lost more than #600m in its first year.
n First-year attendances were more than 10 million and about 9.5 million in the
second year - some one million fewer than Disney had predicted.
n People spent far less than the hoped #46 a head.
n The park has more than 40 attractions including Space Mountain, opened in
June.
n It has 5200 hotel beds and 600 self-catering rooms.
n In the winter of 1993, Euro Disney and its 60 banks began rescue talks that
culminated in a #725m rights issue in June 1994.
n Saudi prince Al-Waleed bin Talal agreed to pump about #300m into the project
as part of this restructuring.
n 1994 also saw the park change its name to Disneyland Paris.
n The new-look attraction cut entry prices by 20% and trimmed its workforce by
5000 to 12,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
