<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>OIL AND GAS Pentex agrees Melrose offer</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT POWELL ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356009</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ABERDEEN-based oil company Pentex has agreed to a #31.2m takeover by Melrose
Energy, which has oil and gas assets in the United States.
The Melrose offer values Pentex at 156p per share, 30% more than its Tuesday
closing price of 120p, and provides for senior Pentex executives to take charge
of running the enlarged group.
London-based Melrose is offering 81 new Melrose shares for 20 Pentex shares in
a deal which will give Pentex shareholders a 29.5% stake in Melrose.
It has sweetened the offer by promising a 50% increase in the full-year
dividend for the current financial year to at least 0.72p.
Pentex chairman Henry Cameron will become chief executive of Melrose and Pentex
managing director George Lane will become managing director of the enlarged
group.
Robert Adair, a geologist and chartered accountant who currently owns 60% of
Melrose, will step down as chief executive to become finance director and
deputy chairman instead. His stake will fall to 40% after the merger
Melrose, which merged with Crossroads Oil in March, is developing oil and gas
fields in Texas, New Mexico and Wyoming in partnership with other investors. It
made a pre-tax profit of #5.3m in the year to June 30.
However, it has only half a dozen employees and works exclusively through
sub-contractors.
Pentex on the other hand is a small hands-on oil company with 67 employees
which produces more than 6000 barrels of oil per day from two fields in the
North Sea.
It also produces about 500 barrels per day of oil equivalent of gas onshore in
the English Midlands. Some of this is used to generate electricity on behalf of
Yorkshire Electricity.
Pentex made a pre-tax profit of #3.3m in the year to December 31 1994.
The Aberdeen-based company was floated on the stock exchange in January with
the aim of eventually issuing new shares to fund an acquisition. But it has
unexpectedly dropped the role of hunter to become prey instead.
Mr Cameron, a 55-year-old Aberdeen lawyer who has headed Pentex since 1988,
said his firm received several takeover proposals.
But Melrose, with which Pentex has been talking since August, offered the best
price and the best guarantees of continued activity, he said.
Pentex shares closed up 20p at 140p.
Melrose, which is launching a one-for-five #13.2m rights issue to raise working
capital for the enlarged group, closed down !sp at 38p.
Mr Adair said the merger would give Melrose ``a more broadly based income
stream'' and ``a highly experienced and innovative oil and gas management
team.''
But he gave notice that Melrose remained on the acquisition trail with up to
#30m of cash available to spend on a new purchase within the next six to 12
months.
The Melrose offer will be put to an extraordinary meeting of Pentex
shareholders on December 11.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000032</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000032</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Campaigners picket petrol station</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356010</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN Edinburgh petrol station became a target of the international protest
against Shell when campaigners picketed customers and urged them to boycott the
brand.
Around 20 campaigners, including Edinburgh University students and Greenpeace
and Friends of the Earth supporters, took part in the demonstration in the
forecourt of the Causewayside filling station, which has been selling Shell
petrol for only a few months.
They handed motorists leaflets highlighting the executions of Mr Saro-Wiwa and
other activists and calling on Shell to withdraw from Nigeria. They urged
customers to write or phone Shell ``to let them know you are outraged''.
Mr Ian Standing, managing director of Kennet, the company which owns the petrol
station, responded by giving the protesters leaflets, distributed by Shell,
which describe claims that Shell has been responsible for ``environmental
devastation'' in Nigeria as ``false and misleading''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000033</DOCNO>
