<TEXT>
MANCHESTER United must defend a second charge of poaching schoolboys after the
Football Association yesterday acted on complaints from Oldham over Old
Trafford's recruitment of 16-year-old David Brown.
They have charged United in respect of an alleged illegal approach to the
teenager while he was registered as an associate schoolboy with their
neighbours.
Alex Ferguson's side, whose youth culture makes them the envy of the
Premiership, already face a similar charge after Arsenal claimed they enticed
away Matthew Wicks.
The son of former Chelsea defender Steve Wicks is already an England Under-18
player.
If United are found guilty they will face a hefty fine, probably in five
figures although nowhere near the #750,000 suggested in some quarters. They
could also be ordered to pay Oldham and Arsenal compensation.
Yesterday's charge follows several months of inquiries. United have been asked
to make a written response within 14 days and can request a personal hearing.
The FA believe United may have broken both Premier and Football League rules.
</TEXT>
