<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Governor sticks to wait-and-see policy</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356012</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BANK of England Governor Eddie George advised the Chancellor of the Exchequer,
Kenneth Clarke, to adopt a wait-and-see attitude to interest rates at a meeting
between the two men at the end of September, the first time he had not
recommended an increase since April.
Minutes of the September 29 meeting, published yesterday, showed Mr George
repeated his view that the Government was likely to miss its inflation target.
``The Bank's advice was to wait until the position became clearer before making
any policy move,'' the minutes said.
Mr George noted encouraging signs that factory input and output prices were
rising more slowly but did not think the evidence was ``wholly reliable''.
He was also uncertain about the slowdown in activity, predicting that it would
pick up modestly in the months ahead.
Mr Clarke said slower manufacturing output and retail sales growth ``had
increased the probability'' that the inflation target - which aims to deliver
an underlying rate of 2.5% or less in two years - would be met and was not
``unduly concerned'' about the pick-up in August's rise in the retail prices
index.
It could be explained by the effect of the exceptionally hot weather on
seasonal food prices.
Mr Clarke said the main cause for concern about the inflation outlook was the
strength of M4, the broad measure of the money supply, but added that it had
behaved in an unpredictable manner in recent years.
``He agreed with the Governor's recommendation that interest rates should
remain unchanged this month,'' said the minutes.
</TEXT>
