<HEADLINE>INSURANCE CU sees rise in premiums</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Table</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975356013</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COMMERCIAL Union yesterday echoed General Accident's contention on Tuesday that
motor insurance premiums, which usually lead general insurance rates, are
likely to rise, writes CHRISTOPHER SIMS.
Currently they are at a low ebb after two years of weakness and finance
director Peter Foster commented: ``I think the next move is probably going to
be in an upward direction, but whether that occurs in the fourth quarter or the
beginning of next year remains to be seen.''
Third quarter profits of CU dipped only marginally from #131m to #137m, a
performance which put 16p on the shares at 614p. The nine months' total came to
#381m against #327m.
In the UK, profits were 14% lower at #74m which compares favourably with the
other insurers who have reported. In common with others, subsidence claims were
up to a total #16m. The London market operations cut losses from #39m to #15m,
reflecting improved claims experience and premium rises.
CU says that its Groupe Victoire acquisition in France continues to bed down
well. The first stage of integration is essentially complete though no major
cost savings have yet been achieved - mass sackings are just not done in the
country. France is now the largest territory, accounting for almost a third of
total premiums, against the UK's 26%.
The purchase swelled life profits to #164m from #95m, though the UK was down
11% at #32m as new annual premiums sank 26%.
CU's Dutch subsidiary, Delta Lloyd, is looking up, with profits ahead #30m at
#83m as reorganisation in recent years paid off. US profits were slightly ahead
at #38m. New disclosure rules mean that insurers will have to itemise
provisions for asbestosis and environmental pollution exposures.
CU's year-end provisions are expected to be $130m for the former and $500m for
the latter, though net annual claims have averaged $16m and $30m respectively
over the past three years.
