<HEADLINE>#14,700 for loss of privacy</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975356014</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A COUPLE who claimed the privacy of their dream home was wrecked when someone
built a house next door won #14,700 damages yesterday from the previous owner.
A sheriff ruled that Mrs Lesley Jenkins, 35, was in breach of contract because
she failed to tell Mr James Mackie, 59, and his wife Jean, 54, that planning
permission had been sought for developing land 80 yards from the back door of
the secluded Hayhill in Bardowie, north of Glasgow.
The couple bought the house - a unique, architect-designed country bungalow -
for #285,000 in preparation for their retirement.
They claimed the privacy was ruined because their new neighbours could see
every move that they made - both inside and outside the house.
Dumbarton Sheriff Frederick Levine judged that Mrs Jenkins knew about planning
permission for the other building - but had failed to tell the Mackies before
the sale was concluded.
Mr and Mrs Mackie were hoping for almost #30,000 in damages, claiming this was
the amount by which the property was devalued by the loss of privacy.
However, in his written judgment, the sheriff set the figure at half this
amount - and criticised Mrs Jenkins' part in the transaction.
Sheriff Levine said Mrs Jenkins had been properly notified more than once about
planning permission being sought for the building of a house in the field next
door.
He added: ``She knew . . . (this was) likely to affect the privacy and value of
Hayhill.''
He then quoted a clause from the ``offer'' letter sent from the Mackies'
solicitor to Mrs Jenkins. It read: ``The seller is not aware of any proposals
by neighbouring proprietors or others which might affect the privacy of the
subjects.''
The judgment continued: ``Mrs Jenkins accepted these conditions of the contract
without comment. She did not disclose the information she was required to under
its terms.''
The sheriff concluded: ``The Mackies have lost amenity of privacy both inside
and outside Hayhill.''
The sheriff set the total damages at #14,700 - consisting of #13,000 for a loss
of property value, and #1700 for inconvenience while the other house was being
built and for a kitchen door which was damaged before the Mackies moved in.
Mrs Mackie, 54, said later: ``Oh is that all we're getting. I can't say any
more. You'll have to ask my husband.''
Mr Mackie, 59, was at work and unavailable for comment - as was mum-of-two Mrs
Jenkins, 35, who now lives at Craigmillar Avenue, in Milngavie.
The court was told that the Mackies, who lived in Lenzie, had searched for two
years for their ideal home - somewhere secluded, yet close to city amenities.
When Hayhill came on the market, they wanted it so much that they offered
#35,000 above the asking price to secure the purchase.
Two days after they moved in, local farmer Jack Brewster came to introduce
himself - and told them work was about to start on his new house next door.
Mr Mackie, an electrical engineer, told the court: ``We certainly would not
have bought Hayhill if we had known what was going to happen.''
The court heard that Mrs Mackie also claimed she had suffered stress from
construction noise - and was subjected to verbal abuse from workmen.
</TEXT>
