<HEADLINE>A question of discipline</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES TRAYNOR  Chief sports writer</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>39</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975356015</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PAUL Gascoigne has been named in the referee supervisor's report on last
Saturday's match between Rangers and Aberdeen at Ibrox, but three other players
- Gascoigne's team-mates John Brown and Alan McLaren, and Aberdeen's Billy
Dodds - also are in trouble.
The report arrived at the SFA yesterday and shortly afterwards both clubs and
all four players were asked to explain their conduct during the match. It is
likely their behaviour and comments will be considered during a disciplinary
committee meeting on Monday.
Gascoigne's behaviour by now has been well documented, but the conduct of the
others didn't receive the same degree of exposure.
They, in fact, became involved in a bad-tempered tussle in the second half,
when McLaren and Dodds disputed possession and then the Aberdeen player
appeared to aim a kick at his opponent.
Brown then arrived and it looked as though he made contact with a hand or an
arm on Dodds' head. McLaren's reaction was ill-tempered, but there was no
physical abuse on his part.
A spokesman at Park Gardens said yesterday: ``We have received the supervisor's
report and, on the strength of what is contained in it, we will be seeking the
comments of those involved.
``The report made mention of Paul Gascoigne and also three other players, John
Brown and Alan McLaren of Rangers, and Aberdeen's Billy Dodds. We hope to have
the comments of clubs and players by Friday.''
Gascoigne is likely to be summoned to appear before the SFA after Monday's
disciplinary meeting and, depending on the mood of the meeting, the others
involved might also have to take the long walk up the hill.
Alan Lawrence, of Hearts, has been asked to explain an alleged use of an elbow
against Rangers' Craig Moore in a game last month and Airdrie's Sean Sweeney,
who is alleged to have kicked Dundee's Morten Wieghorst in a Coca-Cola Cup
semi-final, also will have to offer an explanation.
However, in light of the news which stunned Dumbarton's keeper Ian McFarlane
yesterday, the players should not believe they will be treated lightly if found
guilty.
McFarlane was told he had been sent off twice in last Saturday's match against
Airdrie and has been banned for three games, although that might not be the end
of the matter.
The keeper was dismissed after a disagreement with Airdrie's Jim McIntyre, who
later described the incident as handbags at 10 paces.''
However, the head of the SFA's disciplinary department, Drew Herbertson, said
McFarlane had been sent off twice, once for alleged head-butting and again for
an alleged punch.
Each offence carries an automatic one-match ban and 12 penalty points, which
means the keeper is well beyond the 16-point threshold and picks up another
game ban.
``Both McFarlane and Dumbarton are being asked for their comments,'' said
Herbertson.
Dumbarton have sent out an emergency call to the old warhorse, John Burridge,
who coaches Newcastle's keepers during the week.
Burridge helped Dumbarton out last year when they were left short of keepers
through injury.
q BIRMINGHAM City were at the centre of an alleged dressing room brawl after
their Anglo-Italian Cup match in Ancona yesterday. The coach of the second
division Ancona team was said to have been injured in the fighting between
players and officials.
Massimo Cacciatori allegedly was butted by a Birmingham player and suffered a
cut over his left eyebrow and a bruise. The game, which Birmingham won 2-1, was
marred by rough play and fights between players at Conero stadium.
</TEXT>
