<HEADLINE>Republic's play-off a lifeline EUROPEAN CHAMPIONSHIPi</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>39</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356017</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JACK Charlton and the Republic of Ireland owed an enormous debt of gratitude to
their northern neighbours after a thrilling night in Group 6 of the European
Championship qualifying competition.
Northern Ireland destroyed Austria's hopes of a place in the finals with a
marvellous 5-3 victory at Windsor Park.
And that result took the Republic into a play-off with Holland at Anfield on
December 13 for the final place, despite a convincing 3-0 defeat at the hands
of group winners Portugal.
Northern Ireland manager Brian Hamilton sent a message of goodwill to Jack
Charlton after the game in Belfast. He said: ``We wish the Republic well. They
deserve to go through on the basis of their results in the group.
``I hope Jack is successful. He is a good man and he has done a great job.''
Charlton, who has dismissed speculation that he might be about to leave the
manager's job after nine years, said that despite the drubbing they received at
the hands of an inspired Portuguese side in Lisbon, the Irish still had a
fighting chance of making the finals.
``I have to thank Bryan Hamilton,'' he said. ``I'll be buying him a bottle of
whisky - duty free because it's cheaper,'' he joked.
Michael O'Neill of Hibs was the architect of Northern Ireland's rousing victory
with two goals.
He got the opener when Michael Hughes crossed the ball over and Iain Dowie
chested it down. O'Neill was on hand to fire a sweet left-foot shot home from
the edge of the box. The Irish added a second in the 32nd minute when
Pfeifenberger brought down Dowie in the box. The West Ham striker fired an
unstoppable spot kick past stranded keeper Konsel.
Hunter, making his home debut, scored his first goal at this level after 53
minutes when Konsel punched away a Gillespie cross and the Wrexham centre-half
finished like a decent centre forward.
The Austrians, to their credit, dug deep and got a goal back in 56 minutes when
Markus Schopp headed in.
The Irish regained their three-goal advantage when Phillip Gray got the final
touch after Hunter had beaten Konsel when he followed up a corner from Hughes
in 64 minutes.
Irish keeper Alan Fettis could only parry a shot from Polster in 70 minutes and
substitute Christian Stumpf followed it up.
The fun continued in 78 minutes when O'Neill got his second goal after Hughes
had raced almost the full length of the pitch to put him clear.
Austria got their third goal nine minutes from time when Manchester City's
midfielder Steve Lomas slipped and subsitute Arnold Wetl drilled the ball past
Fettis.
Hamilton said: ``We have made massive changes and my players deserve enormous
credit.
``We showed great resilience tonight and the way we kept possession was very
pleasing.
``There is a wind of change blowing through Northern Ireland football and I
believe we are heading for brighter days.''
Although the Republic fought gallantly in Lisbon to stay on terms in the first
half they were eventually steam-rollered by a Portugese team two or three
classes above them in technical ability.
Only the heroics of Sheffield United goalkeeper Alan Kelly and the brilliant
tackling of veteran centre back Paul McGrath, playing his record-breaking 79th
game for the Republic, prevented Portugal launching an avalanche of goals in
the second period.
Kelly kept out successive shots from Paulo Sousa, Louis Figo and Carlos
Secretairo before finally being beaten when Fiorientina midfielder Rui Costa
lobbed him from fully 30 yards and saw the ball bounce in from the underside of
the crossbar.
Portugal, who had raised the tempo in the second half following a tip-tap
display of pretty passing in the first, proceeded to drive home the victory
and, after the initial breakthrough, it was just a matter of how many they
would score.
Defender Cristovao Helder added a second with a header from Figo's corner on 74
minutes and just before the end substitute Jorge Cadete slotted home the third.
</TEXT>
