<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>OIL AND GAS Pittencrieff warns as reserves disappoint</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KRISTY DORSEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356018</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SHORTFALL in expected production from Texas fields has led Edinburgh-based
Pittencrieff Resources to predict a loss for this year.
Chief executive Terry Heneaghan said yesterday that a fresh evaluation of all
the company's gas and oil assets in the US and Canada showed a sharp drop in
proven reserves to 17 billion barrels of oil equivalent (boe) from 36.1 billion
at the end of last year.
The value of these reserves has been slashed to $83.7m from $156.8m at the end
of 1994.
Mr Heneaghan said exploratory drilling at Pittencrieff's fields in Corpus
Christi, Texas - for which the company paid $38m in 1994 - had revealed fewer
reserves than expected. He added that technical difficulties were making the
exploration process difficult.
``We drilled into the zones and found that we're not getting the results that
the engineers said we would,'' he said. ``Not until you actually poke the hole
down there will you know what is actually going to come out.''
With less oil and gas reserves than previously thought, Pittencrieff has been
forced to reduce its total asset figures. Recent increases in gas prices are
insufficient to offset the asset depletion charges.
Mr Heneaghan said it was difficult to tell at this stage exactly how large the
company's 1995 loss would be.
Pittencrieff has commissioned a $750,000 3-D seismic study of the Corpus
Christi fields to determine exactly what resources are there and how they can
best be recovered. Until that is completed in around six months, it will not be
drilling any new wells at the site.
Edinburgh-based Bell Lawrie White analyst Colin Telfer said the study's
conclusions would determine Pittencrieff's future. ``We have to wait until that
is finished,'' he said, ``but it still doesn't affect their cash flow.''
Mr Heneaghan said Dallas-based Netherland, Sewall &amp; Associates, which is
conducting the engineering evaluation of Pittencrieff's US assets, was widely
known as a highly professional yet conservative company. For that reason, the
preliminary appraisal could reflect a lower amount of reserves than were
actually there.
The preliminary report showed a slight increase in probable reserves, up from
4650 million to 4800 million boe. After deducting net debt, there is
approximately 80p of asset backing per company share.
Mr Heneaghan said the group's other assets, which include the Fort Chadbourne
site in Texas and the Patricia/Dinosaur gas field in Canada, were continuing to
perform well.
Pittencrieff shares were unchanged at 43p.
</TEXT>
