<HEADLINE>Currency falls to all-time low on foreign exchanges as City anticipates an early cut in interest rates Retail sales decline upsets sterling</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>R E DUNDAS Chief Financial Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356019</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STERLING'S trade-weighted index, the barometer of the pound's international
value most closely monitored by the Bank of England, fell to its lowest ever
level last night after figures showed an expected decline in the volume of
retail sales last month and the first rise in seasonally-adjusted unemployment
for more than two years.
The gloomy news on the economy intensified expectations in the City that
interest rates would be cut sooner rather than later. The pound, already under
pressure from a weak dollar, fell sharply against the German mark, where it
lost 1.80 pfennigs to DM2.1849, within a pfennig of its all-time low of
DM2.1755.
The trade-weighted index dropped 0.7 points to 82.6, 0.1 points below the
previous low on May 9, shortly after the Governor of the Bank of England and
the Chancellor of the Exchequer fell out over rates.
But shares and gilts took heart from the speculation that rates would have to
be cut. The FTSE-100 share index gained 23.5 points to 3571.4.
The Retail Consortium, which claims to represent more than 90% of shops, called
on the Chancellor to cut taxes in the Budget on November 28.
James May, the consortium's director general, said: ``The Budget provides an
opportunity for the Chancellor to relieve some of the negative factors which
are holding back consumer spending at present.
``Retailers are looking for a sustainable tax-cutting Budget. As long as public
expenditure is firmly controlled this can be delivered without breaching
responsible limits on public borrowing.''
Later today the PSBR figures for October will show the extent to which the
Government's borrowing requirement has exceeded Treasury forecasts in the first
seven months of the current fiscal year.
Retail sales fell by 0.1% in October, disappointing City forecasts of an
increase of around 0.4% and contradicting an optimistic distributive trades
survey from the CBI last week. The only consolation was that the figures for
September were revised up from a 0.1% rise to 0.3%. There were also small
upward revisions to the figures for July and August. The volume of sales was
precisely the same as it was in October last year.
The three-month on three-month comparisons were even more disappointing. These
showed that sales fell by 0.3% in the latest three months and were just 0.1%
higher than in the same three months a year ago.
In October clothing and footwear sales fell by 1.4% and food by 0.4%. The mild
weather was blamed for the former and higher prices may be hitting food
volumes. Elsewhere increases were modest, except for household goods which
jumped 1.3%.
The three-monthly comparisons showed that this sector increased sales by 1.9%
despite the weakness of the housing market. The ready availability of cheap
credit could explain this apparent aberration from the broader picture.
The biggest declines in the latest three months were recorded by clothing and
footwear (down 2.1%) and non-store retailing (down 2%).
The retail sales deflator edged down from 3.5% in September to 3.4%, suggesting
that October's inflation figures, which will be published later today, may be a
little better than expected.
The unexpected increase of 200 in seasonally adjusted unemployment to 2,265,500
was the first rise since August 1993. The change is minimal and unemployment
was lower in six out of 10 areas, including Scotland. The July numbers -
originally reported as showing an increase - are now sporting a drop of 200.
The Central Statistical Office said that the October figures might be distorted
by an unusually large number of young people joining the register, but other
labour market indicators confirmed the picture of weakness.
Vacancies fell by 1800 in October, the largest decline since June 1989, while
manufacturing employment fell by another 3000 in September, the third
consecutive drop.
Growth in average earnings was unchanged in September at 3.25%, but
year-on-year growth in unit labour costs picked up from 3.6% to 3.8% as the
sharp slowdown in productivity continued.
Adam Cole of James Capel said: ``The rise in unemployment, coupled with stable
average earnings growth and the fall in retail sales, significantly increases
the chance of a rate cut sooner rather than later.
``The last piece of the jigsaw is likely to be the Budget, where a positive
market response could mean rates are cut around the turn of the year.''
</TEXT>
