<DOCID>GH951116-000042</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Front-runners Norway are pipped at the post EUROPEAN ROUND-UP</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>39</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356020</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ON A night when 14 teams booked their places alongside hosts England in the
1996 European Championship finals, with two others involved in a play-off next
month, Norway were eliminated after having led their qualifying group for
almost a year.
The Norwegians, who last year qualified for the World Cup finals for the first
time in 56 years, needed to avoid defeat in Rotterdam to qualify for the
European finals for the first time in their history.
But their dreams were shattered as they lost 3-0 to finish third in Group 5
behind the Czech Republic and Holland.
A goal four minutes into the second half from Clarence Seedorf and two in the
last two minutes from Youri Mulder and Marc Overmars finished off the
Norwegians - who had let in only four goals in their previous nine qualifiers.
But the Dutch, European champions in 1988, must meet Ireland in a play-off in
Liverpool on December 13 for the final qualifying berth.
Germany, the only country to win the European title twice, avenged their recent
defeats against Bulgaria with a 3-1 win in Berlin to take first place from the
Bulgarians in Group 7. Jurgen Klinsmann, who scored twice, took his tally for
the competition to nine.
But it was a night of mixed emotions for Klinsmann, who received a first-half
booking which rules him out of Germany's first match in the finals in England,
where he played with such success at Tottenham Hotspur last season.
Gianfranco Zola went one better than Klinsmann, scoring a second-half hat trick
as Italy overwhelmed Lithuania 4-0 to clinch their berth.
The diminutive playmaker, brought on as a second-half substitute, struck three
times in just 18 minutes after Lithuanian captain Ramunas Stonkus's own goal
had given Italy the lead in 51 minutes.
Nikola Jurcevic's diving header gave Croatia a 2-1 victory over Slovenia.
Croatia topped Group 4 thanks to a better head-to-head record against Italy.
There was joy at last for Azerbaijan - who picked up their first point after
nine defeats by drawing 0-0 with Poland in neutral Trabzon in Turkey.
That left Estonia and San Marino as the only two teams out of the 47 taking
part to have lost all their qualifying games.
France erased painful memories when they beat Israel 2-0 with two late goals.
The French, anxious to wipe out memories of the embarrassing 3-2 home defeat by
Israel in 1993 which cost them a place in the World Cup finals, wasted several
opportunities before taking the lead in 69 minutes.
</TEXT>
