<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000043</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000043</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scots fail to close gap BOWLING</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GORDON DUNWOODIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>38</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356021</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S bowlers staged a brief revival in the European indoor team
championship in Jersey yesterday when they moved to within nine points of
leaders Wales after the men's session of singles and fours matches but, with
Wales drawing a blank last night, Scotland's women tumbled to two defeats
against Guernsey to miss out on a great chance of closing the gap.
The revival started yesterday afternoon when East Lothian's Graham Robertson
had a straight-sets win over Guernsey's Jon Queripel to pick up the maximum
three points. Robertson took the opener 7-4, the second 7-3, and then drew the
match-winning shot with his last bowl of the seventh end for a 7-6 third-set
margin.
Queripel had been pushed into the singles event earlier in the day when Adrian
Welch pulled out for the second day owing to illness.
``Given the circumstances, Jon played well,'' said Robertson. ``Although it was
a straight-sets win, it was a lot closer than that - the first set and the last
could have gone either way.''
Scotland then added the points in the men's fours when Willie Galloway, David
Gourlay, Hugh Duff, and Angus Blair recovered after dropping a second-end 7 to
beat Paul Ingrouille's Guernsey rink 27-16.
However, there was disappointment last night when the women's side failed to
build on these two results.
Joyce Lindores started well against Anne Simon, leading 4-0 and later 6-5, but
she lost the opening set 7-6 and thereafter she struggled. Simon needed just
three ends to take the second set on a 7-0 whitewash and she coasted through
the third 7-2.
Nor was there any cheer for Scotland in the women's fours. Kate Adams, Jan
Woodley, Sarah Gourlay, and Jeanette Conlan lost two shots on the last end to
go down 14-12 to Carol Ingrouille's Guernsey side.
With Wales having lost all four of their matches to England, they stayed on the
33-points mark, where England joined them, although the Welsh have a shots
differential of 107 against England's 93. Ireland now are in third spot on 25
points, one ahead of the Scots. Results:
