<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>England 3, Switzerland 1 Stone seals a rare win for England</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEVE TONGUE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>39</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975356022</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ENGLAND achieved their first victory in a year last night as national coach
Terry Venables confounded his critics and Paul Gascoigne offered no new
ammunition to his.
Gascoigne was involved in the build up to two of the goals and used his arms
only to embrace the scorers of them and wave to a satisfied crowd. Venables was
able to claim vindication of a selection that had left out David Platt, Peter
Beardsley and Les Ferdinand, while finally offering Alan Shearer some support
in the shape of Teddy Sheringham, who headed the second goal.
A goal to each side just before half-time set light to a game that had been
glowing nicely until then. The Swiss went ahead in the 41st minute with two
deft moments of skill under pressure. Turkyilmaz, out on the left, curled in a
cross which his striking partner Adrian Knup met with the finest of headers.
The equaliser, four minutes later, also finished with a significant Swiss
touch, defender Quentin diverting in Stuart Pearce's shot after Gascoigne had
played a short corner to McManaman.
The Rangers man had first quickened English pulses in the fifth minute, given
an opportunity by Jamie Redknapp to turn, some 25 yards out, and move forward
before curling a right-footed shot beyond the far post.
A change in the midfield was immediately necessary, Redknapp having pulled a
hamstring and having to make way for Nottingham Forest's Steve Stone, a more
natural wide player.
It was a poor pass by Gascoigne that put his team in trouble for the first
time, forcing Pallister into a hurried clearance straight to Knup. The
Karlsruhe striker's shot,though fierce, was straight enough for Seaman to parry.
A similar incident gave England their most encouraging moment of the first
half-hour. Alain Geiger, playing for the 110th time at international level,
belied his experience by hitting the ball at Sheringham, who stabbed it square
for Shearer. Goalkeeper Pascolo beat out the 20-yard drive to prevent Shearer
registering his first goal in eight games for his country.
As in Norway on his debut last month, Stone got in some useful crosses, one of
which brought England's second goal after 56 minutes. Gascoigne began the move,
carried on by Lee, Neville and Stone and finished with a flourish by
Sheringham's firm header.
Their confidence soaring, England went on to establish control and claim a
third goal 12 minutes from the end. Stone, looking offside, reacted quickly to
score after the goalkeeper had pushed out Shearer's shot.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
