<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000046</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000046</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Crown her Queen if she zaps pap</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Brian Meek</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356024</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NOT really ill - just jolly uncomfortable. Don't put your sinuses up for
scraping or your septum for a new direction in life unless you wish to feel
that your face has run into Frank Bruno . . . or maybe even Gazza on a
high-pressure day.
Everyone has been most kind. The nurse who admitted me says I will be looked
after by the red team - is this on instructions from St Andrew's House, I
wonder? - the anaesthetist tells me he was at Cardiff last Saturday and that
Fiji should have won. I am about to answer his question about Scotland's
chances this week when all the lights in my stadium go out.
Wake up with a nose packed like Ibrox on Old Firm day wearing a kind of bag
that you used to see on carthorses. Would you like a painkiller, inquires an
angel? No, a large gin and tonic is not what we had in mind.
The television is on in my room, a programme about the Daily Record of all
things. Am I hallucinating or did Joan Burnie really tell a story about a woman
with false teeth who was worried about oral sex? Must have been the drugs.
A long night of snuffling and wiping is enlivened when a friendly nurse gives
me a ham and cucumber sandwich and I give it back, re-cycled, in a matter of
moments. Settled for Sarah Miles, her autobiography.
It's maybe 20 years since I have been kept overnight in a hospital and I have
strict instructions to rest, take a break, watch the television. There are a
lot of splendid programmes on during the day, I am assured. Well I had nine
channels at my disposal and they were uniformly awful.
I started with Kilroy on BBC; he used to be a kind of upmarket Labour MP -
actually he would fit in very well with the new Blair image - but now makes a
lot more lolly from the box. His was the first of many shows where presenters
leapt into the audience.
Sadly the audience did not throw them back.
Kilroy tells us more and more people in Britain are taking the law into their
own hands. There were no stats to back up this assertion but his studio was
full of folk only too ready to zap intruders, fight for the last supermarket
trolley, defend to the death their parking space. Pass the remote control,
Alice.
I flitted for a while on Sky Movies with Mario And The Mob but it was a bit too
like Kilroy and the Cast so I went to Channel 4. Their schools' broadcast was
entitled Maths Everywhere. Only wish it were.
Went back to the Beeb for Good Morning with Anne and Nick. After 10 minutes
decided this pair reminded me of Andy Pandy and Looby Lou, only they have fewer
entertaining ideas. Don't be sick with Anne and Nick would be my guiding
principle.
On the ITV side there were Richard and Judy, just as forced fun and as bland as
beefless burger.
But this lot is just for starters. It is in the afternoons when daytime
television reveals all. Or rather ordinary people do - to Oprah, on several
channels, to Esther, to Ricki.
They are encouraged to confess in public how they slept with their husband's
best pal, went to live on a desert island, couldn't handle being teenagers, had
beaten their budgies and now believe that all men are beasts.
OK, a lot of these shows are American but they are being shown by our
television companies, the ones we always claim provide the finest service in
the world. Frankly I think they are the worst kind of tabloid time-filling, an
insult to the housebound, shift workers, or anyone else who has to be at home
during daylight hours.I was reaching for the book when the mega-story broke.
Princess Di was going to appear on screen to tell all. ``My life of hell with
Chuck'', ``How HM made me eat kippers at Balmoral'', ``The day I discovered
Will's dummy''. There will be no sleeping when this moll sets out her stall.
She will start, of course, on prestige Panorama. But everything she says will
be taken down, dissected, debated, debunked by Kilroy, Judy, Richard, Ricki,
Anne, Nick, and all the other purveyors of pap for weeks on end.
I am sorry for the Prince and Princess of Wales, as I am for any other couple
whose marriage has gone wrong. But that sympathy is much diluted by their
insistence, like guests on any of a thousand chattering shows, on justifying
themselves before the great god television.
Whatever Diana says on Monday, even if it is only ``OK ya'', she will not
emerge with an enhanced reputation. The putative Queen follows the would-be
King on to the hot television seat - ``if you have a question, call this
freephone number'' - and in doing so they may both be throwing away a throne.
I do not expect those who would reign over us to lead lives of absolute moral
rectitude. After all, they never did. But I do not wish them, by their own
decision, to wash the royal linen on screen.
Watching Charles squirming on his chair, mangling vowels along the way, as he
told us he had been unfaithful, is not part of the unwritten contract he has
with Britain. His estranged wife, who may be very kind to young children and
animals, has been proved to possess the intellectual capacity of a goldfish.
They are selfish, silly people who take little regard for the cruelty they are
both inflicting on their offspring.
This branch of the House of Windsor may be the first live suicides on
television. For I believe the country is heartily sick of their antics.
Those like myself who favour the continuation of the monarchy can only hope
that the Princess Royal might succeed her mother, at least until the young
Princes are tried and tested.
But they must promise, in the Coronation Oath, to avoid daytime television.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000047</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000047</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Boardroom shuffle at merchant bank Hambros slides into the red</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STONE, City Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975356025</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT'S not quite all change at Hambros, where bad debts of #23.5m - mostly on old
loans - and exceptional charges of #8.8m have left a first-half loss of #7.7m
before tax against a profit #21.5m last time, but the group is striving to put
up defensive barriers and at the same time concentrating on those activities in
which it can grow.
Given the takeovers that have already taken place in the merchant banking
market place Hambros is regarded as vulnerable although its main shareholder,
the Italian Gruppo Bancario San Paolo, signalled its support for the company
saying that it intended to boost its stake to around 20% from its present
14.12% by buying in the market.
The Italians also own 32.9% of the convertible share capital, and according to
Sir Chips Keswick, who has been appointed chief executive of the group and
non-executive chairman of Hambros Bank, shares the company's vision of the
future of Hambros as an independent bank. Aside from Sir Chips, a fairly
extensive boardroom shuffle also sees Christopher Sporborg relinquishing his
position as chairman and chief executive of Hambro Group Investments and
retiring from the board of Hambros bank to concentrate on his role as chairman
of Hambro Countrywide and Hambro Insurance Services.
Hambros chairman Lord Hambro says that competitive pressures in the main areas
in which the company operates have remained intense, and exceptional costs have
been absorbed in the first phase of reorganising a number of its businesses.
Shareholders also see their interim dividend reduced from 4.5p to 2.5p and a
final of 5p is forecast to give an unchanged total of 7.5p, albeit this is half
the 1993-94 payout.
Under its strategic review, Hambros has been cutting back some of its banking
activities including the equities clearing business and Australian
stockbroking. In addition, treasury operations have been slimmed down both in
the UK and Australia.
The company's residential mortgage portfolio has also been sold, though at a
substantial premium.
On the investment management side, Hambros intends to seek opportunities to
enlarge funds whether by joint venture or acquisitions.
Benefits from the the company's ``new approach'' are expected to begin to show
themselves by the the end of its financial year. But in the meantime profits in
the current year will remain depressed as changes take place.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000048</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000048</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>TENNIS Smith is on song</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JUDY MURAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>39</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356026</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TENNIS
SAMANTHA Smith, the 1994 Scottish Champion, kept the British flag flying in the
Texaco Women's Challenger Event in Edinburgh when she upset seventh seed
Adriana Gersi to book her place on today's quarter-final.
The 23-year-old from Essex, who survived two match points during her 2-6, 6-2,
7-5 first round victory over qualifier Julie Pullin, trailed the Czech 4-2 in
the first set before reeling off six games in a row to establish a 2-0 lead in
the second. Smith, ranked 145 places below Gersi at 365 on the WTA computer,
broke serve again in the fifth game and went on to clinch a 6-4, 6-2 victory to
set up a clash with top seed Sandra Kleinova. The Czech teenager was extended
to a second set tie-break before edging past Ukrainian Nelly Barkan 6-2, 7-6
yesterday.
Exeter left hander Karen Cross and Jo Ward, last year's national champion,
failed to survive the second round. Cross, the British No.3, posed few problems
for big serving Sabine Gerke, a German qualifier, who has yet to drop a set in
five matches in the $25,000 tournament. Gerke's 6-1, 6-3 victory earns her a
clash with third seed Marion Maruska, who won eight successive games from 5-3
down to beat Ward 7-5, 6-0.
JUDY MURRAY
</TEXT>
