<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000049</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000049</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Stadium plan in doubt SHINTY</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HIUGH DAN MACLENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>38</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356027</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PLANS for a national stadium for shinty appear to be heading for touch, with
cold water being poured on the proposal that Fort William be considered as a
venue. The plan will go before Lochaber District Council's leisure and
recreation committee at the start of next week.
The proposal, to upgrade the facilities which have already housed the Camanachd
Cup Final and this season's international against the Irish, would need the
backing of the Camanachd Association to succeed.
Association president Duncan Cameron said yesterday: ``We do not have any plans
at the moment for such a venue and, quite frankly, I doubt if it would attract
the sort of support needed to proceed.
``There is no agreement, it appears to me, where that venue would be. Such a
move would also require changes to our constitution, which requires us to take
the game's showpiece, the Camanachd Cup final, round a series of venues. I
cannot see clubs voting to alter that for a single venue as things stand.''
Meanwhile, Fort William is the venue for the First Shinty festival a week on
Sunday - a modified version of the game, played on a smaller pitch, with a
larger, softer ball and lighter sticks with rubber heads.
This weekend's main action centres on the only premier game lost to the weather
this season, Oban Camanachd's match away to Newtonmore.
Fort William face Strathglass in a replay of their Keyline MacAulay cup-tie.The
pick of the league matches this weekend are at Perth in south division one,
where runaway leaders Kyles are the visitors, and at Spean Bridge in the north,
where the league leaders Caberfeidh face a crucial match against Lochaber.
HUGH DAN MACLENNAN
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000050</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000050</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Shine On's light entertainment on streets</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEITH BRUCE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356028</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALMOST #500,000 is being spent to attract Christmas shoppers to Glasgow.
Shine On Glasgow, a programme of street entertainment, will begin on Sunday,
November 26, with a parade before the Christmas lights in George Square are
switched on.
The Shine On programme, unveiled for the first time last year, is a partnership
between city-centre retailers and local authorities. Funding this year comes
from Glasgow City Council (#170,000), Strathclyde Regional Council (#50,000),
and Glasgow Development Agency (#50,000).
A further cash injection has come from Coca Cola, which this year is
contributing ``more than #100,000'' in cash and sponsorship-in-kind. A further
#60,000 is to be raised from city centre retailers, shopping centres, and
hotels who are members of Glasgow City Centre Association.
Mr Bill Neish, the association's chairman, said the programme brought clear
economic benefits. Last year, when events were scheduled for the Sundays in the
run-up to Christmas, trade had increased by 17% on three of the four Sundays
and hotels in the city were almost full.
This year, there will be events every day for a month, beginning on Sunday when
Coca Cola hosts an Alternative Christmas Party in George Square with music from
Ultimate Kaos, the Night Crawlers, and soap star turned pop star Sean Maguire.
Ms Jane Webb, Coca Cola's business development manager, said her company has
paid for the commissioning of three new structures for Glasgow's pedestrian
areas, two of which will be temporary performance spaces.
Argyle Street will have a six and a half metre Orrery - a steel and neon
sculpture depicting the movement of the planets and stars, made by Julian Goss
at Glasgow Sculpture Studios.
A 17-metre steel Christmas Tree capable of accomodating a gospel choir will be
placed at the bottom of Buchanan Street. It has been designed by city
architects Richardson Associates.
A five-metre cuckoo clock, by Steve Edgar, Graeme Gilmour, and Simon Hopkins at
the sculpture studios, for Sauchiehall Street includes a revolving stage for
performances limited to fifteen minutes.
Mr Alastair Wyllie, director of Shine On, said the aim of the project was to
promote Glasgow as the UK's Christmas shopping capital. Packages are being
offered to visitors through the Greater Glasgow Tourist Board and special
travel deals have been negotiated.
At the switching on of the Christmas Lights, to be performed by Burgomeister Dr
Pieter Schonlein, mayor of Nuremberg, in recognition of the 10th anniversary of
the twinning link between the two cities, 850,000 stars will be launched into
the air at George Square, one for every Glasgow citizen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000051</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000051</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>INSURANCE GA bid success</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356029</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POLICYHOLDERS in Provident Mutual Life Assurance have overwelmingly accepted a
recommended #170m bid by Perth-based General Accident.
About 97% of the Provident Mutual policyholders voted in favour of the move at
an extraordinary meeting yesterday.
Completion of the deal remains conditional on court approval, expected in late
December. Recommending acceptance of the General Accident bid six weeks ago,
the Provident Mutual board warned that the life assurance company would face
short-term costs of at least #20m if it chose to remain independent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000052</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000052</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>CONSTRUCTION Tarmac and Wimpey to sign #700m deal</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356030</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TARMAC and George Wimpey are swapping assets in a deal worth almost #700m,
aimed at focusing each group on a core market.
In the case of Wimpey this is housebuilding and in the case of Tarmac, heavy
building products including aggregates and services.
Following a strategic review Wimpey has decided to withdraw from contracting
and minerals in order to focus exclusively on housing and land development. As
such it has agreed in principle to exchange its construction and minerals
division for Tarmac's housing division which includes McLean Homes in Scotland.
The deal is expected to be an earnings enhancement for Wimpey in the first full
year. Tarmac does not anticipate any dilution of its 1996 earnings.
As a result of the asset swap, as many as 4000 Wimpey employees will move to
Tarmac and 2000 Tarmac employees will transfer to Wimpey. There are likely to
be as yet undisclosed redundancies once the rationalisation of the merged
businesses gets underway.
Tarmac's housing business has been on the market since August. Talks between
the companies began with about a month ago. Commenting on the transaction
Neville Simms, Tarmac group chief executive, said that transferring the housing
division ``to a company which is committed to private sector housebuilding will
provide the best opportunity for the future of the business and its employees''.
Given the perilous state of the UK housing market it may seem an odd decision
to focus a company entirely on housing. Indeed, yesterday Wimpey said that
since its interim statement in September, market conditions had deteriorated in
both housing and construction.
Wimpey's trading profits for the year are expected to be materially lower than
the 1994 level and pre-tax profits substantially lower. Housing completions are
expected to be 7500 although the need for incentives to attract buyers
adversely affected margins.
However Mr Dwyer said that Wimpey's housing business had always been a major
contributor to profits and that it was extremely cash generative. Around a
third of Wimpey's assets are turned into cash each year. He is optimistic about
the group's prospects in 1996.
Last year, Wimpey was the UK's largest housebuilder. Its housing stock is
geared towards first time buyers, with an average selling price of #60,000.
The acquired Tarmac housing business is in the second time buyer market with an
average selling price of around #80,000 and so provides a complementary fit
with Wimpey's existing business. Both concerns are to run as separate
stand-alone entities.
Following the merger Wimpey will consolidate its position as Britain's largest
housebuilder with a market share of around 10%, twice that of its nearest
rivals Beazer and Barratt.
However, there are unikely to be any monopoly at this level. Wimpey will also
be one of the world's largest housing and land development groups.
The deal, which is expected to be formally signed early next year, was welcomed
by the City. Wimpey's shares added 15p to 127p while Tarmac gained 9p to 92!sp.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000053</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000053</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Young Scots do not fear tough draw</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>39</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975356031</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S cocky, fresh-faced footballers, as represented by the Under-21 side,
can look forward to testing their growing reputation against the very best
young players in Europe when the draw for the European Championship
quarter-finals is made today in Geneva.
The quality of the opposition is such that any one of the seven countries who
will go into the hat alongside the Scots will provide a formidable task.
The names alone will very nearly be sufficient - France, Germany, Italy,
Hungary, Czech Republic, Spain, and Portugal - to tell the tale, but the
current Under-21 record of these sides, a level at which they have always been
exceptional, demonstrates the talent at their disposal. However, Scotland's own
performance in Group 8 shows that they have a fair bit of ability themselves.
In fact, the Scots' record of winning seven of their eight games is better than
any of the other qualifiers in their groups, although some did very nearly as
well against tough opposition.
Portugal, for example, did not lose a game in their section, which included
England, drawing twice and winning six times.
Germany, as ever, will be hard to tackle, as they showed in the deciding game
of their section on Tuesday, when they beat their only challengers, Bulgaria,
7-0 in Bonn.
The Czech's growing stature in the international arena was confirmed by their
young side's success in a group that contained Holland and Norway, while
another east European country, Hungary, left Sweden, among others, behind in
their section.
France's group was perhaps the most competitive, with Romania, Poland and
Slovakia all serious challengers at various stages. Spain had to beat off
Denmark and Belgium to get this far, while Italy left it a bit late to secure
their place, making it narrowly after drawing 0-0 with Lithuania at home
yesterday.
Every one a winner, for sure, but Scotland's manager, Tommy Craig, will not be
quaking at the prospect of facing any of them. ``Obviously, when you see the
teams involved you can expect everybody to be wary of the talent on show, but I
think we have done enough in our group for the others to be a bit wary of us
now,'' he said, not unreasonably. What Craig does promise is a complete
commitment to attacking play, in the away leg as well as at home, which he
believes was the key to the fine run in the group.
``It is nice for this group to be among the cream of Europe,'' he said, ``but I
would take this squad anywhere in the world and I know they would put on a show
and maybe win. We will play the same way no matter who we get.''
The man who is also assistant manager at Aberdeen has used 34 players in the
campaign, never having fielded the same side twice, but after the defeat by
Finland in the opening tie the chosen 11 did the job anyway.
The defeat of San Marino on Tuesday completed the first stage of the Under-21's
journey into Europe, but now it gets even more tricky.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000054</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000054</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>This `Band' is tuned up</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WHITE and GOLD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356032</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SMITH'S Band can ensure a familiar set of colours are seen in the winner's
enclosure tomorrow after the Hamilton Litestat Handicap Chase at Wincanton.
Owner Arthur Smith is one of Jenny Pitman's longest-standing patrons and has
enjoyed success with Smith's Man in the Topham Trophy and Smith's Cracker in
the Philip Cornes Saddle of Gold Final in the past decade.
Smith's Band has the makings of a useful handicapper. Like many of his
stable-mates, he left modest hurdling form behind him when sent over fences
last term and picked up novice events at Stratford, Leicester and Cheltenham.
That was despite some less than fluent jumping which saw him come to grief two
out at Kempton in February and prevented his landing a blow in the Sun Alliance
Novices' Chase at Cheltenham the following month.
One of Smith's Band's stable-companions is honoured at Warwick, where the
feature race is the Willsford Handicap Chase, named after last Saturday's
Cheltenham winner who has scored five times on this course.
Though Mrs Pitman will have hopes of landing the prize with Mailcom, he'll
certainly do well to concede nearly a stone to Maamur, a potentially smart
chaser.
q COULDNT Be Better threw down the gauntlet to Hennessy hotpot One Man
yesterday with a satisfactory comeback at Haydock Park.
The gelding's odds were cut to 7-1 from 14s by William Hill and 9-1 from 11s by
Ladbrokes for the big Newbury handicap after defeating Chatam by two lengths in
the Edward Hanmer Memorial Chase.
Chatam, also putting up a creditable performance on his seasonal debut, is 12-1
with William Hill and 16-1 with Ladbrokes, but One Man remains a rock-solid
favourite at7-4 with both firms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000055</DOCNO>
