<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Turkey the newcomers EUROPEAN CHAMPIONSHIP ROUND-UP</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>39</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356033</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HOLDERS Denmark, who ended their group matches with a 3-1 home win over
Armenia, and newcomers Croatia, were among the latest qualifiers for the
European championship finals yesterday.
Germany, the only team to have won the trophy twice, Bulgaria, Romania, Turkey,
Italy, and Scotland also joined hosts England and the previously qualified
Spain, Russia and Switzerland in the finals for next June.
Turkey, who drew 2-2 away to Sweden in their last match in Group 3, have
reached the finals of a major tournament for the first time since the 1954
World Cup. Romania, inspired by their World Cup midfielder Gheorghe Hagi, and
Germany went through by winning their groups, as had former champions Spain and
Russia.
Captain Jurgen Klinsmann scored twice, his second a penalty, as the Germans
came from behind to beat Bulgaria 3-1.
Parma's Hristo Stoichkov put the Bulgarians ahead just after half time, only
for Klinsmann to equalise three minutes later. Thomas Haessler put the Germans
in front after 56 minutes and Klinsmann added a penalty in 76 minutes.
The Bulgarians qualified as runners-up, although other earlier results in their
group had already made sure they reached the finals before kick-off.
The Danes, who finished second in Group 2 behind Spain, made sure their
runners-up record was good enough to be among the six best second-placed teams
and avoid a play-off next month for the remaining finals' berth.
Real Madrid's Michael Laudrup was among the Danish scorers as was Sevilla's
Davor Suker for Croatia in their away match against neighbours Slovenia.
Croatia were another team to have qualified before they defeated Slovenia by
2-1 in Ljubljana, other results ensuring that if they ended the night only as
runners-up in Group 4, in which Italy also won, defeatingLithuania 4-0, their
record was good enough to avoid the play-off. Italy's goals all came in the
second half through a Gianfranco Zola hat trick following an own goal.
Results in Scotland's Group 8 went much as expected.
Greece defeated the Faroe Islands 5-0 at home in Iraklion with a second-half
rush of goals starting in 58 minutes through Alexis Alexandris. Themistocles
Nikolaides in 62, Nikos Mahlas (66), George Gonis (75), and Vassilis Tsartas
(80) completed the rout.
In Moscow, Russia maintained their top form, defeating Finland 3-1. The
Russians went ahead through Dmitry Radchenko five minutes before the break, but
the Finns hit back just on half-time through Kim Suominen. However, Vasily
Kulkov after 55 minutes, and Sergei Kiryakov in 70 minutes, gave the home side
a comfortable win.
Over in Limassol, Cyprus shocked Belgium when Narios Agathocleus put them ahead
after 18 minutes in their Group 2 qualifying match. Two minutes later, Marios
Charalambous was sent off, but the Cypriots held out until the sixty-sixth
minute when Gilles de Bilde equalised.
Moldova beat Georgia 3-2 in Group 7 in fog so thick it was almost impossible to
watch.Meanwhile Northern Ireland's amazing 5-3 victory in Group 6 over Austria
at Windsor Park, Belfast, ensured that the Republic of Ireland, despite their
3-0 defeat in Portugal, would be in the finals' play-off match at Anfield on
December 13 against Holland, who defeated Norway 3-0 in Rotterdam, while France
also qualified with a 2-0 Group 1 victory over Israel.
</TEXT>
