<HEADLINE>DAIRY PRODUCTS Unigate lifts income and looks to Europe</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph Table</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975356034</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SINCE becoming chairman of Unigate in March, Ian Martin has transformed the
dairy products group from one performing adequately into one poised to become a
significant player in the European food industry.
Net debt at the end of September amounted to #174m. But that is being
transformed so that Unigate will have cash balances by the year-end of #200m
and perhaps #250m once it sells off its US restaurants business.
That is being achieved through the now completed disposal of the US arm of the
Giltspur exhibition division for #40m and yesterday's decision to sell the 29%
holding in the Nutricia babyfood business in Holland for around #320m.
The actual amount will depend upon the success of the book-building exercise by
SBC Warburg and ABN AMRO.
Dundee-born Mr Martin was the driving force behind Grand Metropolitan's
acquisition of the Pillsbury foods group in the US which also brought in Burger
King. His track record augurs well for Unigate.
In the half-year, pre-tax profits rose 12.5% to #60.4m on turnover 16.9% ahead
at #1043m.
However, doorstep deliveries of milk in England tumbled 18% following upon a
17% decline in the preceding year as the price margin widened against the
supermarket product. The expectation is that it will reach the Scottish level
of 25% in the pretty near future and so Unigate has been cutting back packaging
capacity.
It is hoped that Unigate's supermarket milk margins will improve - they now
take 60% of deliveries - but possibly not too much should be expected.
Divisional profits eased #2m to #16.5m
Much more positive were the fresh food activities. There was a 65% advance in
profits to #24.5m with half the increase due to two French acquisitions which
supply yoghurt and butter-type spreads.
The core St Ivel ranges saw gains in spreads helped by ``Utterly Butterly'' and
in chilled products although the star performance in the division came from
Malton Bacon which found markets across the world as far afield as Japan and
Korea.
The Wincanton fleet distribution subsidiary was effectively flat at #10.6m with
milk haulage a dull spot, offsetting new contract gains from retailers such as
Kwik Save and Courage.
That activity is now a small part of the whole but is regarded as being an
integral part of the group.
One side-effect of the Giltspur deal is that Unigate will lose perhaps #5m of
profits in the current half year.
Full year pre-tax profits seem set to rise from #117m, before a #58.3m
exceptional charge last year, to about #124m.
That would leave the shares at 432p trading at about 11 times earnings which
does seem cheap on operating grounds while not allowing anything for what Mr
Martin will contribute.
The interim dividend has been increased 5.6% to 6.65p. A total of 20p would
produce an attractive 5.8% yield.
