<HEADLINE>Scots economy a picture of Third World health</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ian Bell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<FLAG>diary</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975356036</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GOOD to see Scotland at last claiming its rightful place in the Third World
thanks to the Chunghwa Picture Tube Company of Taiwan - proof, if any were ever
required, that we never really needed Ravenscraig in the first place, and clear
evidence that we should all be bending over backwards to show what a flexible
workforce we are.
After all, what with Motorola's earlier decision to invest $375m in East
Kilbride, the tube deal, promising 3300 new full-time jobs over the next four
years, has attracted international attention. Even our friends in the German
press have had their attention drawn to ``die staatliche schottische
Wirtschaftsfvrderungsgesellschaft Locate in Scotland'', and in the US, not
least, the word is out.
There, Steven Bennett, LIS's director for North America, said in a press
release yesterday: ``These announcements by Motorola and Chunghwa represent the
latest in a number of very significant inward investment successes for Scotland
over the past year and confirm Scotland's position as the leading electronic
location in Europe.''
Very true. But just so that other potential overseas investors are under no
illusions, the release explains: ``Locate in Scotland is the economic
development agency for the Scottish government.''
It would be far too decent of us to fail to add that the release was
``prepared, edited, issued or (sic) circulated by Al Paul Lefton Company, Inc .
. . which is registered with the Department of Justice, Washington, DC, under
the Foreign Agents Registrations Act as an agent of Locate In Scotland''.
Now that's what we call a Wirtschaftsfvrderungsgesellschaft.
Naked ambition
NO DOUBT it's the Scottish Tourist Board's job to become wildly excited over
anything that might conceivably sell the country to visitors. No doubt
Braveheart, Rob Roy, and Ted Danson's forthcoming Loch Ness will be splendid
promotional tools.
We do, however, counsel just a little caution over the STB's apparent
enthusiasm for the Hollywood term ``kilt movies'' in its embrace of the Nessie
flick. As any tourist knows, the kilt may look splendid, but isn't it the case
that all too often there is nothing very much underneath it?
Signs of the times
ON matching blackboards on either side of the entrance to an Edinburgh pub -
``Cocktails #2 . . . Student meals #2.25''.
Let them eat dry martinis?
Gold-plated
ANOTHER in our occasional series of little-known but deeply fascinating facts:
since the first car registration number sale in 1989 #182m has been raised for
the Treasury from 370,000 of the sort of sad citizens who think it the very
height of comedy to have things like 1 PRAT on their bumpers. We know this
because we have to hand the catalogue for a ``public auction of attractive
vehicle registration numbers'' to be held at Glasgow's SECC on Sunday as part
of the Scottish Motor Show. Now this is funny.
Turning to the ``more money than sense'' section we find, for example, that the
guide price for the immortal 9 HA is a mere #3300, that patriots among you can
secure 2 NAT for only #2700, and that for the litigant in your life there is,
at #3200, 200 SUE. The ``special guest'' at the show will be former rugby
captain Gavin Hastings who could, if he wished, be driving around with 15 GAV
for just #2300.
As the organisers explain, ``a strange culture surrounds auctions'', not least
when number plates can often be worth more than the cars on which they are
displayed, but the DVLA - marketing itself as ``DVLA Classic Collection'' -
isn't complaining. You are, however, advised to take along your bank manager
``to stop yourself getting carried away'' by the Ministry of Transport's
``surprisingly reasonable'' prices.
By the way, the show's catalogue (a snip at #7, or 7 WHIT) goes to commendable
lengths to advertise Greater Glasgow, ``Gateway to Scotland'', as ``one of the
most exciting holiday destinations in the United Kingdom''. There are pictures
of the Botanic Gardens, the Royal Concert Hall, the City Chambers, and the
Italian Centre. Funnily enough, however, someone has forgotten to include a
snap of the gorgeous SECC.
One-man ban
MEANWHILE, agonising times for Britain's Euro-Tories struggling with that
unaccustomed experience, a moral dilemma. Thus a press conference, chaired by
Glenys Kinnock, is held in Strasbourg to discuss Ken Wiwa's demands for
sanctions against Shell after the execution of his father. Lord Plum, leader of
the Tory group, and Edward McMillan-Scott, MEP for York, are pressed for their
views.
His lordship hums a bit, then follows it up with a little hawing, only to have
his non-Nigerian gas put at a peep by his trenchant colleague.
Not only does McMillan-Scott support a boycott, he is, he says, already
conducting his own, heroic one-man campaign.
That this might not be the agreed party line is clear from Lord Plum's face. As
the meeting disperses, however, he asks his Tory friend just what he'll do when
he runs out of petrol with only a Shell station in the neighbourhood. No
problem, says, McMillan-Scott; always keep a gallon drum in the boot.
But of what, we wonder. Esso? BP?
Navel manoeuvres
A CLIPPING from the Wall Street Journal is passed to us, and on the principle
that anything good enough for the voice of capitalism is good enough for the
Diary, we offer without comment a report that the number of bellybutton
reconstructions in Japan went up 375% in the past year.
According to the piece, many Japanese have come to believe that ``the navel is
the core of everything about the person''. Or as the president of a Tokyo
hospital put it, ``People want navels that aren't assertive.''
If the Journal is to be believed, the perfect navel is ``vertical, very narrow,
and absolutely symmetrical''. It is also said to be a popular theme in the
Japanese language. For example, a favourite insult among the young is, ``Your
mother has an outie.''
Wonderful people, the Japanese.
IAN BELL
</TEXT>
