<HEADLINE>Punch in new Bond cocktail</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>William Russell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975356037</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WILLIAM RUSSELL finds the new 007 format has a grittier edge, without losing
its sense of fun
MARTIN Campbell is under no illusions. By the end of November he will know
whether he goes down in cinema history as The Man who killed 007. The
little-known Campbell, a New Zealander, who came to Britain in 1966 to work as
a video cameraman, has directed the seventeenth James Bond movie, Goldeneye,
which opens on November 22 with a new Bond, Pierce Brosnan. His track record as
a director, particularly in television, does not make him an obvious choice to
resurrect the cold war spy.
It is six years since the last Bond film, Licence to Kill, starring Timothy
Dalton, and there were genuine fears that 007's day had gone. But Campbell did
direct that highly regarded television political thriller Edge of Darkness, and
maybe it was that which led to his selection. Since then he has worked mainly
in America and most of his films have not crossed the Atlantic.
The problem for Bond - and Campbell - is that in those six years new heroes and
new styles of action film have emerged. Arnold Schwarzeneggar and Bruce Willis
have taken over as the role model for invincible heroes, especially when it
comes to spectacular stunts. Another pre-production problem was that the
former's hugely successful True Lies proved remarkably similar to the plans the
Bond people had for Goldeneye. A long hard look followed.
The 15-minute clip of scenes from the film - it is still being edited - which I
have seen reveals that Brosnan is second to none, or possibly only Connery,
when it comes to wearing a dinner jacket. The Irish man has the style and
handles the double entendres with a delicacy to match that shown by Roger Moore.
The fight scenes have been spectacularly staged; there is a bungee jump which
takes the breath away and will have the Die Hard people wondering why they did
not think of it first, and a chase through the streets, canals and buildings of
St Petersburg with Bond in a Russian tank, which is something completely new.
The old ingredients are also there. The luscious Bond women are played by
foreign actresses nobody has heard of, and, judging by past experience, may
never do again, while the supporting villains are also played by continental
heavies.
The principal villain, 006, a renegade British agent called Trevelyan, is
played by the blonde, smooth, Nordic Sean Bean, a perfect counterpart to
Brosnan's swarthy, hirsute Celt. As for M, she is played by Dame Judi Dench,
and it looks inspired casting. The scene I saw in which she tells 007 just what
she thinks of him is splendidly funny as she gets across the point that for her
he is a macho male dinosaur whose day is over. If the late Bernard Lee was
irreplaceable, and he was, then this is the way to replace him.
How did Campbell tackle such a sacred bull of a movie hero? ``You just grit
your teeth and get on with it,'' he said. ``Because we had a new Bond we could
start again, and that was good. The action is tougher and grittier than in
previous Bond films and it is also much faster paced, but there are still
plenty of groan lines - you don't want to tamper with those, they are part of
the tradition - and Pierce was made for the role. The suggestion that it might
have gone to Mel Gibson is rubbish. Pierce was always going to be Bond. He was
going to play him before but could not for contractual reasons. I looked at the
tests he made then, and he seemed too young, but now he is just right.''
Campbell said he had devised most of the stunts, especially the tank chase, and
had found the Russians in St Petersburg, where it was shot, extremely helpful
and efficient.
``The final fight between Bond and Trevelyan is pretty tough and the actors did
it all, except for one shot,'' he said. ``I think the series could have died a
natural death after the last Dalton film, and yes, I could go down as the man
who killed James Bond. We will have to wait and see.''
Among the villains are two Scots, Robbie Coltrane, sporting a ludicrous Scots
Russian accent, as a former KGB boss turned arms dealer, and Alan Cumming as
Boris, a crooked computer operator, while American actor Joe Don Baker appears
as a CIA man. He was in the fifteenth Bond film, The Living Daylights, playing
one of the villains, which just goes to show anything is possible in movies. As
for the title song, composed by Bono of U2, it will be sung by Tina Turner.
All the indications are that this time the Bond cocktail has been both shaken
and stirred. But Campbell is not banking on making the eighteenth Bond movie
just yet.
</TEXT>
