<HEADLINE>New crew takes the helm</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Bill Knox</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975356038</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The fresh management structure
is seen as building on the strength
of what existed before, while continuing
the high standards of quality
CREATED by the restructuring of the Henry Boot construction group and
inheriting an already established role as one of the leaders in the Scottish
construction industry, the new Henry Boot Scotland Division takes over, led by
a new team and reorganised in ways which they believe will make for a stronger
position in the highly competitive industry.
``We are also determined to continue the award-winning quality service for
which the company is renowned,'' said James Andrew, who has been appointed
divisional director for Scotland under the restructuring programme.
``Our basic code is to ensure that each contract is delivered on time, to
budget, and complying with our client's specified requirements. At the moment
this is an ever changing marketplace, but we do see green shoots of recovery
and a sense of more activity.
``We are well positioned to take advantage of that, particularly because as the
Scottish division, we have a broad base for activities.'' The established Henry
Boot office in Glasgow will continue to control all the new division's building
and civil engineering projects in Scotland.
``Our immediate aims are established,'' said James Andrew. ``Our new team have
set clear goals for management to achieve, and will measure progress towards
these goals. We have plans to further invest in staff, computerisation and
training - it amounts to providing the correct means to allow the various
disciplines within the business to operate as effectively and as efficiently as
possible.
``That in turn will help towards providing a quality service to the contract
sites, and in turn help them to achieve their project commitments to clients.''
The new Henry Boot structure, decided on by company managing director John
Burbidge, brought together all the group's previous UK contracting operations
carried out by Henry Boot Construction Ltd and Henry Boot Scotland Ltd.
The new company, Henry Boot Construction (UK) Ltd, merges contracting
activities and completes overall restructuring which began in l994.
The Scottish division, led by James Andrew, has already met a welcome from many
existing clients and from new inquiries. The fresh management structure is seen
as building on the strength of what existed before, while continuing the high
standards of quality.
``Our approach to quality takes many forms,'' said the Scottish division's
marketing manager, Andrew Aitken. ``Currently, for instance, we are working
towards achieving ISO 9000 quality accreditation. We are further strengthening
our existing very strong company training policy. We believe in training, we
invest in it, and we have eight training centres throughout Scotland for the
provision of training to the industry.
``We train Henry Boot staff and site personnel in a wide variety of operations
including machinery and safety. We also give training in various skills at
management level.'' The new Scottish division, autonomous in its activities, is
initially expected to be responsible for around 25% of the group's turnover,
then will grow from there as the company grows.
Its activities cover a very wide spectrum from main line building to housing
stock refurbishment for local authorities and housing associations. Special
projects come under the banner of ``design and construct'' and other
procurement methods, and can include management contracting. Civil engineering
projects are carried out under the banner of design and construct or as
traditional contracts.
Henry Boot activities in Scotland range from road building to major water
plants, from defence contracts to new hospitals, from the special skills
required in refurbishment of major buildings to new general building.
``It is difficult to talk about ``special strength'' areas,'' said Andrew
Aitken. ``But we have a wide range of repeat clients who recognise that our
skills and experience include both major engineering work and major, and often
complex, refurbishing in all its forms. That has been amply recognised by the
many top industry awards that we have received.'' Like Scottish divisional
director James Andrew, he sees many practical benefits from the new divisional
structure.
``In marketing terms we are now stronger than ever. As part of a bigger group
we can apply for larger contracts. In addition, we now have a much stronger
financial base and we also have all the benefits of day to day communications
of a larger organisation. Service departments are centralised in terms of man
management, and the people we have here at Scottish headquarters are committed
to the sites.
``In the same way, our decision to instal a more advanced computer system is
already adding more rationalised strength to the organisation - and the
resulting integration of the various disciplines providing service to the sites
brings about savings in time and cost and also brings improved efficiency.
``We achieve more time to study information, to identify and deal with
potential problems - all of which is to our clients' benefit.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000061</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000061</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scottish team restructured</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Bill Knox</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975356039</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HEADED by Scottish division director James Andrew, the new Henry Boot team for
Scotland is drawn from existing staff and backed by a skilled and long-serving
workforce.
Colin J Carrick is divisional surveyor, with Andrew Aitken as divisional
marketing manager. Other key members of the team include G K Smelt, special
projects manager, design and build; S Milligan, contracts manager, civil
engineering; J H Ferguson, contracts manager, new build construction; and A
Herd, contracts manager, housing and refurbishment.
When Henry Boot, the founder of the company, died in 1931 it was taken over by
Charles, the eldest of his three sons. Family control has continued and today
non-executive chairman is David Henry Boot, and another family member, Edward
James Boot, is group managing director.
</TEXT>
