<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Track record builds on future success</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975356040</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PROVEN all-round skills lie behind Henry Boot Scotland being awarded a #20.5m
contract by Central Regional Council for a new water treatment plant which has
begun building at Broadside in Denny, Stirlingshire.
The contract is for the design, construction and commissioning of the treatment
works, which will take thirty months to complete.
``The contract is to be undertaken in partnership with PWT Projects Ltd, a
subsidiary of Thames Water, which will provide technology to meet the very
latest European drinking water standards,'' said John Burbidge, managing
director of Henry Boot Construction (UK) Ltd.
``This award follows the recent completion of a design and build contract for
water treatment works at Overton in Strathclyde, which was also carried out in
conjunction with PWT.'' The Overton contract involved a #l2.5m work project.
The construction of water treatment plant on the scale of what is now being
created at Broadside is a considerable project by any standards within the
industry.
To be known as the Carron Valley Water Treatment Works, it will represent the
largest investment in water services ever made by Central region. Work started
after a commemoration turf cutting ceremony in the summer.
``The plant will use the latest technology to play its part in delivering the
220 million litres of water used in Central region every day,'' said Andrew
Aitken, who is marketing manager for Henry Boot, Scotland. ``Completion of work
is due in spring l998, and the new plant will make the most of the vast water
resources available within the Carron Valley.''
It is a project which has been developed on an ``open book'' tender basis but
operated as a lump sum priced performance contract. A technical description is
that the new water treatment process will consist of chemical flocculation,
dissolved air flotation, rapid gravity filtration, disinfectant by chlorine
gas, and pH adjustment. Allowance has been made for future provision of
ozonation and carbon filtration.
Central Region Water Services say the plant will be fully automated to treat
l25 million litres of water each day. Hi-tech treatment methods will meet the
latest water standards, improving quality and reducing any likelihood of supply
failures to consumers.
It will be a treatment works which will have all the cleanliness and working
environment of a food factory. Enclosed process tanks will reduce the effects
of bad weather, while fully integrated controls with central monitoring will
carry out continuous standards checks. It will also have improved chemical
handling, dosing and washwater facilities, all vital in a modern, efficient
treatment works.
The water treatment plant buildings and operating areas are styled and
landscaped to blend into the surrounding countryside. Similarly, work areas
within the long, relatively low and unobtrusive buildings are bright and
spacious.
The location is to the east of Carron Valley Reservoir on the B8l8, a few miles
from Denny and Dunipace and the M80.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
