<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The quick fix is no cure for Bosnia's wounds</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Mladen Grbin</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975356041</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
As the land brokers strive to negotiate a deal for Bosnia, Mladen Grbin argues
that any `peace' settlement will be hollow, and probably temporary
WHETHER one travels across Bosnia-Hercegovina by negotiating the tortuous local
roads, or by a quick flight in a UN helicopter, the massive devastation of the
towns and villages evident everywhere always impresses. The charred, roofless
remains of the homes of the Bosnian communities are a constant reminder of
three and a half years of war which has now ground to an uneasy halt.
In Tuzla, the well meaning and the curious descend on the people with views and
agendas which at times seem remote from the reality of life in war-torn Bosnia.
Writer and journalist David Rieff strongly attacked the UN in Bosnia; Michael
Ignatieff, after chairing a BBC-like late night show in the hotel bar which
delved into the higher levels of intellectual exercise, concluded that perhaps
we ought to do what we are best at...... some hard drinking.
American playwright Susan Sonntag concluded that Bosnia-Hercegovina is dead and
three or four segregated communities will rise into more or less independent
mini-states, fast becoming clients to the neighbouring states of Croatia and
Serbia proper.
Most outside observers, perhaps inevitably, adopt a tourist's view of the
recent history of the Bosnian people and a somewhat fatalistic resignation over
their future.
Fikreta Sijercic, president of the Independent Trade Unions in Tuzla, maintains
the future of her country lies in the recognition that the three constituent
peoples have no option but to continue living together.
She insists the paramount ingredient for peace is the reconstruction of her
country, whereby economic activity will divert the adversarial position of the
people, instead of concentrating their efforts towards a common goal, namely
individual and collective prosperity.
Fikreta is also in agreement with Tadeusz Mazowiecki, the ex-UN Rapporteur for
Human Rights in former Yugoslavia, when he says the precondition for peace in
Bosnia and Hercegovina rests on these imperatives: that the perpetrators of war
crimes are brought to justice, that the people forcibly removed from their
homes have an unconditional right to return, and that the state of Bosnia and
Hercegovina must remain independent, sovereign, and united.
The clear message here is that the phoenix must rise out of the ashes, but not
without a massive injection of capital, and there is already, by some
estimates, a figure of $12bn being suggested for this purpose.
The latest US initiative, where the three heads of states are quarantined at
the airbase in Dayton, Ohio, is billed as the last chance to achieve a peace
settlement. And yet, are ``peace'' and ``peace settlement'' one and the same
thing?
The Americans want a quick fix, while the Europeans are in a quandary as to
whether they want it to succeed or fail. If the US initiative nominally
succeeds, it points to the failure of Europe. If it fails, the problem will end
up back in Europe's lap.
Croatian President Tudjman's concern, in the wake of the election, with a
somewhat lesser mandate than he had hoped from his electorate, is to support
the extension of Croatian interests by securing the position of the Bosnian
Croats, particularly those in Hercegovina.
This interest lies in the strategic importance of the security of the Croatian
borders. And for this, he is prepared to deal and agree with Milosevic on the
division of Bosnia and Hercegovina, at the same time supporting the Bosnian
Muslim/Croat Federation, in recompense for American support in brokering the
agreement between the two in March 1994.
The agenda of Serbian President Milosevic, the prime mover behind all the wars
in former Yugoslavia, is to minimise retribution from the international
community in the light of his role in the conflict.
To this end, he will demand the lifting of economic sanctions on Serbia, and
some formula which will pacify the Bosnian Serbs, in order to secure his own
constituency in Serbia in the name of the interests of all Serbs in the region.
He will, equally, be preparing to strike a deal with Tudjman, even if it means
relinquishing, for the time being, his claim on the territories occupied by the
Croatian Serbs and the Serb army in Eastern Slavonia. They will both argue for
the partition of Bosnia-Hercegovina, and will have direct input in agreeing its
future constitutional arrangements.
This fact, in itself, augurs ill for those who see their future in a united
Bosnian state. President Alija Izetbegovic in this sense is in the most
difficult position, not only because he is outnumbered in this scenario, but
because the future constitutional arrangement of Bosnia depends on the
agreement of the Croatian and Serbian delegations.
If Tudjman and Milosevic prevail, the vision of a multi-ethnic,
multi-religious, secular state of Bosnia-Hercegovina will be destroyed, and
replaced by a small Bosnian Muslim mini-state which, in turn, would very soon
become unviable through pressure from its neighbours.
The problem of achieving a sustainable peace for the people of
Bosnia-Hercegovina may, ironically, lie in the premature cessation of the war
activities which froze ill-gotten territorial gains through expulsion, murder,
the besieging of cities, and mass rape.
It will be difficult to resolve the issue, due to the lack of clear victory of
any of the sides in the conflict.
The terms of peace will be determined as much by the aggressor as by the victim.
Inevitably, the peace settlement will contain the potential for a continuation
of hostilities, whereby peace will mean merely a temporary suspension, under
the pressure of the international community for a quick fix.
A sustainable peace can only be achieved if the terms are dictated by the
winner. A just peace can only be achieved if its terms are dictated by the
victims of the aggression. Since the international community has decided to be
a mediator and not a defender of fundamental principles, the peace will be
hollow and temporary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
