<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rosalind Cash</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975356042</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ROSALIND Cash, a television and movie actress best known for her role as the
matriarch Mary Mae Ward on the TV soap opera General Hospital, has died at the
age of 56. The Los Angeles Times gave cancer as the cause.
Cash, who was born in Atlantic City, New Jersey, was nominated for an Emmy for
her work in the PBS production of Go Tell It On The Mountain, and was a
familiar face on daytime television with her recurring role in ABC's General
Hospital.
She also appeared in the mini-series The Guyana Tragedy: The Story of Jim
Jones, and she guest-starred in several series, including Barney Miller, Kojak,
The Mary Tyler Moore Show, China Beach, Thirtysomething, Cagney and Lacey, and
Hill Street Blues. Cash's movie credits included The Omega Man, opposite
Charlton Heston, the comedy Uptown Saturday Night, and The Adventures of
Buckaroo Banzai.
In 1987, she won the Black American Cinema Society's Phoenix Award for
achievement in motion pictures and was inducted into the Black Film-makers'
Hall of Fame in 1992.
Her acting career began after college when she was a founding member of the
Negro Ensemble Company in New York. She made her debut on Broadway in 1966 in
The Wayward Stork and appeared on the London stage opposite Glenda Jackson in
The Class of Miss MacMichael. Cash also wrote poetry and played the guitar and
shared a home in southern California with multimedia artist Felipe.
</TEXT>
