<HEADLINE>Covenant fund boost for clinic</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ann Shaw</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975356043</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n HERE'S a good news story: under a covenant scheme a businessman is donating
#100 each year for the next seven years to The Herald Foundation for Women's
Health, writes ANN SHAW. Like many of the donors to the fund he does not wish
any personal publicity but is keen to support the foundation because of its
importance in improving the quality of women's lives.
Donating to the fund via a covenant could be the ideal way for the business
community to support the innovative clinic at Glasgow's Royal Infirmary and the
wider aims of the project. These are to raise the consciousness of every woman
about her state of health and reduce Scotland's shocking statistics for
illnesses which particularly afflict women's lives.
Such a covenant maximises tax benefits to the charity and to the individual
donor. For every #100 pledged by the donor only #75 is handed over while the
remaining #25 is recouped by the charity from Inland Revenue.
Those wishing to take out a covenant, which must be for a minimum of three
years, should contact the Herald Foundation for Women's Health in order to
obtain the necessary form.
Once funds are raised, the clinic devoted to gynaecological and related
problems, will operate under the NHS. It will also commemorate this year's
bicentenary of the Royal, internationally recognised as one of the most
distinguished teaching hospitals in Britain. It will aim to be a centre of
excellence, staffed by attentive personnel who will counsel and ease women's
apprehension about this particularly sensitive area of medicine, and provide an
informed investigation and treatment management.
For the convenience of working women, an early-evening clinic is being
considered.
The cost of setting up and running the clinic will be #100,000 and if each
woman reader of The Herald donated just #1, the total would easily exceed the
financial goal.
Please consider making a donation to the Foundation today, whether you are an
individual reader or a company representative. All contributions, no matter how
small, will be gratefully received.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
