<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975356044</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
George Collie, lawyer; born April 1, 1909, died November 9, 1995
LAWYER George Collie started and finished his legal career in the leading
Aberdeen law firm of James and George Collie, which was established by his
family in the mid-nineteenth century.
He was educated at Aberdeen Grammar School and Aberdeen University before
serving his law apprenticeship, first in the family business and then at
Wilson, Caldwell and Tait, Writers, of Glasgow. He then worked as an assistant
to the Glasgow writers, Robertson, Chalmers and Auld, before returning to James
and George Collie in 1934. He remained there until his retirement in 1981. For
the past 20 years he was senior partner.
During the war he served with the 51st (Highland) Division RASC and was
severely wounded by a shell at St Valery en Caux in France in June 1940. In
August 1942, while still a patient in hospital in Paris, he escaped and
returned to Britain via the Pyrenees into Spain. That year he received a
military MBE for information he provided to the War Office and he also became
honorary colonel of the 51st (Highland) Division.
Mr Collie was a former chairman of the board of management of Aberdeen Special
Hospitals and an honorary sheriff of Grampian, Highlands and Islands at
Aberdeen and Stonehaven. He was also a former president of South Aberdeen
Conservative and Unionist Association for several years and chairman of
Aberdeen University Press. In 1964 he was made a CBE for his public and
political services.
``Geoff Collie was undoubtedly one of the most highly respected members of the
legal profession in Aberdeen,'' said Mr Alex Buchan, senior partner of James
and George Collie. ``He was a partner of the firm for 47 years and I was
privileged to be his partner for 15 of these years. He was a fine solicitor who
was immensely popular with his partners, staff, and clients and after retiring
in 1981 at the age of 73 he maintained an active interest in the business which
he had built up over many years.
``His other interests were diverse and included much charitable work. He will
be sadly missed by so many people in different walks of life.''
Mr Collie, of Morkeu, Cults, is survived by his wife Margery and their two
sons, George and James.
GRAEME SMITH
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000067</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000067</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Why is there no Scottish dream?</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975356045</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE sentiment expressed in Kirsty Scott's article needs to be written into a
dirge of a new Scottish National Anthem (November 10). Then it should be played
at hundreds of megawatts at all national events till more of us are stirred out
of our timidity and apathy.
I live opposite the most prominent feature of this bonny town whereon stands a
large stone tower built by local merchants in the last century and then
dedicated to Lord Nelson. Throughout the summer the Union Flag flies proudly on
top each afternoon signifying that the tower is open to visitors. On November
30, as a special treat, the Saltire gets an airing.
Two months ago I decided that it was not unreasonable that the Saltire should
also get a regular airing. I wrote to the community council expressing that
view and, in what I felt was a spirit of good British compromise, suggested
that the Union Flag should continue to be flown on the anniversaries of Lord
Nelson's battles and on all significant British national anniversaries.
The community council discussed the issue and the local people were asked to
air their views on the matter. A total of 33 people responded, 27 agreed with
my proposal. The local area population is some 17,000.
Attitudes on the council are quite revealing. Three members supported the
suggestion believing the request to be reasonable. Of the remainder one thought
the request ``political'', one thought it ``sad'' because the Union Flag
represents all of Britain, and one feared the nationalistic aspect and reminded
colleagues of the large English population in the area who might be offended.
I now fear that we are probably the only unoccupied country in history
reluctant to fly its flag.
Kirsty Scott asks: ``Why is there no Scottish dream?'' Perhaps because we would
need to wake up to implement it.
W Hercus,
Mayfield, Victoria Road,
Forres.
</TEXT>
