<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Time for society to put on a brave face</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Victoria Freedman</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975356046</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Victoria Freedman explains how community repulsion and intolerance for facially
disfigured people adds to their emotional trauma
SUSAN DUNCAN always walks with her head held high. It is a determined, defiant
gesture, done to prove her rightful place in society. It is also very brave
because many people would rather not look at her at all. For Duncan, 32, from
Gourock, is facially disfigured, one of thousands who endure a daily dose of
cruelty, from comments to overt disgust, if they dare show themselves.
``There is plenty of evidence to suggest that people do not find it easy or
comfortable to interact with somebody who is different in that sort of way,''
says Halla Beloff, a social psychologist at Edinburgh University.
``It is clearly disappointing,'' says Beloff. ``It means that people who are
facially disfigured have to get past the negative experiences in terms of first
impressions, which do count, and then learn to be more socially skilled than
anybody else, just to make others less uncomfortable.''
Duncan is an expert, but she admits it requires enormous inner strength and
positive thinking. She has also had years of practice. A cancerous tumour in
her cheekbone was treated with radiotherapy when she was four months old, and
then removed when she was two, taking half her palate, top jaw and bones with
it.
As a result of the radiotherapy, she lost the sight in her left eye, hearing in
that ear and only reached a height of 4ft 6in. Since her late teens she has
had, on average, three plastic surgery operations a year.
``I've just had to accept that no matter how much surgery I have, I can never,
ever, be like other people. So I've had to say to myself, make the most of what
you have, build up your strengths. Yes, people will always judge by appearance,
even I do it, but if they take time to get to know you, they will see your
other qualities, such as your personality.'' She smiles: ``And a sense of
humour.''
That Duncan works to retain such a positive attitude and give her all in making
others feel more comfortable is quite remarkable considering her daily
experience. People stare, or even jump away in disgust. Some have commented
that she should not be allowed out. She also experiences insensitivity and
impatience from people who cannot understand her speech, discrimination from
employers - she is now at college studying multi-media computing - and a
general lack of imaginaton that she might have ambitions, feelings and
interests like anyone else.
She acknowledges that those who are disfigured later in life may find their
sudden transformation, physically and socially, too much to bear.
Valerie Lobban, from Edinburgh, who has been hit by attacks of facial paralysis
for the past six years, says she understands perfectly why many people wish to
hide themselves away.
``I was totally unprepared for the reaction of others. It's only that I've been
very determined not to let it get the better of me that I keep going,'' she
says. ``Compared with a lot of people, my problem is very minor.''
And even if those who are facially disfigured do manage to accept their new
face and regain their confidence, sometimes their friends or even loved ones
cannot cope.
Doreen Trust, from the Disfigurement Guidance Centre in Fife, a charity that
has funded several laser clinics in the UK to treat disfigurement, tells of a
nurse whose husband was in a car acccident.
``You'd think she'd be accustomed to suffering, deformity and misfortune, but
she found it increasingly hard to cope with the public reaction and would not
go outside with him. It put an enormous strain on the marriage.''
One couple she knows is suffering after the birth of a baby with a strawberry
birthmark; the mother refuses to take her baby out.
While Duncan does her utmost to make others feel comfortable, she believes it
is time we put in a little effort as well.
``Try to look us in the eye,'' she asks. ``I know that's difficult but there's
nothing worse than trying to talk to somebody who is looking everywhere. Most
of all I just want to be treated as a normal person.''
Certainly if the public reaction was more sympathetic, it would make the
private difficulties more bearable.
``I get up every morning and look in the mirror - I don't like this face,''
says Duncan. ``I don't like being facially disfigured. I want to be like
everyone else. It would be nice to be like my sister, who is lovely looking. I
would love to have a boyfriend, to get married. I'm fortunate that I realise I
can't change the past and have to get on with it, but there are times when I
cry buckets,'' she says.
n Changing Faces provides free help, advice and information for anyone who has
a facial disfigurement. Telephone 0171 706 4232.
n Susan Duncan is the Scottish representative of Let's Face It, a support
network. Write to PO Box 4000, Glasgow G12 9JQ.
n The Disfigurement Guidance Centre provides information about laser treatment.
Telephone 01337 870281.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000069</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000069</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hollywood clouds with silver linings</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>William Russell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>review</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975356047</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE are some films which are truly terrible, yet offer wonderful
entertainment, and Alfonso Arau's A Walk in the Clouds is a vintage example.
The name Douglas Sirk springs to mind. He was the Hollywood director who used
to make lush dramas starring people who could not act, like Lana Turner,
filming them in lurid technicolour and coming up with the goods, a film which
kept audiences watching from beginning to end.
Arau's film is about a young GI, Paul Sutton (Keanu Reeves) who returns from
the war to find his bride of two days is not the girl he thought she was. He
has written to her every day, setting out his hopes and dreams, but she,
although she has kept the letters, has not read them. She insists he go back to
his old job selling chocolate and make a success of it, so off on the road he
goes.
On his travels he meets pretty Victoria Aragon (Aitana Sanchez-Gijon) who is
returning reluctantly to the family hacienda in the Napa Valley. She confesses
that while at college she became pregnant by a man who has not stood by her,
and Daddy (Giancarlo Gianni) will have her hide for garters - or words to that
effect. Being a gentleman, Paul suggests he impersonate her husband for a day,
thus pacifying Daddy, and then, to prove he is a rotter, abandoning her the
following morning. But, of course, it does not work out like that. Daddy hates
Paul, but the rest of the family, including the patriarch Don Pedro (Anthony
Quinn doing his Zorba the Mex act) think he is wonderful, especially after he
helps them save the grape harvest from a sudden frost.
One thing leads to another, the deception is revealed, and the grape harvest is
burnt in an accidental fire. It is about as slender a plot as could be devised,
which has been filmed by Arau in lurid technicolour - maybe the fact that Paul
is a chocolate salesman inspired him, because chocolate box top is the overall
impression one gets of the scenery - and with lots of cardboard sets.
As for the acting, Keanu is a male version of Lana, as animated as a
cigar-store Indian, but beautiful to look at, especially when he recycles one
of his vests from Speed, about all one should ask of a matinee idol; Quinn is
embarrassingly ethnic; Gianni emotes like crazy; and Sanchez-Gijon is even more
gorgeous than Keanu.
Arau made the enchanting Like Water for Chocolate, a book which should have
been unfilmable, and his Hollywood debut by the standards it set is a disaster.
On its own recognisances, however, it is hugely entertaining, and I would feel
the same about it if I had paid to see it, should you ask. They should have
called it The Grapes of Slush. I loved every ludicrous moment of it.
The same could not be said, however, about Tommy Boy, one of those brain-dead
comedies best viewed after several pints of lager and a curry which Hollywood
makes from time to time. Indeed Keanu has starred in a couple in his day.
This one introduces Chris Farley, who is fat, as Tommy Callaghan, dumb heir to
an auto parts company, and David Spade as Richard Hayden, his best friend and
the firm nerd. As a double act they have no charisma, no comic timing, and make
Abbot and Costello look like Laurel and Hardy.
When Big Tom Callaghan (Brian Dennehy) dies he leaves behind his new wife (Bo
Derek, who is now a 10 minus) and her alleged son, really her lover (Rob Lowe).
They are after Daddy's money, and a big-time auto parts company, headed by Dan
Aykroyd, is after the Callaghan firm. To save it from being taken over the two
dolts go on the road trying to drum up orders for Callaghan's new super brake
pads.
The slapstick is inept, the verbal humour crass, and the duo unlovable. But
there is one inspired sequence in which they run over an elk with their car,
pick up the corpse and put it in the back seat, except that it is not a corpse.
The animal revives and promptly destroys the vehicle. That was very funny.
Mathieu Kassovitz's La Haine is a powerful story about a day in the lives of
three Parisian teenagers, a Jew, an Arab, and a coloured boy. The friendship is
questionable, because ethnic minorities tend to gang together, but it works in
the context of the film. They live in a slum suburb. There has been a riot, and
one of their friends is in hospital after being beaten up by the police.
They cross Paris to collect a debt from a friend who lives in a smart district,
fall foul of the police, two of them, the coloured boy and the Arab, are taken
for questioning and roughed up, the third runs off. They miss their last train
home, and the film follows their journey across Paris until as dawn breaks they
make it.
The film is a chilling indictment of police brutality, of what happens when
police treat people as suspicious when they are only going about their
business. The boys' problem is that one of them has a policeman's gun, which he
collected during the riot, and they cannot be found with it in their possession.
It all ends badly, as one would expect. What keeps it going is the furious pace
Kassovitz sets and the performances of the three boys, Vincent Cassel, Hunert
Kounde, and Said Taghmaqui. They fizz with energy, mostly misdirected, keep
getting on one another's nerves, throwing out furious challenges to anybody who
seems to have crossed them, and generally behaving in the most pig-headed
manner. If it were not for the police they would be their own worst enemies.
But they are not stupid, just rash and young.
Kassovitz offers no answers, and the story used at the end to set the moral
tone of the film about the man who has jumped off the roof of a skyscraper
muttering ``so far, so good'' as he passes each floor is old and obvious. But
even if he is not saying anything new he is saying it for his generation.
Roland Joffe's The Scarlet Letter, starring Demi Moore, Gary Oldman, and Robert
Duval, about the New England settler woman taken in adultery and forced to wear
the red-letter brand on her clothes, also opens this week, but Entertainment,
its distributors have not shown it to the press. They say they did not have a
print. Draw your own conclusions.
A Walk in the Clouds (PG) directed by Alfonso Arau.
Tommy Boy (PG) directed by Peter Segal.
The Scarlet Letter (15) directed by Roland Joffe.
