<HEADLINE>A measure of fitness</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Dr David DElvin</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>man alive</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975356048</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Q. My wife believes a man's waist measurement should be less than his hip
measurement. Is this right?A. Yes - there's some evidence that you're more
likely to live longer if the circumference of your waist is less than that of
your bottom. I'd advise all Man Alive readers to check these two figures with a
tape measure. If the waist reading is the bigger one, then for heaven's sake
start slimming!
Q. I have just been told that I have piles. Does this mean I've got to have an
operation?
A. No! About one in every five men suffers from piles at some stage in life.
Clearly, if all these guys had to be operated on, the National Health Service
would collapse . . .
Often known as ``haemorrhoids'', they are actually swollen veins, just inside
the bottom. In fact, they look very like the swollen, twisted veins which you
see on many people's legs. Nobody really knows what causes them, but surgeons
tend to blame lack of fibre in the diet, and ``straining'' while sitting on the
loo.
Fortunately, a lot of the time piles produce no symptoms at all. Usually, the
earliest sign that they're there is slight bleeding on the toilet paper. But,
as I've said in this column before, a man should never assume that rectal
bleeding is ``just due to piles''. Always have it checked out by a doctor.
Other possible symptoms include an odd sense of ``fullness'' in the rectum, and
also discomfort and discharge. And if piles get worse, they will often
``prolapse'' - which means come out through the anus.
OK, so what about treatment? Thank heavens, the majority of cases of piles can
be kept in check by very simple measures. These include using rectal creams or
ointments, prescribed by your GP. I strongly recommend anti-haemorrhoid
suppositories which can be exceedingly soothing!
Also, your doc will probably recommend taking action - for instance, by change
of diet - to ensure you don't get constipated. The idea of this is to prevent
you from straining while you're having a bowel action.
If these straightforward measures don't work, then usually the next thing is to
try injecting the haemorrhoids. Though this sounds alarming, it's actually
pretty painless. The surgeon just puts a needle into the anus, and injects some
special fluid which makes the piles ``shrink up''.
Only if haemorrhoids are really troublesome is an operation necessary. The most
common operation involves cutting the piles out. Another possible procedure is
to stretch the anus by putting two hands into it. I hasten to add that this is
done under general anaesthetic; results are generally good.
Q. My wife wants me to stop drinking beer and go on to short drinks instead.
She thinks that this would be better for me. Is that true?
A. Some people have this idea that if a drink is ``small'', it must somehow be
less harmful - or less fattening. But it just isn't true. Maybe your wife is
concerned that your alcohol intake is getting a bit too high? I suggest you
talk this over with her.
Q. Do you think it's OK to go into the office when one has a cold or 'flu?
A. I do not! You stand an excellent chance of giving the germ to the folk you
work with - or perhaps customers. A new survey suggests that Scotsmen are
particularly likely to ``struggle bravely on'' and go into work when they have
colds. My advice is: stay at home until you're better.
Q. You recently mentioned ``premature ejaculation'' in The Herald. I have
suffered from this for many years, and my wife wants to drag me along to a
Family Planning Clinic for counselling. But I cannot face that.
I have heard rumours that there is a drug which my own doctor could prescribe
for me. True?
A. Yes, recent medical research has shown that some men who reach orgasm far
too soon can be helped by judicious use of certain anti-depressant drugs - even
though they are not depressed.
Although it's still very early days, it does seem as though these drugs manage
to have some sort of ``dampening'' effect on the male nervous system - thus
making the chap less explosively triggered. The drugs which have given
promising results are: Anafranil, Seroxat, Lustral (a curiously appropriate
name in this context) - and the famous Prozac.
But I can't emphasise strongly enough that all these powerful medications
frequently have side-effects. So whether your GP will prescribe them for you is
not certain! However, for the sake of your marriage it's well worth going to
see him/her and talking it over. Good luck!
Q. I'm a pipe smoker, and I've had a wee sore place on my lip for several
weeks. Is this anything to bother about?
A. Will you please get down to your doctor's this morning if possible? To be
blunt, pipe smoking is a common cause of lip cancer. The classic way in which
this appears is a sore or raw place on the lip, which fails to clear up. I hope
this is just a benign lesion, but you must get it checked out now.
Q. I hope you don't mind a woman writing to your ``all male'' column, but I am
rather concerned about my husband. My worry is this. For some reason, he always
insists on going to a female doctor rather than a male one when he has to have
an examination. He avoids men doctors wherever possible.
Why is he like this? Do you think he ``fancies'' women in white coats or
something?
A. I doubt it, ma'am. A more likely explanation is this. A number of men aren't
very happy at having their intimate bits examined by another chap - because
deep down, they dislike the sexual implications of one male touching another
male's private parts. So, they pick a woman doc to do the examination.
There's nothing wrong with this; it's just like a sort of shyness, really! So I
reckon you should just respect your man's wishes and leave it at that.
n If you have a query about your health, write to Dr David Delvin at The
Herald, 195 Albion Street, Glasgow G1 1QP. Dr D cannot reply in person, but
will try to respond in this column. Your name will not be published.
</TEXT>
