<HEADLINE>Forgotten fort to see fresh action</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356049</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FORGOTTEN fortress on Orkney is set to become Scotland's latest tourist
attraction.
The fort, built to keep out American warships in the early nineteenth century,
is to be restored and a single-track road widened to enable coach parties to
reach the site.
Next year, a cannon will be mounted atop the 45ft-high, stone-built Martello
tower, near Longhope, on Hoy. It was built after the Americans joined the
French in declaring war on Britain in 1812. In 1922, the Ministry of Defence
sold the site to London-born Mr William Cload, the artilleryman stationed at
the Longhope Battery.
Now, the Government has bought back the buildings from his 75-year-old
grandson, Mr John Cload, who will continue to live in the old officers'
quarters which has been the family's home.
Historic Scotland's island-based team of stonemasons plans to start renovation
work soon.
</TEXT>
