<HEADLINE>Florence Greenberg</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975356050</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FLORENCE Greenberg, a recording industry pioneer who helped discover The
Shirelles, The Kingsmen, and other acts of the 1960s and 1970s, has died at 82
in Hackensack, New Jersey. Greenberg, one of the first women to run a record
company, died after a stroke.
Greenberg headed Scepter for 17 years, developing talent, choosing songs, and
selecting album cover art. Among the hits produced under her label were the
Isley Brothers' Twist and Shout, Louie, Louie by the Kingsmen, Walk on By by
Dionne Warwick, and Raindrops Keep Falling on My Head by B J Thomas.
</TEXT>
