<HEADLINE>Journalist missing  in Haiti</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356051</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Port-au-Prince, Wednesday
A HAITIAN journalist was missing and a group of foreigners sought refuge in a
hospital from demonstrators today in northern Haiti, authorities said.
Evelyn Toussaint, a reporter for Radio VKB in Cap Haitien, was believed to be
in the hands of a hostile crowd after she and a colleague received threats for
citing the names of three people implicated in previous violence, journalists
said.
``It would appear that the crowd is unhappy with comments and statements that
they made,'' UN spokesman Eric Falt said.
``We have brought to the attention of our Pakistani peacekeepers the impact of
this issue on the freedom of the press.''
In nearby Limbe, 16 Americans, three Canadians, one Indian and one Austrian
took cover in a local hospital after demonstrators demanding better public
services set up roadblocks and conducted impromptu weapons searches.
The Haitian capital Port-au-Prince erupted into spontaneous street protests on
Saturday after President Jean-Bertrand Aristide delivered an angry speech at
the funeral of his cousin, slain lawmaker Jean-Hubert Feuille.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
