<HEADLINE>A Season In Hell, Assembly Rooms, Edinburgh</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Mary Brennan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975356052</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Nothing is easy! Pity then
The poet more than other men
THE opening lines of a poem, learnt in childhood, drifted in on me as I watched
Xpress Munich striving to conjure the hectic, random existence of Arthur
Rimbaud who blazed - like a comet wreaking havoc - through the respectable life
and esteemed career of Paul Verlaine.
But which poet to pity? Verlaine - who unhinged his settled routine and almost
lost everything because of his violent attachment to Rimbaud? Or Rimbaud - who
could never fall into step with anyone else, let alone moderate his ideas, his
behaviour, his intense sense of self, even to ease his own situation?
In truth it's hard to decide, since - in this new production - we never really
get close to the spirit of the men or their work.
Whereas their previous piece, Titanic, really did explore what - if any - were
the moral boundaries that existed within an artist's life and the creation of
his work, A Season in Hell seems to stick at sketching in the aura of uproar
that Rimbaud occasioned as a disreputable character, rather than as a radically
unsettling poet.
Unfortunately, the company weren't helped by the boomy acoustic of the space
which swallowed chunks of the text and thereby placed additional stresses on
the physical theatre, the design elements and the back projections - all of
which were nicely judged if taken as indicators of the brittle society that the
youthful iconoclast disrupted.
It's a pity that a more intimate space couldn't have been found within the
Assembly Rooms, because there are indicators that at closer quarters we could
have shared in some of the tensions and conflicts that the piece seeks to
generate.
</TEXT>
