<HEADLINE>Challenge to gain jobs edge</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alf Young</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC> Photograph Graph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975356053</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Alf Young, Economics Editor, talks to industry minister George Kynoch about the
battle to win jobs by selling Scotland to the world
SCOTLAND'S attraction as a location for inward investment will be damaged if
the UK signs up for the social chapter of the Maastricht Treaty, introduces a
minimum wage, and legislates for a tax-raising assembly north of the Border,
claims the Scottish industry minister George Kynoch.
But, in an extended interview with The Herald about the importance of inward
investment to the Scottish economy, the day the Scottish Office confirmed the
Chunghwa Picture Tube company of Taiwan is going ahead with a #260m investment
in Lanarkshire, Mr Kynoch denies that deep divisions in his own party over
Europe could have the same negative effect.
The minister also denies that his claim about the impact of Labour's minimum
wage proposals confirms that some inward investors already here operate
low-wage factories. He did, however, admit that some inward investment jobs
would be lost if the union target of #4.15 an hour for the minimum wage were
enforced.
Mr Kynoch also disputes the oft-heard complaint among indigenous companies that
the Scottish Office devotes too much of its limited industrial budget to luring
inward investors to Scotland. He claims indigenous companies have just as much
access to aid and support. Too many, he argues, are slow to grasp the supply
opportunities inward investment brings.
With the Chunghwa project safely in the bag, and the UK's largest-ever haul of
jobs from a single investment destined for Lanarkshire, Mr Kynoch could be
excused a smile or two of satisfaction. Eight months into the job, he had
played an important personal role encouraging the most senior Chunghwa
executives to favour Scotland.
It hadn't, he insists, been all about waving the biggest cheque book under
Taiwanese noses. ``That irritates me because I know it's not true. Very often
we're in a situation where we can't match what others outwith the UK are able
to offer.
``What we can do is sell the very positive attributes of Scotland,'' he went
on, citing a transport infrastructure now capable of next day delivery in
Europe, a skilled and flexible workforce and one of lowest corporate tax rates
in Europe.
``The financial package is important but it's not necessarily the deciding
factor.''
Scotland remains a competitive location in Europe, he argues, because we have
deliberately positioned ourselves as the ``electronics base for Europe'' and
are not ``shackled'' with the problems of the social chapter.
``Our opposition to a minimum wage is very clear. I think virtually everyone -
I suspect even Tony Blair - accepts that if he was to agree to a minimum wage
at the level the trade unions want of something like #4.15 an hour that it's
going to cost the UK something of the order of two million jobs. That's why
he's not willing to specify the rate.''
But did that, I wondered, also imply an admission that many of the jobs on
offer from inward investors are insecure and low paid, at rates well below that
putative minimum wage figure?
``I saw round Chungwha's factory in Taiwan. You can't possibly say these are
low-wage, low-tech jobs. This is a very hi-tech company. The bulk of our
electronics industry is hi-tech. In all businesses you get a spectrum of skills
from the highly skilled through the semi-skilled to the labouring jobs. I would
argue that by being successful in the electronics industry we tend to be
heading very firmly for a significant quantity of very hi-tech, high-skilled
jobs with high wages.''
But if that was true for every inward investment, why would Labour's minimum
wage pose a threat? ``OK there are always going to be some inward investments
in industrial sectors where wages are less than in others but the bulk of the
jobs that come are clearly solid employment prospects,'' the minister replied.
It was, Mr Kynoch added, ``very possible'' that some inward investment would be
scared away by a #4.15 minimum wage. ``But that is not necessarily saying that
all inward investment jobs are low paid. The social chapter, the minimum wage,
even a tax-raising parliament for Scotland, all of these must introduce
uncertainty and difficulty to business in ensuring it maintains its
competitiveness.''
And what about the perception that growing segments of his own backbenches now
favour withdrawal from membership of the European Union, the very market reason
American and Asian investors come here in the first place?
``I believe our party is very much more united than the opposition,'' he
insisted, calling in evidence the fact that eight Tory MPs voted against the
Government whip in the last significant vote on the subject, while 42 Labour
MPs defied their whip. ``Europe is a sensitive subject across all the parties.
But I don't think this ever enters into discussions with inward investors.''
With Lanarkshire missing out to North-east England on the Samsung and Siemens
investments in the past year, but now winning Chunghwa against South Wales, the
minister declined to be drawn on just how competitive Scotland is as a location
within the UK.
``I'm not sure we've actually got a breakdown,'' he said. Martin Togneri,
director of Locate in Scotland, who sat in on the interview, pointed out that
the Invest in Britain Bureau stopped publishing league tables some years ago
because they ``induced squabbles''. ``We feel we are certainly normally at the
front, or very close to the front, in UK terms,'' added Mr Togneri.
Despite that reluctance, it is, in fact, still possible to make some precise
comparisons. As our tables show, for most of the 1990s, Wales did significantly
better than Scotland in attracting international investment and the jobs that
come with it. It was only last year, thanks in part to two huge investments in
the semiconductor sector from NEC and Motorola, that Scotland got its nose in
front. Precise figures for the English regions are much less accessible.
That Welsh advantage over Scotland was, in part, due to South Wales's
locational attractions, lying as it does at the end of the M4 corridor, close
to the biggest UK markets and the main routes to Europe. Until now Scotland has
had to try to build strength in depth in particular sectors, like electronics,
where it has a long-established edge.
Mr Kynoch has an oft-repeated mantra which encompasses that edge - ``Scotland
produces 12% of Europe's semiconductors, over 35% of Europe's personal
computers, over 50% of Europe's automated banking machines and nearly 60% of
Europe's workstations''.
But is that focus on electronics - to the extent that the sector now dominates
Scottish manufacturing output and Scottish exports - also a potential weakness?
Just as we put too many eggs in the shipbuilding, coal and steel baskets in the
past, are we betting too much on silicon now?
``I take your point. But we are successful in other areas of inward investment
as well,'' Mr Kynoch replied, pointing to Selfcare International, an incomer
from Boston who announced in July it is creating 375 jobs to produce diagnostic
medical kits in Inverness.
The minister says he is anxious to broaden the base and sees encouraging more
indigenous companies to export as one way of doing it. ``That is where
government can help, ensuring the assistance we give is better targeted and
better co-ordinated so that small and medium-sized companies which, let's face
it, are the embryos of large companies, can get the guidance and assistance
they need in export markets much more easily.''
To those indigenous companies which complain that too much Scottish Office
emphasis and support goes to inward investors, Mr Kynoch is relatively blunt.
Most of the financial packages available to the likes of Chunghwa are available
to them too. He and his officials, he insists, go to considerable lengths to
ensure they do not bring in companies which might distort the local market.
``We are not allowed to put forward a package which would cause such a
dislocation,'' he adds. And Mr Kynoch has a challenge for local companies.
``Going round some of the inward investors, I find the comment being made quite
often that they can't source products and services here.''
That's a long-standing concern within Scottish Enterprise. The minister is not
depressed by the lack of progress. I tell him that 15 years ago, when Scotland
was awash with joiners' shops beginning to reel from the decline of traditional
industries, I talked to the Japanese boss of the first Mitsubishi television
plant in Haddington. He couldn't find anyone in Scotland to supply him with the
wood veneer cases in which television tubes were then housed.
Hadn't we, I asked, taken an awful long time to plug that and countless other
gaps in local sourcing for inward investors? ``I think it gives us a further
challenge to ensure we can fill that gap,'' came the unflappable Kynoch reply.
``We now produce 35% of Europe's computers. That's a hell of a lot of
computers. You've got to get a hell of a sourcing. It takes time. We're making
steady progress.''
When I asked if Scotland can keep up the pace, you can perhaps guess what he
said. ``It's a constant challenge.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
