<HEADLINE>Sister of swing</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Rob Adams</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975356054</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Rob Adams examines pianist Katia Labeque's divergence into jazz and how her
musical interpretations have added to the world-renowned twin-piano duets with
her sister
KATIA LABEQUE is trying to make up for lost time. In her late teens, while she
and her sister Marielle were learning a repertoire of contemporary classical
compositions and developing their extraordinary twin-piano partnership which
has bewitched audiences all around the world, Katia feels now that she was
missing out on studying another kind of music - jazz.
``I was 17 when I discovered jazz,'' she says. ``I listened to John Coltrane's
quartet with McCoy Tyner like crazy, but I never learned to improvise. Oh, I
can play around with a few chords but that doesn't mean I'm making music by
doing so.''
The voicings are doubtless more sophisticated these days but it was through her
playing around with a few chords and picking out melodies from the radio that
Katia's musical promise announced itself, at the age of three. She demanded
piano lessons from her mother (a piano teacher) and made such startling
progress that she gave her first concert at Paris's Theatre de Champs-Elyses,
aged seven. At this point her younger sister, Marielle, who had shown no
interest in music previously, demanded piano lessons also.
By the time Katia was 13, Labeque mre realised that she could teach Katia no
more, so the sisters enrolled at the Paris Conservatoire, graduating with
distinction three years later. At this point they made two decisions: to work
together and to play the works of contemporary composers. ``We had no choice,''
Katia explains. ``If we had arrived, two little girls, cute and charming,
offering to play Mozart and Schubert, no-one would have listened to us.''
People did listen to them. Olivier Messiaen invited them to record his Visions
de l'Amen and overnight they gained a reputation as contemporary music
specialists. Their list of subsequent collaborations is exhaustive but it was
with their recording in the early eighties of Gershwin's Rhapsody in Blue that
they really became established in a big way.
Ragtime and jazz pieces entered their repertoire shortly afterwards as Katia
began working with guitarist John McLaughlin's band. With her Conservatoire
training, she says, jazz came as a shock. ``The tutors wouldn't even admit that
Coltrane and Miles existed but I've come to believe less in schooling and more
in personality and imagination. School can teach you the basics but no-one can
teach you to be yourself.''
The experience of making her recent album, Little Girl Blue, on which she duets
with jazz piano masters including Chick Corea and Herbie Hancock as well as her
sister, made Katia determined to develop her jazz playing. At the moment she
considers herself an interpreter. On tracks such as Bill Evans's Turn Out the
Stars, rather than creating a new solo of her own, she plays a transcription of
Evans's original solo.
``Sometimes people don't realise that jazz musicians, by creating something new
out of old tunes every time, are being really great composers,'' she says.
``For me, they are the equal of Ravel and Debussy and by playing transcriptions
of their great solos I hope to draw this to as many people's attention as
possible, although Chick Corea is very keen for me to improvise more when we
work together in the future.''
Little Girl Blue was, she says, a dream come true. Working with musicians who
have been her heroes for many years made her ``petrified and yet at the same
time so happy''.
``It was an amazing experience because for the first time I was my own producer
and in the classical world you're not used to that. So, whatever anyone thinks
of Little Girl Blue, I can't blame it on anyone else and from now on I will try
to extend production into classical music, to make them understand that we are
responsible, that we know what we want and can take decisions about the sound.''
For their concerts in Scotland this weekend Katia and Marielle will be joined
by the brilliant Cuban pianist Gonzalo Rubalcaba. They will play Mozart (Katia
thinks Wolfgang might be a jazz musician were he alive today), some Spanish
music, and some of Rubalcaba's originals, including - they hope - a piece for
six hands which he is currently writing.
Rubalcaba, who was a sensation on his Scottish debut in September, also
features on Little Girl Blue and recently joined Katia on a Brazilian tour.
``He mixes the three disciplines so well. He started as a classical pianist, he
inherited the Latin style from his father and grandfather, and he has really
studied jazz. Working with him in a duet is quite scary because he changes what
he plays every time and I never know what he's going to do. But sometimes I
recognise that he is playing the arrangement and I'm very happy.''
n Katia and Marielle Labeque play Aberdeen Music Hall, this Friday, Edinburgh
Queen's Hall, Saturday, and Glasgow Royal Concert Hall, Sunday.
</TEXT>
