<HEADLINE>Labour and the 1970s</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975356055</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CLEARLY Brian Wilson is destined to climb the ranks of the Labour Party as he
has at least one main attribute: never let facts stand in the way of truth. I
have never met or indeed spoken to him, but he appears from his media
appearances to be one of Labour's young brigade. Indeed, he may even have been
in short pants when last Labour were in power -1979, 16 years ago.
Does he never wonder why his party has been out of power for so long? Let me
remind him of the seventies. Almost daily strikes, spiralling taxation over
90%, inflation at an outrageous 20% plus, it may even have been referred to as
the period of rape and pillaging of the British people.
Indeed, pundits said at the time, ``we may never see Labour in power again this
century,'' and they may yet be proved right. Brian Wilson was perfectly correct
when he said Stephen Hendry loved Scotland and loves his country. He does.
While other birds have flown the coup, he has remained and will continue to do
so unless the events of the seventies return.
The Tartan Tax could, of course, be a reduction, not just an increase. Indeed,
our own Braveheart George Robertson suggests Jimmy White may come and live in
Scotland!
Brian Wilson and Mr Robertson should let us know what the cost of a Scottish
parliament is to be, bearing in mind they are suggesting an increase from 72
members currently in Westminster to 129 in Edinburgh, with all the additional
ancillary staff.
If we can have a profit-and-loss account and if the benefits to Scotland and
the people of Scotland outweigh the horrendous costs then maybe the three blues
will vote for Brian Wilson, but he should remember that before you can pot the
blues you have to pot three reds first of all.
Ian Doyle,
Cuemasters Ltd,
Kerse Road, Stirling.
</TEXT>
