<DOCNO>GH951116-000079</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000079</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mirad, a Boy from Bosnia, MacRobert Arts Centre, Stirling</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>John Fowler</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975356057</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE war in Bosnia has been so savage, so bewildering (at least to an outsider),
and has had such extensive media coverage that any play runs the risk of being
overshadowed by the drama of real life. Mirad, a Boy from Bosnia, in this
production by the Oxford Stage Company, makes its point quietly by rejecting
histrionics in favour of a low-key, understated narrative style. From the
start, when the actors trudge on stage to address the audience directly in the
apologetic manner of refugees seeking asylum, the tale is told by a cast of
four in a dry, matter-of-fact manner.
In the first half of the play Mirad, a teenage Muslim boy forced to flee the
horrors of Serb invasion, is present only in the words of his diary and the
conversation of others. In part two, as the innocence of childhood gives way to
a maturity warped by experience, he appears in person (played by Gareth Corke),
quitting his safe haven with relatives in Holland to return home in the hope of
finding his lost mother. Of the two, the earlier part is the more satisfying,
perhaps because it was originally intended to stand alone as a complete work.
The play, which is aimed particularly at young audiences, has a powerful and
convincing intensity in this production by John Retallack, though in the end
the unflagging earnestness of it all is hard to take. Almost two years ago,
when the English version of the first part was introduced with a starry cast,
its raw topicality must have been shocking. But it still carries a potent
message.
</TEXT>
