<HEADLINE>Vision of a Clyde flowing with shimmering vitality</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALASTAIR MacDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>open forum</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975356059</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I WAS very interested in an article by Alan Dunlop, ``A short-sighted vision of
the future'' (October 30). Returning recently from a three-city tour of
Australia, I was struck by how much the river and waterfronts contributed to
the vibrant life of each city in contrast to Glasgow's own riverside.
From Hobart, Tasmania, commuter ferries ply across the Derwent estuary to
Belerive, a popular commuter suburb. Traffic-flow across the main river bridge
is relieved at peak times by the ferries which revert to sight-seeing mode
during peak day-time tourist activity.
In Melbourne, the Southgate Centre has transformed a run-down area of dockland
on the Yarra river into a convivial area for the business community, complete
with restaurants, cafes, design shops, and a small aquarium. This centre now
provides a bridging point linking Swanston Street, the main axis of the central
business district across the Yarra, with the national gallery, concert hall,
and botantic gardens. From Southgate, riverboats follow the recently upgraded
foot and cycle paths which are alive with people taking exercise along its
green banks.
Anyone who has been to Sydney will be struck by the constant bustle of Circular
Quay, which was revamped for the 1988 bicentennial and is home of the museum of
contemporary art and the iconic opera house. The adjacent Darling Harbour, with
its renowned aquarium and massive tourist park, was derelict and inaccessible
to the public 10 years ago. Now it is alive day and and night; wardens and
infra-red cameras provide a sense of security after dark.
Commuting by ferry is a natural part of city life, and cheap and fast rail
links to the centre and suburbs ensure that river life is fully integrated into
the transport network.
These river scenarios could easily be Glasgow's, but does it have the vision to
find a use again for the natural asset of the Clyde on which it has turned its
back for so many years? Should we be seeing the river feature in the
city-centred millennium plan's transport strategy? It doesn't at present.
A coherent river development policy would greatly add to the proposals outlined
in the public realm strategy guideline document, concerned with the streets and
spaces in Glasgow city centre, which has already identified opportunities for
increased linkages along the river's edge. Instead of the ``severing effect''
of the Clyde, the river could have a much more cohesive role binding the north
and south of the city together.
Although each of the Australian cities is very different from Glasgow, there
are useful lessons. The increased peopling of the riverfront areas makes them
safer and imparts a shimmering vitality which draws people, together with their
spending power, to the water's edge. The natural highway of the river can also
relieve stress on the road system, and increase pedestrian journeys. That no
coherent plan exists for such a wonderful natural asset is unbelievable.
The city is working hard to reinvent itself, and surely the river should once
again be part of the new Glasgow. There are certainly many separate, and often
conflicting, proposals for developments along its length. These include the
proposed #90m leisure and business-use redevelopment at Pacific Quay to include
the Scottish National Science Centre; the Clyde Maritime Trust's proposed
maritime museum; and a #30m Sir Norman Foster designed extension to the
Scottish Exhibition and Conference Centre. Recent discussions of a direct rail
link to Glasgow Airport could be replaced in part by some sort of river ferry,
and the river could once again play an important role in the transport
infrastructure, while at the same time providing a recreational axis.
In May, the Royal Incorporation of Architects in Scotland's 1995 convention in
Glasgow took as its theme ``Cities on the Edge'' with one day devoted to the
theme ``The Water's Edge''. International and more local speakers showed case
studies of cities which had revitalised their waterfronts through inspired
design schemes.
The Laganside Development in Belfast by Robinson &amp; McIlwaine has already
produced two fine buildings, the Belfast Concert Hall and the Clarendon
Building. In Boston, participants in the Harbour Visions project were
challenged to dream up imaginative ideas for the harbour area ranging from the
immediate future to a century or more, but were also charged with the task of
grounding their visions in reality and proposing practical implementation
strategies. We have enough architects, designers, and artists in the city and
beyond capable of producing visionary, but practical ideas.
What is also required is something to bring all the separate discussions
together, and create a coherent and workable plan for the whole river. Charles
Scott, the convener of ``The Clyde Conference - The City and its River in the
21st Century'', to be held at Strathclyde University next June, states
emphatically: ``We don't want this to be a talking shop. We are keen to form a
unitary body and secure funding to develop the whole river and to stop the
present piecemeal development.''
The conference has already attracted, as one of its main speakers, David
Mackay, responsible for the redevelopment of Barcelona's shoreline, which used
to be cut off from the city centre but now forms a natural destination for a
major city axis.
Meanwhile Scott cites Tyne and Wear Development Corporation which secured #300m
of Government funding for its river-development programme, although funding
structures are somewhat different south of the Border.
As Simon Jenkins, one of the judges for 1999, put it: ``Here is a city that has
lost the reason for being where it is; the design and construction of ships.''
We need to find a new role and a coherent plan for the river which will help in
the regeneration of our city. Hopefully the Clyde conference will provide the
catalyst and all interested parties can have a say. There are enough excellent
case studies from around the country and further afield to inform and stimulate
the imagination, and enough hard evidence of the economic benefits of such
schemes to reassure the bankers.
As Gordon Murray of the Glasgow Institute of Architects reminds us, ``With the
demise of Strathclyde region and the instatement of the unitary authorities, a
unified plan will be essential.''
n Alastair Macdonald is senior lecturer in Product Design at Glasgow School of
Art and has been a member of the UK City of Architecture and Design 1999
steering group for the past two years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
