<HEADLINE>Correct and exquisite phrasing</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356060</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO corrections. First, the Diary buried Lord Fraser in Kilmarnock. He was
buried in Kilmaronock, near Gartocharn, on Loch Lomondside.
Secondly, in your report of a Remembrance Service at Westminster attended by
the Queen Mother, Mrs H Jones was said to have quoted Binyon's verse For the
Fallen, ``They shall not grow old''.
I cannot believe that a woman as sensitive as Mrs Jones would have been so
ill-informed as not to know Binyon's exquisite phrasing, ``They shall grow not
old''.
An ignorant reporter with a tin ear must have been the culprit for the Daily
Telegraph and the Times carried the same report. It is unforgivable that the
error should have been perpetuated in the public prints, especially at this
time of remembrance.
S L McKinlay,
Woodlee,
Woodham Waye,
Woking, Surrey.
</TEXT>
