<TEXT>
In principle
STEWART Lamont wrote of ``people whose lack of
religious belief makes them uncertain, fearful of death, and who cling to life
regardless of value'' (November 11).
Since he was talking about the principle of voluntary euthanasia, he seems to
be suggesting that religious people are more inclined to accept this principle
than non-believers.
He is wrong. Although many people have reservations about the practicalities of
legalising voluntary euthanasia, especially with regard to possible abuses,
most of those who are opposed as a matter of principle are religious people.
John Clunas,
5 Cairnlee Avenue East,
Cults, Aberdeen.
</TEXT>
