<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Woman held over plot to kill Rabin</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975356062</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Jerusalem, Wednesday
AN Israeli court today remanded in custody for 11 days a woman Jewish settler.
Police have described her as ``dominant'' in the plot to kill Yitzhak Rabin.
Police told a Petah Tikva magistrates court that Margalit Harshefi, 20, like
confessed assassin Yigal Amir a law student at the religious Tel Aviv
university Bar Ilan, played a central role in the prime minister's murder and
plans to attack Arabs.
``She is one of the dominant members of an organisation that wanted to kill
Rabin. She was deeply connected to the murder of Rabin and to planning attacks
against Arabs,'' officer Tsion Tsafon told the court.
Harshefi, of Beit El settlement in the West Bank, was brought into court in
handcuffs. She wore a sweatshirt and long denim skirt and clutched a small
black prayer book.
When Judge Eliezer Cohen read the charges - conspiracy to commit a crime,
failure to prevent a felony, and involvement in an unnamed illegal organisation
- Harshefi gave a little laugh and said: ``I request a meeting with my lawyer.
I am not guilty.''
In addition to the remand, Cohen ordered that she not be allowed to see a
lawyer until Sunday.
Her lawyer, Denel Peli, and her father, Dov, both said she knew Amir, 25, well
but had no criminal connection with him.
Amir, a religious Jew, shot Rabin on November 4 as he left a Tel Aviv peace
rally. He said he killed Rabin to prevent the handing over of land, mostly in
the West Bank, to Palestinians.
Police today detained two Jews who spat on Rabin's grave in Jerusalem.
The two ultra-religious Jews admitted in a Jerusalem court they spat on the
grave but denied one of them had tried to urinate.
A magistrate's court remanded them in custody for six days while police
consider charging them with desecration.
Police freed Avishai Raviv, head of the extreme-right Jewish group Eyal,
arrested on November 6 on suspicion of conspiracy to murder Rabin. Raviv was
released on bail to remain under house arrest at his parents' home for seven
days and he may not enter the Israeli-occupied territories, a police spokesman
said.
Aside from Amir, Harshefi and Raviv, five people are being held in connection
with the assassination. All are religious Jews in their 20s.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000085</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000085</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Razor King's city is meaner than ever</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>John Burrowes</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975356063</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
John Burrowes claims that Glasgow may have transformed itself since its No Mean
City days but there is still a raw side which rivals anything from the thirties
THE predictable ones are being predictable again. They, together with sundry
good-news spin doctors, are set to pounce on a new book about the city of tree,
bird, bell and fish. Author Ron McKay's nascent novel titled Mean City is a
story based on the lives of those descended from the immortalised fictional
gangster Johnny Stark, his family, and contemporaries who featured in the most
successful book of all time about Glasgow - about modern Scotland? - No Mean
City.
In fact, the unaware McKay may have some other unforeseen problems about his
book, but more about that later.
The City of Culture that is destined in three years to be the City of
Architecture and Design bleats no louder than when the occasional writer
reflects on the raw and the real there is about Glasgow. They not only want to
shoot such messengers - they want them exterminated.
They screamed at their loudest, of course, when No Mean City itself was thrust
upon them in 1935. Instead of storming Westminster with such contemporary facts
as the city's housing standards being so horrific the infant death rate of 112
per thousand was almost twice that of Birmingham and London, including its
impoverished East End, they turned on the author of No Mean City, Alexander
McArthur, an unemployed baker who had turned to writing.
McArthur had an intimate knowledge of the Gorbals of the day, but was no
Hemingway. But to date his book has sales in excess of a million worldwide and
more than 3000 are still bought yearly. No mean feat was No Mean City.
The book's hero is portrayed as the city's greatest gang fighter, regularly
warring in gang battles with and against sometimes hundreds of participants.
Yet all my research for three books I've written on the thirties shows that No
Mean City was, in fact, a mild representation of those very primitive years.
``Sir, it is depressing nowadays to take up one's paper and read the daily
catalogue of assaults and murders with knives, razors and other lethal weapons.
Indeed, razor slashing and stabbing are becoming so common that they appear to
be accepted as part of modern youth's recreation.''
That was a letter published in the Evening Times on March 14, 1930, and
reflected the grim state of law and order of those very rough-and-tumble years.
Of course, Glasgow is nothing like those bad old days of the thirties.
Quick-response hi-tech cops armed to the ears with instant communications have
done as much for sword and cudgel gang fighters as throwaway shavers have done
for razor slashings.
And yet...... and yet! Take out the reference to razors in that 1930 Letter to
the Editor and it is still germane about our Glasgow of the 1990s. Those who
keep telling us how much they love the city - like the ones who will be
blasting McKay's book - will, of course, say otherwise. But it's those of us
who have the truest love of our city who want the warts to be shown and written
about in the hope that one day there really will be change.
Confront those who deny the truth that Glasgow is in so many ways a meaner city
than ever, and they're horrified. And that despite the graphic nightly details
uncovered so explicitly in the Evening Times Drugs Hotline where the streets
and the houses of the drug merchants were pinpointed.
Let those who defend our city through what they say is their ``love'' name a
public park where you can walk with impunity today. Who would even dare to set
foot after dark in the likes of Queen's Park, haunting ground for the strange,
hunting ground for the violent.
Rouken Glen, surrounded by a cluster of the city's most affluent suburbs, is
equally out of bounds. Two foreign visitors, unaware of its dangers, have in
recent times paid the penalty of innocence on evening strolls. Both were
viciously assaulted, sustaining the severest of injuries, one dying after
months of agony.
Who would let their wife or girlfriend walk through the city to meet them at
night? In Johnny Stark's day Glasgow was a mean place, all right, but not that
mean. The Razor King from the Gorbals fought his battles against other gangs
all over the South Side, Dennistoun, and the East End, but my granny and your
granny were safe in their houses. So were the kids who played in their
thousands in the streets. Aye, and in the dark as well.
Like the author of No Mean City, McKay will never be forgiven for this latest
book on the city. Glasgow put the boldest of stamps on its feelings four years
ago when it was suggested there should be a plaque, perhaps even a statue, in
memory of Alexander McArthur. The mere notion almost apoplexed city Labour
leader Pat Lally, whose snappy retort to the idea was: ``This man McArthur did
neither Glasgow nor the Gorbals any favour by writing his book and we will
certainly not be doing anything to remember him.''
They all run, don't they, when the raw side emerges? They were doing it again
before and after the airing last Sunday of Football, Faith and Flutes, the
Glasgow-produced Channel 4 programme on aspects of Rangers and Celtic fans.
It's as though they actually believe we don't have the kind of people any more
who populated what used to be known as the terraces at Ibrox and Parkhead. But
we do. Sadly, many aspects of that mean city are still out there.
Alas, as I mentioned earlier, there may be other problems in store for author
McKay. Twelve years ago I set out to write a similar book to Mean City. It had
the working title of No Mean City II and took all the characters from the
original on another generation.
Two lawyers in Scotland with whom I checked said there should be no copyright
problems but still wary, I sought expert copyright advice through the Authors
Society to learn that counsel's view was that such a book could be in danger of
what was termed ``passing off'', that is, a claim could be made against me for
causing confusion to the public by the publication of a book which might damage
the marketing potential of the earlier work.
I scrapped the 15,000 words I had written and started again, the result being
my book Jamesie's People, for which there are plans for yet another print.
Like so many things, the origin of the phrase that gave birth to Glasgow's most
eminent book can be traced back to the Bible. When Saint Paul was asked if he
was a certain Egyptian (Acts 21, verse 39), he replied he was a Jew from Tarsus
``a citizen of no mean city''. And prophetically he added: ``Suffer me to speak
unto the people.''
q.John Burrowes is a Glasgow journalist and author of the trilogy which began
with Jamesie's People, published by Mainstream and Fontana. Mean City is
published by Hodder and Stoughton.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000086</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000086</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Unedifying royal tussle Old certainties lie in the gutter</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975356064</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PERHAPS it is time for a new compact between the royal family and its subjects.
The agreement, deal, call it what you will, used to be reasonably clear. The
royal family provided leadership, example, ceremonial treats, and a titular
position as head of the state in which we live. In return it was given loyal
support, respect, the duties due to headship of state, and affection bordering
on love. Some of the above was earned and much of it came with the job, but the
relationship has changed radically now and it is only fair to point out that
any changes which have occurred have done so entirely at the instigation of the
royal family. In the light of the public tussle between Prince Charles and
Princess Diana, which has alternately enthralled and depressed loyal subjects
for more than three years, it is clear that another and quite different
question to all those that have gone before must be asked. This is it: what
does the royal family want from us now?
The answer is not obvious. It would be sensible to make clear at this point
that the question should be addressed to Prince Charles and Princess Diana who
are, after all, presumed to be the future of the royal family in this country,
whether they are together or apart. They might reply that what they would
really like is something similar to that which was bestowed on the present
Queen and her predecessors; that is loyalty, respect, affection, love, and an
acknowledgement of a sense of the numinous which lifted them above the common
ruck and which was enjoyed by both royals and subjects. Then again, they might
not. Prince Charles has expressed his irritation with the traditional duties
and expectations which have constrained him, and Princess Diana does not have a
regal bone in her body. You see, it is they who have changed the compact, who
have come out of the palace and all-too-frequently into the gutter. It is they
who have removed the old certainties of both their position and ours, and
because of that it is they who are faced with the necessity of re-defining the
relationship.
It can probably never be put back as it was. Perhaps the most objectionable
aspect of the disagreement between Prince Charles and Princess Diana is the way
in which the public has been used as an unwilling arbiter in their argument.
Whoever or whatever is to blame for the breakup of their marriage is not in
question here. What is at issue is the tiresome way in which we have all been
dragooned into providing an audience for their tantrums. No, this is not
entirely the fault of the media. Both parties have persistently leaked their
version of affairs and have supplied information to authors of books which have
taken the position of one or the other. Prince Charles gave his infamous
television interview in which he bared far too much and Princess Diana
evidently intends to do something similar on Panorama next Monday.
Did we ask for this from our royals? No, we did not. It is fascinating, of
course, and to admit as much does no more than reveal us as humanly fallible in
our tastes. But looked at objectively, and with an interest in the status of
the monarchy, it is not edifying. There must be a better way of managing
things; indeed there is. It is the way of the many ordinary subjects who find
their marriages broken but who behave with dignity and sense and earn the
respect of their friends and family.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000087</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000087</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Service medals and diplomas</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975356065</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE remembrance parades produced a brave show of medals from those who served
in the Second World War and later conflicts. But how many watching would have
much awareness about the origins of these? Most would be campaign or service
medals. Some, however, would be decorations for outstanding and gallant conduct.
The death of Jackie Mann reduces the number of living holders of one such
decoration - the Distinguished Flying Medal (DFM). This was awarded to
non-commissioned RAF aircrew. Among the holders are Battle of Britain pilots
and bomber crews whose life expectancy at one stage was measured in days and
weeks rather than months. Knowing this, I felt rather honoured recently to be
in correspondence with someone showing DFM after his name in the official
letterhead. However, it transpires that DFM in his case stands for diploma in
forensic medicine.
Sadly, this person is by age, profession, and status someone I would have
expected to have known better. He is also surrounded by people at least some of
whom should have had the awareness to put his gaffe right.
So much for knowing about and respecting the debt owed to those such as Jackie
Mann.
The DFM was awarded in the period from 1918. It was superseded in 1994 by the
Distinguished Flying Cross (DFC), previously only awarded to officers. The
awards are by Royal Warrant and misuse of the letter indicating them could be
regarded as gross discourtesy to the Queen.
Let those issuing diplomas warn the recipients that Dip and never D should be
used in abbreviation to avoid similar gaffes.
A McDonald,
Meikle Tile, Balfron.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
