<DOCNO>GH951116-000088</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000088</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Targeting the drug-smugglers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975356066</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS a press spokesman I am well used to reporters being selective with quotes in
an effort to sell a story. A missing word here or there or a quote out of
context can turn a story on its head. In general, however, I have found The
Herald to be reasonably balanced in its reports, until now.
Reports on October 28 and November 13 referring to the Krakow II and 50 tonnes
of cannabis said to have been missed by Customs officers are incorrect. The
total amount of drugs found by Norwegian Customs was 20 tonnes.
The 21.7 and 27.7 tonnes referred to in your October report were, in fact, the
gross weight of the two containers This emphasises the danger in basing stories
on information sent anonymously.
The Customs team at Invergordon identified an irregularity in the paperwork of
two containers bound for Poland. There was insufficient time to search the ship
after the information had been fully analysed and the Norwegian Customs were
informed. They searched the containers and found 20 tonnes of cannabis. This
was a success for international co-operation in the fight against drugs.
The map in your November report highlights drug seizures over several years
around the Scottish coast. All the large seizures made were as a result of
international intelligence supported by brigading of Customs staff. This
supports the changes we are making to our organisation.
The international drug-smuggler is a well-organised professional who spends
considerable time and money setting up large operations for the illegal
importation of prohibited drugs.
The idea that a few lone Customs officers patrolling the remote Scottish
coastline will deter the commercial drug-smuggler is outdated.
We intend to combat that professionalism with greater professionalism - through
international co-operation, intelligence gathering, and the brigading of staff
so that when we do identify a problem we are there in numbers.
We have moved on some way from the booze-and-baccy seizures of the old days to
a much more risk-based targeted approach in our fight against the drug
smuggler. What we do need, however, is the support of the media, not this
misinformed attack on the work of Customs and Excise.
Change inevitably brings criticism from the uninformed but I wonder if Rabbie
Burns, a famous Exciseman, had the same media attention when his horse was
replaced by a bike.
Bill Forsyth,
Customs and Excise Scotland,
44 York Place,
Edinburgh.
</TEXT>
