<TEXT>
The unchanging needs of society
THE editorial on Bishop Holloways's comments about morality and the Bible
deserves commendation (November 15)
Human nature has not changed since Old Testament times - only the outward
trappings of culture. (The Patriarchs' polygamy does not rule out the
advantages of trust in monogamy, which seems all the more necessary and for
many apparently difficult, in our western as opposed, say, to patriarchal Saudi
society.)
The Ten Commandments - regardless of whether they were in some sense, inspired,
as somehow they must surely have been for their day - represented a social
``back to basics'' programme. The prime needs of that society had to be met.
Even allowing for some social changes (eg, in the West the status of women and
servants), the commandments address the unchanging needs of any stable society
today - and even outside biblical Christianity they have many echoes. One
example only: Epictetus the Stoic has a passage censuring adultery. It is as
elevated in tone as  much in the New Testament.
Bishop Holloway does not seem to stress sufficiently that trust as a challenge
to adultery is a corollary to the fact that adultery is theft. Trust must
indeed be promoted if relationships (in monogamy or otherwise) are to survive;
and implicit in adultery is stealing. One cannot easily trust a thief.
Jesus transmuted the commandments into the call to love one another. That is as
necessary today as in his century - and Christian love is neither sentimental
nor promiscuous (despite human fallibility) but includes justice; and justice
does not countenance theft of any kind - or indeed any failure to conform to
the essentials for social stability.
This need not be said censoriously. Christian preaching should be an appeal to
look oneself in the face and ask whether one's guiding principle is a love that
is also just to others and ``takes up its cross''.
Something of this the Bishop appears to realise. But let us not play down the
need for self-discipline. Reason itself commends this.
Rev J C G Greig,
St John's Croft,
Sorbie, Wigtownshire.
</TEXT>
