<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000090</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000090</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Southside Johnny, Garage, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Keith Bruce</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975356068</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PERFORMING ``unplugged'', or ``stripped'' as the Stones have it, is all very
well when there is some aesthetic behind it. I suppose. But when it is clearly
forced on a rocker by economic necessity it is desperately sad. Say hi to
Southside Johnny without the rhythm 'n' blues powerhouse that was the Asbury
Jukes - just guitar, acoustic bass guitar, and electric piano.
The man himself still looks the same - same prescription shades, same bad
haircut - and the voice is still superb. It is one that John's mentor Bruce
Springsteen would give his strumming arm for if he had any sense. But John
hasn't developed a style to match his pared-to-the-bone band and still sings as
if fronting a 12-piece din-machine. The only times that the event burst into
life was when the musicians gave up any pretence at doing something radical and
just settled in to be a good old-fashioned bar band, pumping out stuff like
Help Me. Even then they could still have done with a drummer.
No complaints about the material though. Fever segued into his own (well,
Bruce's) Got the Fever. Tom Waits contributed Heart of Saturday Night. Talk To
Me might have been one of the worst affected by the limited line-up (and an
initially lousy sound mix), but it is still a great song, with a cracking male
lyric, simple and affecting.
But in the end there is no appeal in hearing the demos of songs you first heard
in their full glory 15 years ago. Southside Johnny's take on the basics went
crashing between an entire IKEA store of stools.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
