<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Spaniard is new  front-runner for top Nato post</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356069</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Madrid, Wednesday.  SPANISH Foreign Minister Javier Solana tiptoed towards
Nato's top job today after weeks of public wrangling among the allies.
Mr Solana, whose name has emerged as a possible solution to the alliance's
search for a new chief, has been given signs of support so far from Germany and
Italy, as well as the US, the senior member in the 16-nation alliance.
``There is no reason at all for Spain not to be able to have the general
secretariat of the Atlantic alliance,'' Solana told reporters. ``But that
doesn't mean it will have it.''
Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez said earlier that Solana, 53, would make a
``magnificent'' secretary-general even though Spain was surprised by
suggestions he should run.
Gonzalez and Solana both said Spain had not considered fielding a candidate.
A foreign ministry spokesman said: ``For the time being there is no Spanish
candidate - for the time being.''
With the traditionally discreet process of picking a Nato chief now public
after weeks of rows between Washington and its European allies, Solana appeared
to be measuring his steps to avoid any risk of rejection.
Washington's European allies are still smarting at its blunt treatment of
former Dutch premier Ruud Lubbers, who was put forward by the Netherlands and
endorsed by key players only to be rejected by the US after holding talks there.
``I think everyone wants to make sure at this stage there are not going to be
any new fiascos,'' one official said. ``It's very likely that anyone who
doesn't want to take the risk now might be waiting to be reasonably sure of a
consensus.''
Mr Solana, a former Fulbright scholar in the US, is said to have good relations
with Secretary of State Warren Christopher and even with President Bill Clinton
- important personal assets in a race where personal chemistry matters.
His name emerged as a possible compromise candidate after the American
rejection of Mr Lubbers left only one other declared runner, former Danish
foreign minister Uffe Ellemann-Jensen.
Mr Ellemann-Jensen today dismissed rumours that he was about to withdraw from
the race but diplomats doubted he could overcome apparent French hostility to
his candidacy.
At a ministerial meeting in Madrid of the Western European Union defence group
yesterday, several fellow European foreign ministers openly praised Mr Solana
and said he would make a good replacement for Belgium's Willy Claes, who quit
on October 20, facing an investigation into a Belgian arms procurement scandal.
Diplomats said for a real consensus to start emerging, Solana would probably
have to declare his ambition.
Potential backers could be reluctant to throw their weight behind someone who
may then not run - a point underscored today by the US envoy to Nato, Robert
Hunter.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
