<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000093</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000093</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tenuous golden thread Queen's Speech provides welcome tedium</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356071</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WE ARE acquainted now with the contents of what will be the last full programme
of Government legislation before the next election. It has leaked out in dribs
and drabs of course, to such an extent that there are few surprises; indeed we
have already had the opportunity to comment on much of it. Although the Queen's
Speech has been planned together with the Budget as an effective two-headed
assault on Labour's current popularity, it is clear that the bulk of
responsibility for this task will rest with the Budget. The problems
encountered by Tory drafters of the Queen's Speech are obvious. A programme of
reasonable legislation must be brought forward with decent expectations of
success, but with a majority of just six in the Commons it was clearly
impossible to present active and controversial legislation. If the result is
dull in terms of both parliamentary drama and in the effect which controversial
legislation might have on already battered sectors like education and health,
then we should delight in the tedium. In Scotland in particular we have little
beyond the humdrum and again we should be grateful. Yet this is a busy enough
programme containing 15 Bills, which is two more than last year.
In his response in the Commons yesterday Mr Tony Blair delivered his customary
vigorous performance, spurred on it seemed by the gloomy faces on the
Government benches. The core of his attack rested on the allegation that the
proposed legislative programme had more to do with the political fortunes of
the Tory party than with governing the nation. This was an easy jibe if an
accurate one, although nobody needs suspect that Mr Blair would do anything
different if he were to find himself one day in Mr Major's predicament. In
attempting to emphasise the difference between Tory and Labour policies or, in
more realistic language, trying to grub for some votes, the Tories have decided
to concentrate on the unlikely figure of Mr Michael Howard, the Home Secretary.
It is difficult to think of a more vilified occupant of that office or one who
has had so many rebuffs from his legal peers and suffered so many legal
reverses of decisions. Nevertheless, Mr Howard is the bobbing cork of the
Cabinet; his pursed and shadowed smile never fades and with his policies to
streamline the handling of asylum applications and to fine employers who
unwittingly employ illegal immigrants he hopes to gather popular support. We
hope he is wrong. The so-called light regulatory touch does not remove the
absurdity of turning employers into immigration officers, and the list of
countries to which the Government believes it will be safe speedily to return
asylum-seekers includes Nigeria.
The Secretary of State for Scotland, Mr Michael Forsyth, believes he can
discern a golden thread running through the programme presented yesterday. It
is a curious metaphor, for while gold has an attractive glint, thread is easily
snapped. Mr Forsyth plans to make sensible use of the existing legal framework
to apply further controls to the running of raves at which youngsters can be at
danger from drug pushers. His support for the nursery voucher scheme is
unlikely to enhance its attractions and the easing of the problems caused by
school placing requests will help the sufferings of Balfron High School in his
own constituency but will be of little use to popular secondary schools in
urban settings. For real information on the Government's intentions in coming
months we will have to wait for the Budget. In comparison with the Queen's
Speech it may even be a relief.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000094</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000094</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Far from written off</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Carole Woddis</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356072</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The Traverse Theatre has been honoured for its creativity, as CAROLE WODDIS
explains
THEATRE may be said to be dying - and certainly final rites are constantly
invoked - yet it shows no signs of actually kicking the bucket. On the
contrary, according to London-based American critic and producer Blanche
Marvin, despite financial stringencies and more glossy co-productions, ``the
avant garde work just keeps on growing''.
Edinburgh Traverse's Ian Brown is less sanguine. ``People are spending less on
going out. Our audiences are being split. Something's got to give. That's why
recognition like this is so important to us.''
Brown was speaking in London yesterday after receiving a special achievement
award on behalf of the Traverse and its thirtysomething years of creating
theatre in small spaces - part of the annual Empty Space, Peter Brook Awards
initiated by Marvin in celebration of the ideals of the international, Paris
based-director and his life-time devotion to the new and experimental. Now in
its fifth year and held annually in conjunction with Covent Garden's Theatre
Museum, this year's major award went to the Royal Court Upstairs for a stream
of controversial and eclectic new plays - double its usual work rate as James
Macdonald, one of its young directors pointed out ``but entirely to do with the
response to writers from a new generation coming through who amazingly still
choose to work in the theatre instead of other art-forms that might be more
seductive''.
Paying tribute to writers, Brown feels Scottish writing may also be on the
brink of a new era. ``It's not exactly been a golden age in recent years but
now I think we're into a new phase. It's very encouraging the number of new
writers coming out of Scotland.''
But, he pointed out that new writing remains a high-risk activity. Which is why
accolades such as the Empty Space awards are so important.
``Some people don't appreciate us as much as they should. It's too easy to
underestimate and marginalise what we do. But we're part of a national system,
a link in the chain of new writing and all the attendant costs that involves.
It's a major achievement we are open and solvent, for the challenging kind of
work we produce, year-round.''
He hopes Edinburgh District Council are listening. For, he believes, a change
of policy and financial recognition of the cost of producing new work is long
overdue. Without it, the Traverse's future looks less than promising.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
