<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Trident and English votes</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356073</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE article on Trident refit work rightly focused on the betrayal of the
workforce at Rosyth Royal Dockyard by the Government and the particular
treachery of Malcolm Rifkind (the Defence Secretary at the time) in not
supporting both the taxpayer and the Rosyth workers (November 10).
As Mr Jack Dromey proclaimed, the Government was happy to accept the Devonport
Dock's bid for the contract of refitting Trident submarines despite the fact
that it was an unrealistic quotation and the taxpayer would have to pick up the
cost of the necessary upgrading work.
The real reason for the contract being awarded to the south coast of England is
that there are few or no votes (and parliamentary seats) to be gained or lost
by assisting Fife, but John Major was very alert to the fact that, had the
Trident work come to Scotland and not the south coast, a number of his
sycophant MPs would have lost their seats in the next General Election (which
will happen in any event).
W N Gibson,
Manufacturing, Science and Finance Union,
1 Woodlands Terrace,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
