<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000096</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000096</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Unst is an unsatisfactory Alcatraz</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356074</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS A FORMER parish minister of Unst I was amused by your report of that most
northerly island of Shetland as being tiny, barren, and remote (November 14).
Tiny? It is the same size as Jersey in the Channel Islands. Barren? Though
virtually treeless and with plenty of rock and moor it has magnificent cliff
scenery, glorious beaches, lovely lochs, an undulating hilly landscape, and
some passable farms and crofts.
Remote? Well, as the old lady in Lewis said: ``Remote from where?''
Curiously the name may derive from an old Norse word meaning ``nearest''.
However, I suppose that as there is only one absolute everything is relative.
As a former secretary of the island development group and an initiator of the
island's airstrip I would find it sad to see that lifeline close. But a high
security prison on a civilised parish where you could leave your ignition keys
in your car, where doors were rarely locked? I am doubtful - albeit years ago I
did suggest the small uninhabited island of Uyea to the south as a possibility.
Difficulties of recruiting staff, the cost of transporting prisoners and
visitors would, I reckon, make it prohibitive as an Alcatraz unless it was a
smallish enterprise.
Moreover, one wonders if the ``hard'' men would be tough enough to withstand
the occasional gale - Unst has the UK's highest, albeit unofficial, windspeed
of 177.2mph.
While ``Unst'' might possibly also derive from an ``ern'' (the sea eagle)
therefore ``eagle isle'', it has to be remembered that Scotland had an Alcatraz
for centuries - it was ``the Bass,'' much nearer supposed ``civilisation''.
Rev A Douglas Lamb,
St Margaret's Manse,
Dalry, Ayrshire.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000097</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000097</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Waiting Room Germany, Royal Court, London</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Carole Woddis</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975356075</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THIS eye-witness account of life in Germany after reunification was first
performed as a rehearsed reading upstairs at the Royal Court and almost without
precedent transferred downstairs immediately for a short season.
A collection of real-life testimonies by Klaus Pohl, one of Germany's most
performed dramatists, its power resides less in the conventional meaning of the
word drama than in what it reveals - a country still deeply at odds with
itself, a kaleidoscope of events that flatters neither side, neither Western
capitalism nor the former communist regime.
In a large, grey, impersonal hall that shrieks a state of transit, be it
immigration, passport or railway waiting room, director Mary Peate's five
multi-purpose actors deliver their testimonies straight to the audience.
And what a riveting, sad story they tell - of individuals at the mercy of
political systems, pushed hither and thither like pawns both before the Wall
came down and since as a trail of human wreckage piles up in the wake of a
planned economy forced overnight to become a market one.
A West German insurance exec smugly criticises the non-commercial attitude of
his East German counterparts; a former East German worker describes the
emergence of ``cowboy'' salesman preying on gullible workers in comparison with
the lack of consumerist pressure under the old regime. A woman psychiatrist
meanwhile inveighs loudly and bitterly against the straitjacket mentality of
her former East German homeland, but an ex-East German mayor, spelling out the
food shortages of the old system, also laments the loss of a shared sense of
community.
Rueful and salutary, brutality in its many guises seeps out from the stage of
the Royal Court. In the hands of its cast, and particularly Freda Dowie and
Robin Soans, it takes on the unarguable force of truth.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000098</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000098</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Council rubbishes hospital waste claim</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356076</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CLAIMS that dangerous hospital waste was dumped at a tip in Dundee have been
condemned by the district council.
However, the makers of last night's BBC Here and Now programme were standing by
their claims amid accusations that they had ``misled'' Dundee District Council
over film footage of bloodstained swabs and test tubes allegedly taken at the
Riverside rubbish dump.
The row broke out after the programme makers investigated the city's Baldovie
incinerator which destroys 18,000 tonnes of waste a year from hospitals across
Scotland.
The television team claims to have filmed footage of confidential patient
records, test tubes containing blood, and other dangerous waste at the
Riverside landfill site.
A spokesman for Dundee District Council accused the BBC of having ``nothing''
to support its claims.
The spokesman also disputed claims that the film crew had seen clinical waste
on the Riverside tip.
``The film crew did not visit the site until the day of the interview. The BBC
has told us that what they saw was contained in a video made by a third party
unknown to the council.''
The spokesman also claimed ``not one member of the crew saw any evidence of
unburnt material when they visited the Dundee tip''.
However, BBC spokesman Jon Steel said: ``We firmly stand by our story. We have
film of syringes and surgical gloves on this dump. That is our footage, which
we took. There is also other video evidence taken by a local campaigner.''
The programme also claimed that the incinerator is producing ``a cocktail of
dangerous substances''. The council spokesman said: ``If Her Majesty's
Industrial Pollution Inspectorate thought there was a problem the plant would
not be allowed to operate.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000099</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000099</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Adams attempts to enlist Clinton</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From PATRICK BROGAN Washington, Wednesday</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356077</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GERRY Adams is calling on the white House again today, in an effort to enlist
President Clinton's support for his position in the negotiations with Britain.
He has accused the British government of dragging its feet and setting
impossible conditions before the all-party talks on the future of Northern
Ireland can begin.
Mr Adams has been to Washington several times since Mr Clinton allowed him into
the country for the first time early last year.
This time, he will meet the president's national security adviser, Anthony
Lake, and Mr Lake's chief assistant on Irish questions, Nancy Sonderberg. He
will not meet the president.
Leaders of the Unionist cause in Northern Ireland visited Washington last month
on the same errand. The president is due to visit Britain and Ireland at the
end of the month, and ``celebrate the extended period of peace and the end of
violence, and illustrate that the people of Belfast can now move freely and
that life has returned to normal,'' according to a White House official.
Mr Adams wants to persuade the president to use his considerable influence in
London and Dublin to get the British Government to give up its demand that the
IRA accept at least the principle of partial disarmament before the talks can
begin.
The partial shut-down of the US government has upset Mr Clinton's travel plans
this week: he has cut short a visit to Japan for a Pacific Rim economic summit
in Osaka. He will now leave Washington late on Friday and return on Monday,
spending the bare minimum at the conference.
It is too early to say whether the continuing political crisis in Washington
may affect his visit to Britain, but it is at least possible that he may cancel
it altogether.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000100</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000100</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Government takes tougher line on asylum-seekers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356078</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Queen's Speech contains a raft of measures which the Tories hope will give
them a clear advantage over the Opposition on law and order.
The most controversial is likely to be the new Asylum and Immigration Bill
which, according to the Speech, will ``streamline further the handling of
asylum applications and strengthen enforcement of immigration controls.''
The Speech contained no detailed explanation of the plans and how they would
work, but the measures envisaged by Home Secretary Michael Howard have been
widely trailed in recent months.
A key proposal designed to accelerate and reduce the cost of processing asylum
claims is the creation of a so-called ``white list'' of countries deemed to be
safe. Asylum applications from residents of those countries will be presumed to
be unfounded.
The other key part of the Bill is likely to be an attempt to deal with illegal
immigrants.
Earlier this year, Mr Howard floated the idea of heavy fines for employers who
gave jobs to illegal immigrants. However, the proposal prompted deep misgivings
within the Department for Education and Employment - which feared it could
result in companies being less ready to recruit ethnic minority staff - and
among employers' bodies and civil rights groups.
It is now expected the Bill will require employers to check the records of
potential recruits, in an effort to stop illegal immigrants working, backed up
by a ``light, regulatory approach.''
Narendra Makanji, chairman of the Anti-Racist Alliance, said unions and
immigrant welfare groups would unite to defeat the Bill.
``This Bill is undoubtedly a curtain-raiser for a Tory racist campaign in the
run-up to the next election.
Claude Moraes, director of the Joint Council for the Welfare of Immigrants,
said that the move to hold employers responsible for taking on illegal
immigrants would deeply damage race relations and would alllow unscrupulous
employers to discriminate against black British citizens.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000101</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000101</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scots missing after avalanches</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356079</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOUR Scots are among a party of Britons not heard from since Himalayan
avalanches killed at least 40 people, it emerged last night.
The Scots, two married couples from Prestwick, Ayrshire, were among a group of
72 visitors who set off for Nepal 12 days ago. Sandra and Cameron White hope to
raise money for breast cancer research. They were with friends Peter and Tracy
Croudace.
Nothing has been heard of the group, who were part of a 17-day charter tour and
were accompanied by more than 30 Sherpa guides.
However, a close friend of the Prestwick couples said last night that their
families were confident they had escaped the tragedy. ``We don't think they
would have been far enough in yet. It was a 17-day trek but I think it would be
almost a month altogether, to allow them a few days at base camp to acclimatize.
``Communication is non-existent once they get on with their trek, which could
be why nobody has heard anything yet, so no news is good news.''
She added: ``Tracy wasn't going to phone her mum until the end of November.
That's when they're back in Katmandu. It's not like going off to Benidorm. We
wouldn't expect them to be in touch if they can't get near a phone. They
probably don't know the avalanche existed.''
Mr and Mrs Croudace, who live in Main Street, Prestwick, are believed to be in
their late twenties. They both work for the Civil Aviation Authority in air
traffic control at Atlantic House, Prestwick.
Mrs White, 40, is a breast care specialist nurse at Ayr Hospital. Her
44-year-old husband is also an air traffic controller at Prestwick. They live
at Caerlaverock Avenue, Prestwick and have two sons Stephen, 24, and Jason, 20,
who has already visited the Himalayas on a church fellowship.
</TEXT>
