<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000102</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000102</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Strict curbs aim to make raves safer</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By Our Parliamentary Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356080</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A BILL aimed at making raves safer for young people will impose new licensing
conditions and will seek to control the size of licensing boards under the new
local authority structure.
The Scottish Drugs Forum has been asked to prepare advice for organisers,
setting out the practical steps which can be taken, such as providing
``chill-out areas,'' free drinking water and appropriate stewarding.
Under the Scottish Office proposals, licensing boards would be given the power
to attach specific conditions to licences for premises used for raves to
enhance the safety requirements covering the events.
A key feature will be to target potential and actual drug misuse, and
supporting guidelines will be issued to licensing boards to aid their decision
making.
Each of the new councils coming into being in April, 1996, will be required to
decide whether to elect one licensing board for their area or whether to divide
the area into licensing divisions, each with its own licensing board.
Either way, the Bill will contain measures to ensure that, after local
government reorganisation, representation on licensing boards is kept at a
workable level.
Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth said: ``The dangers of recreational
drug-taking have been highlighted yet again in recent days with the reports of
the collapse of an 18-year-old girl after taking an ecstasy tablet.
``In Scotland last year, we saw the tragic deaths of three young men in
Ayrshire after attending a rave at Hanger 13. All of us - parents, teachers and
indeed young people themselves, have a responsibility to spell out the dangers
of drug taking. The Government will continue to help this education process and
at the same time hammer the dealers in this evil trade.''
Mr Forsyth said that raves and the club scene had been linked to the taking of
recreational drugs, which was why he had decided to take action to make sure
that the organisers of raves, and the young people who attended them, knew how
the risks could be reduced.
He added: ``I intend through the Licensing (Scotland) (Amendment) Bill to give
licensing boards the power they need to require that there are proper
safeguards and control over raves held in licensed premises. If the organisers
of these events cannot or will not comply with the conditions set down they
will not be able to operate.
``I do not want to deprive young people of a source of entertainment, but I do
want to ensure they can enjoy themselves safely.''
Labour's Scottish Home Affairs spokesman, Mr John McFall, said: ``What is
required is proper licensing of rave clubs and outdoor venues where raves
occur. Model conditions for rave license should deal with attendance levels,
stewarding and searching of people entering the rave venues.
``I welcome this measure, but on its own it cannot deal adequately with the
problem and should only be seen as the first step.''
THE Prime Minister told the Commons yesterday that he is to ask the European
Union to help Caribbean states stem the flow of drugs from South America.
``In an evil trade like this, no drug is soft, and no drug is safe,'' he said.
Disclosing his new initiative, Mr Major told MPs many of the drugs from South
America were smuggled to northern Europe through the Caribbean.
``Over the last few weeks, I have been consulting Caribbean leaders about the
ways of breaking this chain,'' he said.
``At their request, with their agreement, I will be asking the EU to give them
effective help.
``The intention would be to find the resources to stop the Caribbean being used
as a way-station for drugs from Latin America en route to northern Europe.''
Mr Major said he believed the country must use every resource against the drugs
threat.Hence the Queen's Speech proposed to lift the existing barrier to the
Security Service helping the police and other agencies against organised crime.
</TEXT>
