<DOCNO>GH951116-000103</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000103</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Foreign Digest</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356081</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Ferry hero plans
to adopt Thai boy
BANGKOK: A British man who rescued a toddler from a sinking ferry now wants to
adopt the boy, it was reported yesterday. Mr Arthur Hughes was a passenger
aboard a ferry going to the island of Koh Samui, 270 miles south of Bangkok,
when it capsized and sank last Friday.
Mr Hughes, a tourist, was reported to have given his life jacket to
three-year-old Thai boy, Jessada Laohbhram, and helped him escape from the
lower deck as the boat went down.
Tourism prize
BRUSSELS: Regional parks in Britain and France, an Austrian region and an Irish
town are nominees to win the European Prize for Tourism and the Environment,
the European Commission said yesterday. The French Cevennes National Park, the
medieval Irish town of Kinsale, the Austrian region of Weissensee and the
British Peak District National park are all finalists.
Cambodia deaths
ARANYAPRATHET: Two Khmer Rouge guerrillas and one Cambodian government soldier
were killed and many others wounded yesterday after several hours of the
heaviest fighting for the past few months, officials said.
Growth areas
OSAKA: Asia-Pacific ministers edged closer yesterday towards agreement on how
far and how fast to open up the world's fastest-growing economies, and a new
report spelt out the potentially huge rewards of a deal. A report forecast the
18 member economies could grow by a massive 20% by the end of the century, the
highest regional rate in the world, if infrastructure and energy shortcomings
were overcome.
EU film fund
BRUSSELS: The European Commission proposed yesterday that the European Union
set up a guarantee fund that could generate more than one billion dollars to
help its struggling filmmakers compete against Hollywood.
Boy killed
NAPLES: A two-year-old boy was shot dead yesterday in a war between organised
crime groups in southern Italy. The boy and the man whose car he was travelling
in were killed near Naples, when a gunman in a second vehicle pulled up
alongside and opened fire, police said.
Former Nazi
BUENOS AIRES: The Supreme Court in Buenos Aires has rejected a final appeal by
a former Nazi officer accused of the 1944 massacre of 335 men and boys outside
Rome, clearing the way for Erich Priebke's extradition to Italy.
Vodka fatalities
MOSCOW: The Russian government must act to stop men drinking themselves to
death, scientists attending an international conference on alcoholism said
yesterday. Experts at the conference in Moscow told Tass news agency that the
average Russian man drinks half a bottle of vodka a day.
De Gaulle statue
PARIS: A copy of a London statue of the late French president Charles de Gaulle
will be inaugurated at the Invalides war museum in Paris on November 22, the
Defence Ministry said yesterday. The original statue was erected two years ago
at London's Carlton Gardens, the wartime headquarters where General de Gaulle
led resistance in Nazi-occupied France.
</TEXT>
