<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scottish divorce reform urged</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By LYNNE ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356082</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CALL for divorce laws in Scotland to be reformed was made yesterday by a
Scottish group which helps separated families maintain contact.
The director of Family Mediation Scotland Ms Susan Matheson welcomed the
announcement of proposals in the Queen's Speech to review divorce in England
and Wales
She said the reform was ``long overdue,'' and the group would be seeking
similar moves north of the Border.
``Contrary to the opinion of some, this reform will not encourage divorce - the
divorce law has little bearing on the difficult decision to separate.
`` These reforms offer parents time to consider the consequences of their
actions and make the best possible plans for their childen,'' she said.
Ms Matheson said proposals in England and Wales to abolish the fault grounds
and increase the role of mediation were particularly welcome.
She added:``As the aim of FMS is to meet the needs of children of separating
and divorced parents, we are watching with interest the divorce law reform
proposals for England and Wales.
``We would welcome reform in Scotland along similar lines for the benefit of
very many thousands of Scottish children each year,'' she added.q.The Prime
Minister could face Tory right-wing wrath by pushing ahead with divorce law
reform in England and Wales.
The Bill faces a difficult passage and there could be concerted attempts at
amendment.
The Lord Chancellor, Lord Mackay, is said to be prepared to undertake serious
amendments.
</TEXT>
