<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Clinton and Congress dig in citing  `irreconcilable differences' Presidency staked on budget resolution</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From STEVE HOLLAND Washington, Wednesday</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356083</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CONGRESSIONAL Republicans offered a plan today to reopen business for the US
government, but President Bill Clinton vowed to veto it and said he was ready
to stake his presidency on the budget fight.
``If the American people want the budget that they (Republicans) have proposed
to be the law of the land, they're entitled to another president, and that's
the only way they're going to get it,'' he said in a television interview.
Fearing the government shutdown could drag on for days, Clinton cancelled a
weekend trade trip to Japan and put Vice President Al Gore in his place.
House Speaker Newt Gingrich and Senate Republican leader Bob Dole, seen by many
Americans as the bad guys in the budget fight, proposed a temporary spending
bill dropping an increase in premiums for Medicare insurance for the elderly
that had troubled Clinton.
But the measure would commit the Democratic president to achieving a balanced
budget in seven years using Republican estimates of future economic growth that
the White House said would force deep cuts in popular social programmes.
Clinton prefers a gentler path of nine or 10 years to a balanced budget.
The White House specifically rejected this plan and Clinton struck a defiant
stance against Republican budget priorities in general when told that Gingrich
had warned the impasse could drag on for 90 days.
``I'm not going to do it, even if it's 90 days, 120 days or 180 days,'' he told
CBS News. ``If we take it right into the next election, let the American people
decide.''
Gingrich, a Georgia Republican, told Dole he expected the House to pass the
measure and send it to the Senate. He said it would fund the government until
December 5 and give both sides time to work on a permanent budget solution for
1996.
The speaker said of Clinton: ``If he wants to sign the stopgap spending measure
that will reopen the government, then he is signing a contract that says seven
years to a balanced budget.''
But the White House, aglow at polls showing that Americans for the most part
agree with Clinton's position, was adamant.
``There has been no dramatic shift at all as a result of what the Republican
leaders said. This is the same formula for impasse that we've been living with
for the past 48 hours,'' White House spokesman Mike McCurry said.
There was every indication that 800,000 federal workers, ranging from tax
collectors to White House chefs, would stay home for a third straight day on
Friday.
White House chief of staff Leon Panetta travelled to Capitol Hill for talks
with Democratic lawmakers. No new talks between the White House and
congressional Republicans were scheduled. Indeed, the major players were
talking to each other only through the news media.
The only sign of progress was House and Senate passage of an $11.6bn Treasury
Department appropriations bill that, if Clinton signs it, would let 190,000
federal employees go back to work. Clinton was expected to sign it when it
reaches his desk in coming days.
Day Two of the government shutdown was marked by a cross-fire of warnings and
recriminations. The White House said ``irreconcilable differences'' existed
between the two sides.
Illustrating the enmity between Clinton and Gingrich, the speaker groused anew
at what he considered shabby treatment on Air Force One on Clinton's flight to
Israel on November 5 for the funeral of assassinated Prime Minister Yitzhak
Rabin.
Gingrich said he wanted to discuss the budget during the 25-hour round trip to
Israel but was rebuffed, and was forced to exit the plane from the rear
entrance.
``Where is their sense of manners?'' he said. McCurry expressed incredulity
that Gingrich had said any such thing, but said that in any case Clinton was
too shaken by Rabin's death to talk business at that point.
Meanwhile Washington was far less crowded than usual, bereft of many of its
briefcase-toting bureaucrats. On a related battlefront, the two sides are also
at odds over raising the government's borrowing authority to avert an
unprecedented default on the US debt.
Clinton announced on Wednesday that Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin was forced
to take ``extraordinary but necessary actions'' to keep social security cheques
going out next month.
Rubin dipped into two federal pension plan trust funds for about $61bn to make
debt payments and said that would avert a default through late December.-Reuter
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000106</DOCNO>
