<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>More powers for deer commission</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By Our Parliamentary Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356084</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Deer (Amendment) (Scotland) Bill is designed to introduce a number of
measures aimed at promoting the sustainable management of wild deer populations
in Scotland.
It is based largely on proposals for reform prepared by the Red Deer Commission
in 1994 after a Government consultation exercise.
The plan is for the commission to promote, and take action to manage, all
aspects of the relationship between deer, their habitat and other land uses. In
particular, the commission will be allowed for the first time to promote action
to protect the natural heritage.
In short, the Bill amends a number of provisions relating to the culling and
shooting of deer, making it, for example, easier to authorise shooting to
prevent damage to the natural heritage or to protect public safety.
The definition of agricultural land over which owners and occupiers can shoot
deer, if necessary, to protect crops and pasture will be changed.
Scottish Office Agriculture Minister Lord Lindsay said yesterday: ``The Bill
represents an important step forward in the Government's overall policy to
ensure the sustainable development and management of Scotland's natural
resources.''
The chairman of the Association of Deer Management Groups, Stephen Gibbs,
welcomed the Bill's announcement, but added that ``significant progress''
already had been made under the existing statutory framework over recent years
in reducing deer numbers in areas where deer populations had risen most
markedly.
However, he added: ``We agree that there is a need to extend statutory
protection to natural heritage interests; also that some flexibility as to the
statutory deer seasons will be helpful to deer managers.''
Mr Steve Sankey, head of policy and advisory at the Royal Society for the
Protection of Birds, said:``A lot more thought is being put into deer
management plans, and as long as clear objectives and clear targets are linked
to the provision of biodiversity, they we will be happy.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000107</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000107</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rural schools to benefit from placing changes</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH BUIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356085</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MOVES to ease problems at high capacity schools where parental placing requests
have left incomers unable to find a school place for their children are likely
to benefit rural schools, but not popular urban secondaries, it emerged
yesterday.
As predicted earlier this year, the Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth has
acted to overcome the difficulties at Balfron High, within his Stirling
constituency, by amending regulations so that ``certain schools'' will have to
retain ``a few'' places for incomers to the school area.
Parents, teachers, and the school board at Balfron had been pressing Mr Forsyth
to change the rules because incomers to the area were finding it impossible to
place their children in the school because there was no spare capacity. New
arrivals had to be transported to schools outwith the catchment area.
It emerged last night that the changes in legislation were aimed mainly at
rural areas where no suitable alternative school was available for parents to
send their children. The criteria for selecting schools are mainly geographical.
The so-called ``magnet'' secondaries such as Holyrood Academy or St Ninian's in
Glasgow, often over-subscribed due to placing requests from parents, are
unlikely to fall into the category of schools which will be permitted to retain
a small proportion of places for incoming families.
It is understood that provided there is another equivalent school within
walking distance, to which parents who move into the area can choose to send
their children, then the much-requested school will not have to retain places.
Last night, Scottish Office sources were emphasising that the key to the
legislative changes was the principle of ``parental choice''.
However, Mr David Alexander, senior depute director of education in Strathclyde
Region, predicted that many ``incomer'' parents in busy urban or suburban areas
would be angry that their plight was not being considered.
``Once it becomes clear that only certain schools are being considered, I think
a number of parent bodies and school boards are likely to be quite upset. They
will be pressing for their schools to be included,'' said Mr Alexander.
He added: ``Balfron is almost a one-off. All the examples of problems in
relation to not being able to retain capacity are in urban areas.''
The rector of Balfron High, Mr Jim Fleming, said: ``Any move in this area will
be greatly welcomed by the school and school board. We have had a fairly
well-publicised problem with pupils being transported long distances out of the
catchment area in buses.''
Mr Fleming said he hoped the Scottish Office would adopt Balfron High's
recommendation that 2% of school places be kept open for incoming pupils - in
its case 17 places out of a school roll of 850.
There is no indication yet from the Scottish Office of how many places it
envisages should be retained in certain schools.
Councillor Rob Ball, chairman of the education committee of Central region,
said: ``Mr Forsyth has obviously seen the light, although until now he has
resisted it. My only reservation is that it does not specify what proportion of
places would be held.''
</TEXT>
