<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000108</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000108</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Space `ballet' ends with a party</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356086</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Houston, Wednesday
ASTRONAUTS guided the US space shuttle Atlantis to the Russian space station
Mir and docked early today, neatly executing the difficult manoeuvre 245 miles
above Earth.
It was the second linkup of Atlantis and Mir, but was considered more
complicated - and dangerous - than the first because of the five-metre docking
tunnel jutting out of the shuttle cargo bay.
The docking tunnel will be left behind on Mir when Atlantis pulls away on
Saturday. It will make the next five Atlantis-Mir dockings easier.
Shuttle commander Kenneth Cameron pulled within 50 metres, then nine metres, of
Mir as both spacecraft hurtled around Earth at 17,500.mph.
Cameron slowly steered Atlantis up under Mir, avoiding the station's maze of
solar panels.
Docking occurred right on time, easing the tension in space and on the ground
at the Houston space centre. A collision could have breached the two
pressurized spacecraft and killed all eight men aboard.
Chris Hadfield, a Canadian astronaut aboard Atlantis, called the docking ``a
ballet of concentrated effort''.
About 50 US personnel, including astronauts headed to Mir next year and
managers of the planned international space station, watched the docking on
huge television screens at the Russian Mission Control outside Moscow.
Like the first docking by Atlantis in June, this one required perfect timing,
perfect speed and perfect alignment.  Cameron could not see the end of his
docking port while closing in on the sprawling, 120-plus-ton station, however,
and had to rely on remote camera views, radar and lasers.
With solar panels, or arrays, sticking every which way out of Mir, it was a
monstrous obstacle course. Before the flight, Cameron admitted he was concerned
about snapping off a solar panel - or worse.-AP.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000109</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000109</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Stock market losses prompt suicide bid</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356087</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Bangkok, Wednesday
A DEPRESSED investor shot himself after scores of protesters rallied outside
Thailand's stock exchange today as the battered bourse continued its recent
sustained dive.
Heavily indebted investor Vivat Srisammacheep shot himself under the chin with
a pistol blaming exchange officials for his losses of over $1.2m from dabbling
in shares. He is in hospital.
The sugar and molasses trader was part of a group of over 100 investors who had
earlier staged a peaceful protest at the exchange to complain about the
bourse's plunge and to call for changes to the exchange's board in hopes of
stemming the downward spiral.
``The recent fall is due to the incompetence of the Stock Exchange of
Thailand's (SET) board and related government agencies,'' said a statement
circulated by the protesters.
The bourse has plunged a hefty 18.8% in value since July, when the new Thai
government came to power, amid worries about the competence of some ministers
to handle the economy.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000110</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000110</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Solicitor admits #2.5m thefts from clients Court told that US scam was to blame for downfall of a `greedy social climber'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356091</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FORMER Wigtownshire solicitor Giles Davies was sent to prison yesterday pending
sentence tomorrow after admitting two charges of embezzling #2.5m.
A plea of not guilty to a third charge alleging a #48,000 bank bridging loan
fraud by Davies, who practised in Newton Stewart, was accepted by the Crown.
Davies, 40, of Corwar House, Barrhill, Ayrshire - struck off by the Law Society
of Scotland in December 1992 for professonal misconduct - had originally faced
charges of embezzling almost #3.7m.
Yesterday, Advocate-depute Alan Turnbull told temporary judge Sheriff Robin
McEwan QC at Glasgow High Court that the Crown was prepared to accept guilty
pleas to lesser amounts involved.
Davies admitted that between April 29, l983, and May 13, l992, while acting as
a solicitor at McCormick and Nicholson, Symons and McDonald, of Victoria
Street, Newton Stewart, Wigtownshire, and at his home, he embezzled #1,165,016
and almost $1m.
He also admitted a similar charge between December 1991 and May 1992 involving
#696,785.
None of the money which went missing has ever been traced, despite intensive
police and Law Society of Scotland investigations. Mr Kenneth Pritchard,
secretary of the society, said yesterday: ``If there is any money which Davies
has salted away, both the investigations carried out by the Judicial Factor and
the police would now have identified it. No such money has yet been
identified.''
A plea by defence QC Neville Shaffer that Davies's bail be continued was
rejected.
Mr Shaffer had argued that Davies suffered from a severe depressive illness and
had failed to bring his medication to court with him.
Mr Turnbull told the judge he would need several hours today to explain to the
court the details of how the embezzlements were carried out by Davies. Mr
Shaffer is expected to address the court tomorrow before Davies is sentenced.
Last night, Mr Alan Boyd, president of the Law Society of Scotland, said
wide-ranging consumer protections funded by Scottish solicitors meant that no
member of the public suffered loss as a result of Davies's activity.
Davies's firm had insurance cover of about #1.3m through the Law Society's
Master Policy and Guarantee funds which paid out more than #2m in connection
with the case.
Almost 900 clients, many of them farmers and business people in Wigtownshire,
were understood to have been affected by the fraud.
Davies, regarded as a pillar of society in the market town of Newton Stewart,
was said by Glasgow solicitor Ross Harper, who represented him at a Law Society
disciplinary hearing, to have been the victim of a ``clever and unscrupulous
international fraud''.
A Rotarian, a member of the local country sports fraternity, and chairman of
Penninghame Primary School Board, he lived with his wife Moira and children
Zoe, 17, Paul, 13, and Jenny, 11, in Barrhill, Ayrshire. He bought Corwar
House, about eight years ago and was said to have a mortgage of #130,000.
A former colleague claimed he had been taken in by a multi-million pound scam -
which was understood to have been perpetrated by a company of rogue lawyers in
North Carolina.
The colleague said: ``He was fed bait a couple of times which made him think
the deal was genuine. Then the next time the cheque did not arrive and he was
in trouble. Davies was always a bit of an eccentric and a social climber. He
was also greedy - and that proved his downfall.''
His case caused such alarm in the profession that the Law Society wrote to
every practising solicitor, warning them not be taken in by the blandishments
of high-powered conmen looking for quick finance.
The ``get-rich-quick schemes'' included raising finance for a 2000-bed Aids
hospice in California, the creation of a million-acre wildlife park in South
America, a senior citizen township in South Africa, and the purchase of untold
numbers of aircraft and ships around the world.
Apart from ending his own legal career, Davies's activities brought disaster on
his former partners in the firm of McCormick and Nicholson, Symons and
McDonald, which had offices in Newton Stewart, Stranraer, and Dumfries.
The six partners, who were either sequestrated or signed trust deeds to pay off
as much as possible of the money owed by the firm, were absolved of any blame
in connection with Davies's activities.
They were automatically suspended pending a Law Society investigation. Five of
them have since taken up with other solicitors' firms in Wigtownshire, while
one has retired.
The solicitors' firm was plunged into chaos in May 1992, when Davies
disappeared. His car was found at Glasgow Airport but nine days later he
arrived home after apparently claiming he had been hitch-hiking.
The Law Society immediately launched an investigation into the firm's accounts.
This followed Mr Davies's involvement in various ``fund-raising exercises'' in
pursuit of which he opened client accounts with the National Westminster Bank
in Guernsey.
It emerged that, at the end of April 1992, Davies had instructed a credit entry
on one of the accounts for nearly $3m (#1,694,844). He then instructed a number
of debits resulting in a deficiency in the client account of #1.8m the
following month.
Leeds Permanent Building Society closed the agency which the firm operated from
its Victoria Street office in Newton Stewart. Soon afterwards, Dumfries and
Galloway Police launched an investigation into his dealings.
It emerged that a cheque issued by the firm for #83,000 as part payment for a
land deal had not been honoured two days before Davies's disappearance.
Meanwhile, other families were running into problems with cheques from the
company, including one family which expected to collect about #500,000 from the
sale of a farm.
If there is any money which Davies has salted away, both the investigations
carried out by the Judicial Factor and the police would now have identified it.
No such money has yet been identified
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000111</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000111</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Court date for church professor</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS HOLME</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356092</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FREE Church of Scotland Professor Donald Macleod was yesterday ordered to
appear at Edinburgh Sheriff Court to answer six charges of assault.
The case was continued without plea until November 29 following a motion by Mrs
Pamela Watson, depute fiscal.
Sheriff James Farrell also ordained him to appear on that date.
The charges relate to five women over a period from July 1985 to June 1993.
Professor Macleod, 54, of Craiglea Drive, Morningside, Edinburgh, is alleged to
have carried out four of the assaults at the Free Church of Scotland College on
the Mound, where he holds the chair of systematic theology, and the remainder
at his home and in a car parked at the Cameron Toll shopping centre in
Edinburgh.
In four of the charges, he is accused of placing his arms around the women or
pulling them towards them and kissing or attempting to kiss them.
Two of the charges relate to one woman during 1986 in which Professor Macleod
is alleged to have interfered with her clothing and handled her breasts and
private parts.
Professor Macleod, who is married with three sons, was not at yesterday's
hearing, which lasted less than two minutes.
</TEXT>
