<DOCNO>GH951116-000113</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000113</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Four changes to make a mark in the classroom</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN McGREGOR Parliamentary Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356095</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Education (Scotland) Bill, arguably the centrepiece of the Government's
legislative programme for Scotland, will introduce a number of changes.
It will establish a qualifications authority to take over the existing
functions of the Scottish Examination Board and the Scottish Vocational
Education Council.
It will introduce a voucher scheme for nursery schools and will reform the
procedures for school boards.
In addition, the rules on school placing requests will be modified to cater for
pupils moving into an area during the school year, and the requirement for
local authorities to obtain the approval of the Secretary of State for major
school building projects would be ended.
Scottish Education Minister Raymond Robertson said: ``The Bill will contain
important measures and confirms the Government's continuing commitment to
maintaining and further enhancing the high standard of education and training
in Scotland.
``The Bill will include provisions for a new Scottish Qualifications Authority
to take on the current functions of the SEB and Scotvec, and to administer the
Higher Still arrangements to improve post-16 education in Scotland.
``The merger of the two bodies was widely welcomed during recent consultation.
It would improve links between schools, colleges, and training for employment,
as well as promoting parity of esteem between academic and vocational
learning.''
On school boards, the legislation will contain proposals to improve their
operation, including a plan to give all local councillors whose wards lie
wholly or partly within a school's catchment area the right to attend and speak
at board meetings.
Mr Robertson said: ``I believe the Bill, with its combination of improvements
to existing legislation and important new initiatives, ranging from education
for pre five-year-olds to post 16-year-olds, will extend provision, widen
parental choice and further enhance quality and effectiveness in Scottish
education.''
</TEXT>
