<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000114</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000114</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>`Hawk' gets 12 years after shotgun threat to constables</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE McKAIN Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356097</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN armed robber nicknamed ``The Hawk'' was jailed for 12 years yesterday, for
threatening police with a sawn-off shotgun and a knifepoint raid on a building
society.
Lord Gill told Brian Martin, who has a string of previous convictions dating
back to 1976: ``Your record establishes you as a thoroughly dangerous criminal.
You cannot expect leniency in this court today and I can see no reason to
extend it to you.''
The judge said he regarded the assault on the police officers as all the more
serious because it took place in a public street. The effect on at least one of
the constables - who broke down in the witness box - had been all too plain.
It is understood that police in England now wish to question Martin about a
number of armed raids on building society's south of the border.
After a seven-day trial, a jury at the High Court in Edinburgh found Martin,
38, guilty of assaulting Constables Neil Stewart and John Hughes by menacing
them with a sawn-off shotgun. The incident took place in Craigie Street,
Ballingry, Fife, on October 29, 1994.
Martin, who formerly lived in Ballingry, pleaded guilty to assaulting three
employees at the Yorkshire Building Society, George Street, Oban, on November
24 last year, presenting a knife at them and robbing them of #4639.
He was also charged with being part of a gang of four which carried out a #8350
payroll robbery in the Fife village of Glencraig, in which victims were tied
up, had their eyes taped, and were threatened with a knife and sawn-off shotgun
on September 25 last year.
Martin also denied abducting a bookmaker and his wife in Lochore, Fife, and
threatening them with a sawn-off shotgun before robbing the bookmaker of #2000
on November 6 last year.
The jury returned a majority not guilty verdict on the payroll robbery charge
and a majority not proven verdict on the abduction charge.
The jury was told that police wanted to interview Martin and were tipped off,
on October 29 last year, that he was in the Craigie Bar, Ballingry. Martin ran
from the pub to be confronted by uniformed officers waiting outside.
Constable Stewart broke down in the witness box as he told how he looked down
the barrels of the sawn-off shotgun produced by Martin.
He described how Martin's long leather jacket flew open to reveal the gun.
Martin had it hung over his shoulder from a piece of string, and swung it up
towards him.
``He cradled the barrels of the gun with his left hand and put his other hand
on the trigger. He shouted at me: ``Back off or I will shoot you.''
Mr Stewart broke down in the witness box and Lord Gill had to halt proceedings
to allow him to regain his composure. The constable told the court that, after
the shotgun incident, he was in a state of shock and was off work for 51 days.
Martin told the jury that, following the Oban robbery, he stayed in a local
hotel overnight, then went on the run for nine months in England, Wales,
Ireland, and Spain.
He was arrested in July this year when he and girlfriend Julie Bryce, 31,
stepped off a cross-channel ferry at Portsmouth.
After yesterday's verdict, Lord Gill pointed out that Martin had been convicted
on 33 previous occasions, involving 54 charges.
In 1987, he had been jailed for six years at the High Court in Edinburgh for
robbing a Fife bookmaker's shop and a building society in Stirling, both at
knifepoint.
The robberies were committed while Martin was on the run from Noranside Open
Prison.
</TEXT>
