<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000115</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000115</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mercy flight to fulfil last wish</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356099</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MOTHER-OF-THREE fulfilled her last wish, to be at home with her family when
she died, with the help of the Scottish Ambulance Service.
Mrs Sally Drake, 37, a cancer sufferer, was being cared for at the Highland
Hospice, Inverness, but wanted to spend her last weeks with her fisherman
husband Peter, 40, and children Christopher, 15, Rebecca, 13, and Elizabeth,
six, at their family home in the remote Wester Ross village of Achiltibuie.
However, Mrs Drake, a district nurse, would not have been able to undertake the
100-mile journey by road, as much of the route is on rough and potholed
single-track roads.
The Scottish Ambulance Service stepped in and took the unusual step of laying
on their air ambulance helicopter, normally used only for emergencies, to take
Mrs Drake home.
They also provided a road ambulance to take a special bed and equipment from
the hospice to her home to ease the suffering of the remaining days with her
family.
After five weeks at home Mrs Drake died and her funeral takes place today at
the crematorium in Inverness. A memorial service will be held in the village
hall tomorrow.
Mr Drake said yesterday: ``I do not know just how irregular it was for the
hospice and ambulance service to arrange for Sally to get home in the only way
possible, but we were all very grateful she could be with us right up until the
end.
``She put up a brave struggle against her illness for more than two years after
discovering it during her midwifery training in Inverness. The last few weeks
have been very hard on the children, but their teachers and our friends have
been very supportive. I have not been at sea since September.''
A spokeswoman for the ambulance service said: ``Normally, terminally ill
patients would be taken home by road, but each case is judged on its own merits
and obviously a humanitarian decision was taken here.''
</TEXT>
