<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000116</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000116</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>News digest</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356100</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Ford offers
`best' deal
FORD last night offered its workers an inflation-busting two-year deal, which
it said was the best in the industry.
At the end of day-long negotiations with union officials, the company offered a
rise of 4.75% now, followed by 4.5% or the rate of inflation plus 0.5%,
whichever is greater, next year.
Sixth arrest
A SIXTH person was under arrest last night in connection with the police
investigation into who supplied ecstasy to 18-year-old Essex girl Leah Betts,
who is in a coma. Her parents are maintaining a vigil at her hospital bedside.
Lesson wrecked
FOUR police officers - an instructor and three students from the Scottish
Police College, Tulliallan - were recovering yesterday in Borders General
Hospital with cuts and bruises, after a crash, near Greenlaw, Berwickshire, in
which their patrol car was wrecked while they were on an advanced driving
course.
Bard honoured
NOBEL Prize winning poet Seamus Heaney is to take part next year in a festival
celebrating the bicentenary of the death of Scottish bard Robert Burns. The St
Andrews University festival will also include contributions from Scottish
novelist A.L Kennedy.
Threat to beauty
AN area renowned for its beauty could be facing the threat of rural squalor, an
MP warned yesterday. Mr John Home Robertson, MP for East Lothian, is demanding
environmental safeguards against a massive rubbish dump near Dunbar and private
opencast coal sites.
Facade remains
ONLY the facade of an 18th century building at 25 St Andrew Square, Edinburgh,
will be left in a #3m office extension, a development committee heard
yesterday. The committee approved the application from London &amp; Wiltshire
Scotland on the condition that the roof material was suitable.
Police award
A PIONEERING training programme which has helped police officers protect
themselves has won Strathclyde Police its first Scottish safety award. The
programme involves training in the use of side handled batons, rigid handcuffs
and safety awareness.
Tube strife ends
LONDON Underground's five-month dispute - which involved three strikes and was
one of the longest in its history - ended yesterday with the Rail, Maritime,
and Transport Union accepting a 3% pay deal.
</TEXT>
