<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Part-time workers may win #95m</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS Industrial Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356102</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SIXTY thousand part-time workers could win #95m in compensation for backdated
benefits from occupational pension schemes, depending on the outcome of an
industrial tribunal hearing which opened in Birmingham yesterday.
The claims, which are being co-ordinated by the TUC, were lodged following a
European Court of Justice ruling in September last year that employers who bar
part-timers from pension schemes could be guilty of indirect sex discrimination.
In an unprecedented move, the 60,000 claims have been put on hold pending the
hearing of 22 test cases at the Birmingham tribunal. They will test key legal
points - including the right to make a retrospective claim and the amount which
can be claimed.
Mr James Goudie QC, leading counsel for the TUC, argued that he was opposed to
setting a two-year limit on the period of retrospection as has been floated by
the Government.
He suggested that if there need be a cut-off point, then a previous 1976
European Court ruling on part-timers would appear to present a more appropriate
date.
If the 60,000 claims are backdated to the 1976 ruling, the TUC calculates that
total compensation could amount to more than #95m and argues this is affordable
given that UK pension fund assets total #500bn.
The 22 test cases, from all around Britain, include teachers, local government
officers, lecturers, bank workers, and NHS employees.
The TUC backing for legal action on occupational pensions forms part of its
two-year campaign to win Britain's 5.4 million part-timers rights to pro-rata
pay and conditions across the board.
TUC general secretary John Monks says the Government and employers must wake up
to the fact that part-time workers deserve to be treated the same as
full-timers.
The hearing is expected to last up to two weeks.
</TEXT>
