<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Post Office staff intercept bomb sent to Labour MP</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES FREEMAN Home Affairs Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356103</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POST Office staff in Glasgow have intercepted a bomb addressed to Shadow
Scottish Secretary Mr George Robertson.
The package contained a home-made device, which, although crude and
unsophisticated, might possibly have caused slight injury had it exploded. It
was spotted at the St Rollox sorting office in Baird Street, Glasgow, where
Labour Party-bound mail is being checked following two previous devices.
Police and Army bomb disposal experts were called and the suspicious package
was examined and made safe. While it was being described unofficially as an
improvised explosive device, one source said the device was a ``whizz-bang hoax
which might conceivably have caused a hand injury''. The Labour Party yesterday
declined to comment.
Explosives experts at Strathclyde Police forensic laboratory at Pitt Street
were last night examining the device. The obvious line of inquiry was the
possible links with the two previous devices received at Scottish Labour Party
headquarters, Keir Hardie House in Lynedoch Place, Glasgow.
These devices, believed to have come from Scottish republican terrorists, whose
avowed aim is to achieve self-government for Scotland by the bomb and the
bullet, caused an acrimonious exchange between the Labour Party and the
Scottish National Party.
The first device arrived in late September, an envelope containing pieces of
metal accompanied by threats to Mr Robertson, but the second, on October 7, was
a more elaborate hoax device.
Although no-one had yesterday claimed to have sent the latest ``bomb'' the
spotlight will inevitably fall on the Scot Adam Busby, currently living in
Dublin, who was named in the High Court as the man behind a campaign earlier
this year to drive out the English which resulted in two lesser figures
receiving lengthy jail sentences for sending fake bombs and threats.
Busby's alleged activities in relation to the Scottish National Liberation Army
have been the subject of a recent investigation by the Scottish police, and The
Herald has been informed that reports have been in the possession of the Crown
Office in Edinburgh for some time.
A number of police forces, including Grampian and Strathclyde, are believed to
have been involved and potential witnesses, including journalists who have been
contacted by Busby, have been interviewed. It is understood that exchanges
between Dublin and Edinburgh have taken place in relation to Busby, but that no
decision has been reached.
A previous attempt to have Busby extradited from Ireland to the UK to face
charges failed, but the changes in legislation in 1994 closed the loopholes
which caused previous hiccups between the countries in relation to allegedly
political offences. The feeling in Dublin is that, if the UK really wanted
Busby back to face a court, there would be no real impediment.
All extradition cases are now handled by the High Court in Dublin and prepared
by the Dublin-based Department of Public Prosecution, which should eliminate
faults in warrants and other vital documents which scuppered many previous
extradition attempts.
</TEXT>
