<HEADLINE>Row flares over plan to visit twin town in France</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By IAIN WILSON Chief Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356105</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FALKIRK Labour councillors were accused yesterday of dumping political
principles as soon as all-expenses-paid foreign trips were waved under their
noses.
Labour leader Councillor William Anderson and Provost-designate Alex Fowler fly
to Paris next month to attend a conference sponsored by the new Falkirk
Council's twin town, Creteil.
The SNP on the council insisted Labour should boycott the conference, whose
title - 24-Hours for the Right of Man - was dismissed as ``the ultimate irony''
because of French nuclear testing in the South Pacific.
SNP leader Councillor David Alexander said: ``I find it incredible that at a
time when France are becoming increasingly isolated within the international
community for the appalling denial of human rights in the South Pacific, Labour
councillors should effectively condone this by their attendance.''
He added: ``It is sad how quickly political principle goes out of the window as
soon as a free plane ticket is waved.''
Councillor Anderson said the SNP knew full well the council had personally
lodged protests about nuclear testing with French president Jacques Chirac, and
also offered Creteil support in making its own concerns known.
Mr Anderson said: ``We have already made political noises and, having discussed
the matter, see no benefit from a boycott. If everyone adopted that attitude,
we might as well close the Channel tunnel, stop boats and planes, and lose our
business and cultural links with France.
``There is no point in being insular. There have been benefits from our good
relationship with Creteil and we do not want to damage that.''
He also denied dropping principles for the sake of a ``freebie''. Under a
reciprocal agreement on exchange visits with Creteil, the towns paid their own
air fares, about #225-a-head, but expenses were covered by the hosts.
Mr Anderson, who will depart on December 7 and return on December 10, said it
was expected nuclear testing would be raised under issues of a general nature
at the conference.
The agenda concentrates on the homeless and underprivileged and is aimed at
discovering how different communities tackle these problems. The conference
will be attended by Creteil's other twin towns in Europe.
However, Falkirk SNP accused Labour of hypocrisy and of paying lip-service to
the nuclear issue.
Monsieur Alexandre Lermany, directeur du Cabinet of Creteil, which is just
outside Paris, said on behalf of Mayor Laurent Cathala: ``It is important that
other people who are against nuclear testing in the South Pacific come here. It
would not help that at all if the Scots did not come.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
