<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000122</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000122</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pressure on Chancellor for Budget to give party better chance of surviving. Tories hope policies can buy time</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GEOFFREY PARKHOUSE Political Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356108</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Prime Minister bought another 12 months in government yesterday with his
programme for new laws next year, but the pressure is increased on his
Chancellor of the Exchequer Kenneth Clarke to provide a Budget in 12 days' time
that would give the Tories a chance of surviving the next General Election.
Tory voters could be attracted by yesterday's Queen's Speech, but it is up to
the Chancellor to persuade them that it is in their interests to keep Mr Major
in power.
Yesterday the pound fell, largely due to the confusion in the United States
where President Clinton is being denied by Congress sufficient money to run the
administration.
A blip in the unemployment figures in Britain added to the unease, and outgoing
Tory back bencher, Mr Julian Critchley announced that he would not vote Tory
next time.
Despite these unlooked-for reverses, the Prime Minister brought in his new
legislative programme of 16 Bills, which are designed to unite the Tories at
Westminster and embarrass the Labour Party.
Labour leader Tony Blair ridiculed this, but Mr Major, with a direct appeal to
Mr David Trimble, the new leader of the Ulster Unionists, shrugged it off.
The Prime Minister set out to establish that he will maintain his stance on
Northern Ireland. There will be no constitutional talks until Sinn Fein
persuades the IRA to start decommissioning its weapons.
However, last night, Mr Major tried to inject new life into the stalled peace
process. He wrote to his Irish counterpart, John Bruton ,in effort to repair
relations following last weekend's angry bout of ``megaphone diplomacy''
between London and Dublin.
The exact proposals being put forward by Mr Major were not being disclosed,
although Downing Street characterised the letter as ``friendly, constructive
and forward-looking''.
In a moving passage in his Commons speech on the legislative programme, Mr
Major asserted that Sinn Fein must denounce punishment beatings and stop
threatening a return to violence if the 15 month-old ceasefire is to be
sustained.
``We cannot move forward at any price. We cannot move forward with the gun held
to our head,'' he said. ``Each assault, each threat, each so-called warning
puts a question-mark in the minds of reasonable people.''
Mr Blair told the Commons that he will maintain the bipartisan approach in a
quest for a permanent solution to Northern Ireland.
The Prime Minister's problems on Northern Ireland lie elsewhere than the House
of Commons at this time.
He said that for the last six weeks Sinn Fein had been declaring a state of
crisis coupled with a warning of a return to violence unless other parties came
quickly to the negotiating table. ``But violence doesn't return of its own
accord like the daffodils in spring,'' Mr Major said.
Ulster Unionist leader Mr Trimble, who commands nine votes in the Commons as
the Government's majority decreases, listened to these words carefully.
There is little prospect that he will help Mr Blair ambush the Government to
get it out of power on any other issue over the next 12 months. So Mr Major has
ensured with his legislation yesterday and his attitude to Northern Ireland
another 12 months in Government.
The 16 Bills for the new session reflect this situation. There is nothing in
them that will cause a split on the Tory back benches. The Prime Minister
confirmed yesterday that Lord Chancellor Lord Mackay's divorce and family
violence legislation will be put to a free vote in the Commons. There is no
significant European legislation to reawaken a Tory revolt.
The proposed new law and order and education Bills are designed primarily to
woo erstwhile Tory voters and to embarrass the Labour Party.
To regain the political initiative the Government, nearly 40% behind in the
opinion polls, has to re-establish itself with its own natural voters.
The Queen's Speech legislation, embracing an expansion of choice and private
finance into schools and tougher measures against criminals and illegal
immigrants, reasserts the Tory mood on these issues.
Mr Blair may be in some trouble as to how to conduct his opposition to these
measures, but the main thrust of the Prime Minister's new legislation is to
recover confidence in his own natural voters.
However, the Budget statement on November 28, handling both state spending and
revenue plans will be the ultimate key to a Tory revival.
Back benchers at Westminster last night were happy with the legislative
programme but they are still in considerable doubt about whether the Chancellor
can handle the dilemmas about tax cuts and Government borrowing and expenditure.
Mr Clarke has already declared that his Budget statement will be crucial to
Tory election chances. By May, the Prime Minister should know whether he can
reverse what now looks like a Blair General Election landslide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000123</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000123</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Computer virus writer jailed</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356110</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A COMPUTER virus writer who called himself the Black Baron was jailed for 18
months yesterday.
Unemployed computer programmer Christopher Pile, 26, from Plymouth, Devon,
appeared for sentence at Exeter Crown Court after earlier pleading guilty to 11
offences under the Computer Misuse Act 1990.
It was the first prosecution under the legislation.
The court heard that Pile designed two computer viruses called Pathogen and
Queeg, names drawn from the Red Dwarf TV series.
He also designed a device called Smeg - another expression from Red Dwarf -
which, attached to the viruses, made them harder to find.
He wrote what prosecutor Brian Lett described as a training manual, enabling
other virus writers to learn how to use Smeg - which was now available
worldwide.
Judge Jeremy Griggs said damage caused, or potentially to be caused, by Pile
could run into millions of pounds.
What he designed and released would constitute a threat for the foreseeable
future, said the judge.
The judge said he could not accept Pile was naive. He must have known the
viruses would cause significant problems to computer users.
``I dare say you were looking forward to reading in the computer press about
the exploits of the Black Baron,'' said the judge.
He told Pile: ``Those who seek to wreak mindless havoc on one of the vital
tools of our age cannot expect lenient treatment.''
Pile pled guilty to five offences of unauthorised access to computers to
facilitate crime, and five of unauthorised modification of computer material
between 1993 and April 1994.
He also admitted a charge of inciting others to spread viruses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000124</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000124</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wage fears over hi-tech jobs `Quality' employment in Lanarkshire may not be matched by Taiwanese firm's pay levels</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAIN WILSON Chief Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356111</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE ``quality'' jobs on offer in Lanarkshire with the arrival of Taiwanese
company Chunghwa may not be matched with ``quality'' wages for hundreds -
perhaps thousands - of workers at the new factory.
In many cases, the basic pay of operatives at the hi-tech plant is likely to
fall below the UK average weekly income of industrial manual workers.
They are more likely to receive around the #4.15-an-hour national minimum wage
which some trades unions want a Labour Government to introduce.
Chunghwa is to build a #260m factory to manufacture tubes for computer monitors
and televisions at Mossend - creating 3300 jobs - under an inward investment
deal struck with the Government, reputedly worth at least #80m to the firm.
But there could be other, hidden, costs to taxpayers if wages are so low that
they need to be topped up with benefits. These range from help to meet rents
and council tax, to family credit.
Chunghwa is currently studying a wage structure taken from a 1995 pay and
conditions' survey of major manufacturing companies in Scotland.
The Scottish Enterprise survey reveals that pay rates - for the electronics
industry already in Lanarkshire - are as low as #3.13 an hour for process
operators, rising to a maximum #4.25 an hour.
The average hourly rate stands at #3.98, or #147.26 for a 37-hour week. A
married man with two children is eligible for family credit if net income is
below #212-a-week.
Chunghwa intends to have some 2400 ``operatives'' at the factory, according to
Lanarkshire Development Agency.
It is expected that pay rates will fall somewhere between that of a process
operator, currently averaging #3.98 an hour, and craft levels which average
#5.93 an hour.
Overtime, bonus, and - most importantly - shift allowances, could boost incomes
by anything between 5% and 10% a week, according to the statistics passed to
the Taiwanese.
In addition to the 2400 operatives, the plant will employ 600 technicians, 200
engineers, 70 administration staff, and 58 management. With their annual pay
likely to range between #10,000 and #50,000.
Agency sources believe the company will aim for the higher end of all wage
scales, not only to attract the calibre required, but to ensure jobs will be
filled.
The Scottish Enterprise survey shows minimum hourly pay rates of #3.60 for
craftsmen and a minimum of #4.30 for technicians, both rising to a maximum of
#7.60.
Their respective averages of #5.93 and #6.28 an hour (#219.41 and #232.36 a
week), stand below the #272 UK industrial average income for manual workers.
But if maximum rates were met, weekly incomes with bonuses would come close to
the UK industrial non-manual average weekly income of #336.
When the deal was announced by an ecstatic Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth
earlier this week, Mr Brian Cole, head of the Asia Pacific desk at Locate in
Scotland, said the jobs offered would be ``quality'' jobs.
There is no question that the jobs involve skills, especially in the
maintenance of the machines which will do most of the assembly work.
However, wages for operatives - which will compare unfavourably with those at
the former Ravenscraig steelworks - are likely to underline just how badly paid
the electronics sector is.
It remains better than some in Lanarkshire, where minimum rates for process
operators in the food and textile industries can be as low as #2.88 an hour.
Meanwhile, Lemac, of Haddington, East Lothian, which lost a computer keyboards
contract to cheaper competition from the Far East, faces laying off more than
half its 420 workforce. A spokesman confirmed talks are underway aimed at
protecting jobs after IBM recently transferred the work to Thailand.
</TEXT>
