<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Woman wins rottweiler damages</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356113</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A WOMAN who brought a civil action after being bitten by a rottweiler was
awarded #1620 in damages and loss of earnings yesterday.
Sheriff William Fulton, who heard it had been the dog's second attack in just
four months, made the award against owners Christopher and Jeanette Yates, of
Corshellach, Kingussie.
Mrs Alice MacDonald of Cluny Terrace, Kingussie, raised the against the Yates,
after she had been bitten and knocked to the ground as she walked to the shops.
Mr Yates claimed Mrs MacDonald should have kept a good lookout and watched
where she was going. He also argued that Mrs MacDonald had been walking too
briskly and bumped into the dog, called King, which was on a short lead. He
claimed Mrs MacDonald had been negligent in that she had a duty to take
reasonable care for her own safety.
Sheriff Fulton disagreed. He ruled in his judgment issued yesterday: ``This
woman was going about her normal business and we can't have people inching
towards street corners and peering carefully and anxiously round them to ensure
a chance encounter with a dog does not occur.''
The court heard King had previously lunged at the throat of a 12-year-old
Kingussie boy.
Sheriff Fulton said: ``I am firmly of the view that, after that incident, the
dog should have been muzzled when being taken in the public streets.''
The dog was muzzled after the attack on Mrs MacDonald and later put down after
contracting a fatal illness.
</TEXT>
