<HEADLINE>Flights `confirm' Dounreay's reputation as world's dustbin Anger at plans for nuclear air cargo</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROSS Highland Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356114</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ENVIRONMENTAL opinion was outraged last night by the prospect, next year, of 14
cargoes of weapons grade radioactive fuel being flown from Germany to Wick, on
route to Dounreay.
Anti-nuclear activists claimed the news that an offical application had been
made to the German Federal Government ministry, for permission to make the
flights, served to underline Dounreay's growing international reputation as a
nuclear dustbin.
The Caithness plant has already confirmed it will try to win contracts to
reprocess several thousand of the 15,000 spent fuel elements currently
stockpiled at research reactors around the world. They had been due to be
returned to their country of origin, the US, but domestic opinion there has
delayed that, and Dounreay is now being viewed as an option.
Many of the fuel rods in this latest German contract were originally
manufactured for the fast reactor at Kalker, which is similar to Dounreay's
reactor.
The German plant, built at a cost of #2400m near the Dutch border, never came
into operation because the Social Democrat Government would not grant a
licence. The programme has since been abandoned.
Yesterday, a German Environment Ministry spokesman claimed the planned flights
``were safe and responsible from a technical point of view''.
However, anti-nuclear activists here were outraged by the planned movements,
which have been secret until now.
Ms Lorraine Mann, of Scotland Against Nuclear Dumping, said: ``This is
extremely worrying and very irresponsible. The people at Dounreay and the
German authorities do not have the slightest care or concern about the very
real dangers to the people of the Highlands. Their only motivation is to make
money.''
In Germany, Green Environment Minister for Hesse, said: ``This involves an
irresponsible risk to the populations of both Germany and Scotland.''
The value of the new contract to the Atomic Energy Authority, which operates
Dounreay, was not known last night, but it is expected to run into many
millions.
Meanwhile, more than #500,000 of public money is to be spent to mop up
radioactive leaks which have led to Dounreay Castle - which sits in the grounds
of the atomic plant - being cordoned off since the contamination was detected
last year.
</TEXT>
