<DOCNO>GH951116-000127</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000127</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Another bomb haul</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356115</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POLICE in the Irish Republic sealed off a farm near the Ulster border last
night after an explosives find, the second in five days in the same area.
The discovery was made at Tonyglasson, County Monaghan, about six miles from
the border. Police will make a full search this morning.
Details of the explosives were not immediately available and detectives could
not say if the find was linked to last Friday's haul intercepted eight miles
away.
The latest find was made in an outhouse of a farm building.
Last Friday, a van loaded with 1700lb of explosives mix was found, with a
further 700lb of explosives located nearby. Police blamed a breakaway
Republican group, the Irish National Republican Army.
</TEXT>
