<HEADLINE>Archbishop urges people to face up to the culture of contempt</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CRAIG WATSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975356116</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Dr Allan Gaw, who works with Professor Shepherd at Glasgow Royal Infirmary,
estimated that a quarter of the target group - men aged 45-64 - would have
moderately raised cholesterol, that is, between 6.5 and 7.8mmol/L, and of these
a half would be able to bring it within safe levels by following
THE culture of contempt in an increasingly cynical world must be confronted by
all Christians, the Archbishop of Canterbury, Dr George Carey, told an audience
in Glasgow last night.
Dr Carey was giving the William Barclay lecture at Renfield St Stephen's Church
entitled ``Called to serve: Christian ministry and mission in a post-modern
world''.
He warned against the ``privatisation of morality'', the day after the
Episcopal Bishop of Edinburgh, the Most Rev Bishop Richard Holloway criticised
calls to return to so-called biblical morality. He said the Bible's moral code
should be updated for every generation.
Dr Carey avoided any direct reference to Bishop Holloway's comments but talked
about ``the dangers inherent in the privatisation of morality''.
He said communism had been replaced by capitalism and a sense of selfishness.
He added that the Christian mission and ministry must adjust to a world that is
losing hope and experiencing excesses of human greed and the destruction of the
environment.
He concluded: ``I firmly believe that in a world where there is no agreement
about shared values, and where a culture of contempt so often holds sway, the
church's mission will be found increasingly relevant and important.''
</TEXT>
