<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cavalryman hurt as horse bolts</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356118</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CAVALRYMAN riding with the Queen's coach was injured when he was thrown from
his horse during the procession for the State Opening of Parliament.
The horseman fell to the ground when his mount bolted close to the Victoria
Memorial outside Buckingham Palace.
The force of the fall snapped the cavalryman's sword.
The Queen appeared not to have seen the accident which happened behind the
royal coach.
Other carriages in the procession to Westminster had to detour around the
injured Lifeguard as he lay on the ground.
Police and ambulancemen lifted the horseman on to a stretcher and into an
ambulance which took him to hospital.
A St John Ambulance spokesman said the cavalryman injured the right side of his
head, his arm, elbow, and hip, and was briefly unconscious.
The horse bolted and returned to the Household Cavalry's stables nearby.
</TEXT>
