<DOCNO>GH951116-000131</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000131</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fury at claims against cheesemaker</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356119</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHEESEMAKER Humphrey Errington has been accused of ``a lack of candour'' in
written legal submissions to the sheriff hearing the Lanark Blue cheese case.
The accusation was made by Mr Neil Brailsford QC, for Clydesdale District
Council, which wants to destroy 44 batches of the cheese worth #60,000.
Details of the legal submissions were released yesterday.
The council claimed in a 19-day hearing before Sheriff J.Douglas Allan at
Lanark Sheriff Court that the cheese should be viewed as unfit for human
consumption because it contained various levels of listeria monocytogenes.
Mr Errington's QC, Mr Michael Jones, sent in his legal round-up to Sheriff
Allan, and this was followed a couple of days later by the council's submission
containing the ``lack of candour'' allegation.
Mr Jones, obviously unhappy about the comment, sent in a second submission,
rebutting the allegation and making counter points.
The cheese had been tested by a food laboratory at Bellshill, and Mr Errington
told the council via a lawyer's letter last December that the amount of
listeria was ``small''.
However, it was revealed during the hearing that the sample tests showed a
listeria level of 6900 cells per gramme.
The case had heard that the Public Health Services Laboratory recommended that
blue cheese should not have a listeria monocytogenes level higher than 1000
cells per gramme.
Mr Brailsford's legal argument claims that Mr Errington was aware of the PHLS
guidelines.
Last night, a furious Mr Errington said at his farm near Dunsyre: ``My evidence
on those tests was quite clear and my lawyer's letter to the council was
accurate.
``We said the level of listeria monocytogenes was small because the overall
reading for listeria was at 6900.
``This was bound to include some listeria monocytogenes which undoutedly would
have been small. All food contains listeria and possibly a little listeria
monocytogenes.''
Mr Errington and his experts maintained throughout the hearing that his cheese
was safe and that the listeria found was harmless to people.
Sheriff Allan is expected to announce his decision towards the end of this
month.
</TEXT>
