<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000132</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000132</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Presidential Blair baits Commoners</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356120</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Lord Chancellor managed to back down the steps to the Throne without
mishap. The Cap of Maintenance did not fall off its ceremonial pole. So the
really tricky bits of Queen's Speech day were successfully accomplished.
The possibility of painlessly reforming constitutional procedures was
demonstrated by the radical innovation of providing three gold chairs for the
Queen's ladies-in-waiting so that, quite properly, they no longer had to stand
beside the Throne while the Queen played one of her constitutional roles as a
rather superior newsreader.
The Commons, who rather go out of their way to shamble along to their
Lordships' House in a manner which stresses the vulgar or popular nature of
their own, are rewarded by being penned into a tiny area which, if a similar
number of sheep or cows were confined there, would have animal rights
protesters abseiling from the glittering galleries in protest.
Back in their proper place, the Commons were not long in living up to their
name. Mr Tony Blair, having said that he could not, of course, drag the Queen
into a political debate, proceeded to do exactly that. Her Majesty might have
been forgiven he thought, if, when presented with the Speech to rehearse, she
had said to herself ``is that it?''
She might have thought she was being hoaxed a second time, mused Mr Blair. The
Labour leader then bowed to tradition by declaring that the Queen's Speech
lacked vision, a line hallowed through annual use by Leaders of the Opposition
down the ages.
A Queen's Speech is occasionally conceded to contain the odd good Bill, but the
L of O points out that they are uncontroversial Bills that his lot would also
have introduced had the electors been more discerning at the last election. But
most Bills are bad, some even dangerous and the thing that no Government ever
shows is ``vision''.
Mr Blair, who was in his running-for-President vein, declared grandly, so we
cannot say we have not been warned, that Britain needed ``a giant of a Queen's
Speech'', and instead the Government had produced ``a pathetic mouse''.
He got rather carried away mocking the Tory back benchers who had apparently
been ordered by their whips not to interrupt him as Mr Blair is usually pretty
good at dealing with interventions. After he had mocked them a bit more,
several Tores rose to the bait and, as he remarked, demonstrated the wisdom of
the original instruction.
On the whole, it was effective stuff, although the odd trace of
sanctimoniousness creeps into a Blair speech. He should take something for it
before it becomes a habit.
Technically within his rights in attacking Tory MPs for sending their children
to private schools, he seemed oblivious to the fact that the London Oratory
school is hardly your average state comprehensive. Scolding the Government for
going for ``whatever can squeeze a headline out of tomorrow's papers'' was,
given the ceaseless activities of his own spin doctors, in the whited sepulchre
class of political utterance.
Britain was crumbling. Mr Major had lurched towards the right to whom he owed
his re-election, an analysis which failed to account for Mr Michael Heseltine's
occupancy of the post of Deputy Prime Minister.
Mr Major seems far more in danger of becoming a prisoner of his own spin
doctors than of the right. He is better being quiet and reasonable. But the
doctors prescribe material which might be described as macho schizophrenic.
First he attacked Mr Blair's ``cheap and silly soundbites'' and ``silly name
calling'' then, barely pausing for breath, said the Labour leader had been
talking ``total baloney'', ``copper plated nonsense'', and ``humbug.'' Humbug
indeed.
He manoeuvred his way round Labour's current favourite statistic that Britain
has fallen from 13th to 18th place in the world prosperity league and, more
tellingly because more convincingly, suggested that while Mr Blair may have
lurched to the right we could feel much less certain about much of the rest of
his party.
Mr Blair then, on points, partly because the Queen's Speech hardly seems to
amount to a coherent strategy and has certainly not got the Government off the
ropes. The Tory problem was illustrated by the confident laughter from the
Opposition side which greeted the only witty intervention of the day.
Mr Gyles Brandreth, seconding the loyal address, was in full flow about the
multifarious attractions of his constituency, the fine city of Chester. ``Two
thousand years of history,'' he enthused. ``And a thousand majority,'' shouted
a voice of doom.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000133</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000133</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Corneliu Coposu</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975356121</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Corneliu Coposu, Romanian politician; born April 20, 1914, died November 11,
1995
CORNELIU Coposu, the respected leader of Romania's opposition who died on
Saturday, was a mild but uncompromising man whose own life vividly mirrored
Romania's harsh ordeal under Communist rule. ``He was a national symbol,'' one
senior opposition leader said. ``A whole world has gone with him. Coposu was
the kind of person whom friends loved and enemies had to respect.''
Coposu, chairman of the National Peasant Party (PNTCD), became the uncontested
leader of the Democratic Convention (CD) opposition bloc after the 1989
collapse of communism. He became identified as the soul of opposition to the
ruling neo-communist Party of Social Democracy in Romania, and the embodiment
of Western democratic values.
He always kept his tall frame erect despite the years and untold tortures he
endured in communist political prisons. Coposu won praise even from his
political rivals, who said they could not help admiring his moral strength,
despite their different political views.
With Coposu as spiritual leader, the CD was cemented by what he used to
describe as a shared dedication to restore the rule of law to Romania, to
dismantle the remnants of communist structures, and to make the country a
genuine democracy.
``Recently I met one of my former torturers in the street. I smiled, pitying
him for lowering himself to torture         people,'' Coposu said in an
interview last year.
Coposu was born in 1916, in the village of Bobota, in Transylvania, then under
Austro-Hungarian rule. Both his grandfathers were Greek Catholic priests who
supported the Romanian national cause in Transylvania, as did his father, also
a priest. Coposu was educated at the Greek Catholic college at Blaj, and at
Cluj University where he studied law.
He joined the National Peasant Party in 1932 and became private secretary to
its leader, Luliu Maniu. During the Second World War, Coposu was closely
involved with British efforts to assist his party, and, after the pro-German
dictator General Ion Antonescu came to power in 1940, helped maintain contact
with Britain to provide political intelligence.
In 1947 Moscow-backed communists took power in Romania and had Coposu arrested
and sentenced to 25 years of hard labour for ``high treason and subversion
against the working class''.
Seventeen years later, when he walked out of jail in 1964, the former
university heavyweight weightlifting champion had lost half his body weight. He
had also forgotten how to speak after spending the final eight years of his
sentence in solitary confinement.
Though he had a degree in legal science, he was not allowed to practise law in
the communist era. He worked for several years as a mechanic on a building site
and then as an economist. He retired in 1976 but, after the 1989 revolt which
overthrew dictator Nicolae Ceausescu, he became one of Romania's most active
politicians.
He underwent lung surgery in a German clinic last year, and was readmitted to
hospital in October where he died following severe breathing and heart
problems. His Swiss-born wife Arlette died in jail after serving 14 years
of a life sentence with            hard labour. Coposu never remarried.
An estimated 60,000 mourners filled the streets of Bucharest on Tuesday for his
funeral. Old and young, many in tears, filed into Revolution Square where
Coposu's coffin was placed on a wreath-laden podium. Taxi drivers draped their
cars with the Romanian tricolour and gipsy flower-sellers sold mauve
chrysathemums to mourners who threw them on to the bier.
The mayor of Bucharest, Crin Halaicu, proclaimed Tuesday an official day of
mourning in the capital, and said that a street and market-place would be named
after Coposu.
President Ion Iliescu, a former communist, now of the ruling Party of Social
Democracy, was on a visit to Egypt and did not attend the funeral. Instead, he
was represented by the speaker of the Senate, Oliviu Gherman, who attracted
boos from the crowd when he spoke.
Coposu was strongly royalist, arguing that only a monarchy could preserve
Romania's dignity as a strong European country. In honour of his beliefs, some
people carried banners for exiled King Michael, who was not allowed to return
to Romania to attend the funeral. However his wife, Anne de Bourbon-Parme, and
two of his daughters were greeted warmly in the capital earlier in the week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000134</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000134</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>I will not vote Tory, says Critchley as he writes off party</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356122</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TORY MP Sir Julian Critchley yesterday revealed he will not vote for the party
at the General Election.
Mr Critchley, who is stepping down from his Aldershot constituency at the next
election, said his decision was based on objections to Mr Christopher Gill, the
anti-European MP for Ludlow, the constituency where he will spend his
retirement.
He would not back Labour or the Liberal Democrats, Mr Critchley said.
He announced his decision in a newspaper article in which criticised the ``less
well-educated, deeply prejudiced and chauvinist'' Tory Party left by Margaret
Thatcher, and wrote off the chances of a Tory election victory.
The timing of the attack, on the day the Government unveiled its legislative
package, will infuriate John Major and his Ministers.
Sir Julian, who has been no stranger to controversy during his political
career, said he could not bring himself to vote for Mr Gill, who was one of
nine Tories briefly kicked out of the parliamentary party over Europe at the
turn of the year.
Sir Julian said Mr Gill, would take Britain out of Europe.
``Gill sits for Ludlow where, it so happens, like Horace, I will spend my
retirement,'' Mr Critchley wrote in London's Evening Standard.
``Should I then vote for Gill at the election? Should any Tory who has been
pro-Europe since the days of Harold Macmillan and a member of the One Nation
group of Tories be obliged to vote for a candidate who not only lost the party
whip in 1994, but voted for John Redwood in 1995 and does not seem to care
whether his party wins or not?
``I shall sit on my hands. Blair's new Labour Party holds no attraction for me
and nothing on earth would persuade me to vote for the Liberals.''
Almost more damaging than the revelation that he will not vote Tory was his
assessment that the Tories were ``unlikely'' to win the next election and would
lurch to the right in Opposition.
``Ken Clarke could pull a rabbit out of the hat, but were we to be defeated in
1996, the rump of the party would be an unattractive blend of English
nationalists, radicals, and populists,'' he said.
``Little Englanders, we would be out of office for eight years or more.''
He predicted that John Major and Michael Heseltine would refuse to lead such a
party and the right-wing Mr Redwood would defeat Mr Clarke for the job.
Former MPs from the right, whom he dubbed a ``mixture of the clever and the
crass'', were lining up for new seats and would change the nature of the party.
Turning to Baroness Thatcher, Mr Critchley added: ``It is all Margaret's fault.
``A simple woman who was too big for her boots, she turned what was essentially
a non-political party, a party of few but essential beliefs. . . into an
ideological crusade, the objectives of which are either unattainable or
undesirable.''
Tory policies were balancing isolation from both Europe and the United States
with an endless quest for worldwide free trade and zero inflation.
``Little wonder Tony Blair is laughing all the way to the bank,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000135</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000135</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Glasgow University's gamekeeper-turned-poacher gives his first major interview to The Herald Principal hits out at funding by results</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>EXCLUSIVE By BARCLAY McBAIN Education Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356123</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CONTROVERSIAL Government scheme to improve academic standards by introducing
performance-related funding in higher education has been opposed by Scotland's
newest university chief.
Professor Graeme Davies, who took over as Principal of Glasgow University last
month, said he did not believe in output-based funding for teaching students.
In his first interview since becoming chief executive of Scotland's biggest
university, Professor Davies told The Herald that the idea, in a consultation
paper sent by the Scottish Higher Education Funding Council to the 21
institutions it funds, could be counter-productive by further threatening
standards. His criticisms are significant because, before coming to Glasgow
University, he was chief executive of the Higher Education Funding Council for
England.
The consultation paper, which has caused widespread concern in Scottish higher
education, said that a move to output-based funding might arise before 1997 but
emphasised that it should not be regarded as council policy.
Professor Davies said: ``I think the funding council was under considerable
pressure from central Government to ask the question because there was concern
that one of the consequences of the expansion in student numbers had been a
drop in standards.
Institutions receive an amount of money for each full-time funded place each
year, taking account of actual enrolments and the previous year's funded
places. However the council says this does not measure output because there are
no guarantees that enrolments convert into qualified graduates.
Funding output would give institutions greater incentives to match student
abilities to courses and encourage them to help students experiencing
difficulties. Funding could be awarded on the basis of final qualifications and
successful completion of a year's study or individual units or other chunks of
learning.
The council concedes there are big drawbacks. With strong financial incentives
to secure outputs, institutions could drop standards to allow more students to
pass.
Access to some courses could be restricted to those students seen to have
better chances of passing, partly because they would need less support, which
has a cost. Institutions could also cut the number of places in disciplines
which had higher failure rates.
Davies also said he would be prepared to ``be at the barricades'' fighting for
the Scottish four-year honours degree, which some fear could be under threat.
``I did a four-year degree and I think it is part of the whole process of
intellectual and personal development,'' he said.
No other university chief can be so well placed to exploit the lessons of
poaching, gamekeeping, and poaching again than Professor Davies. Before he
became funding council chief executive in 1991, Professor Davies was
vice-chancellor of Liverpool University. A New Zealander of Scots and Welsh
descent, he is a career academic who had responsibility for bringing the
polytechnic and university sectors together in a single funding council for
England's 144 HE institutions.''
After about three years in the post, he wanted to return to the academic
community. Glasgow University had then started the search for a Principal to
take over from Sir William Fraser, whose retiral was imminent.
Although offered an extension to his five-year stint with the funding council,
it was an easy decision to come to Glasgow, he said. ``My experience of
Liverpool made it very clear to me that I liked large, multi-disciplinary,
city-based universities which had very strong links with their communities.''
``Glasgow is a university which has all of the structure, background, and look
that I had been seeking,'' he said. There was a rustling of gowns, however,
when it emerged that a part-time senior research fellow's post had been created
for Florence, the new Principal's wife.
Professor Davies said he understood the concerns but pointed out that his wife
was a career academic in her own right. It was increasingly the case that, when
academic appointments were being made, the requirements of a spouse had to be
taken into account. Professor Davies's wife was a research director at Bristol
University when he worked for the funding council in the city.
Researchers are a valuable commodity these days, particularly with the deadline
for submitting research materials for the forthcoming research assessment
exercise looming. On current figures, about #95m a year in public funds will be
riding on the results of the exercise, which will involve institutions'
submissions being rewarded on the basis of a seven-point scale.
The older universities have been so concerned to maintain or improve their
ratings and some of the new ones so determined to make an impact in research
that a transfer market among researchers has emerged. Professor Davies believes
talk of such a market for researchers' expertise and publications is over-rated
but he is concerned about the phenomenon of ``non-traditional'' universities,
particularly in England, seeking to establish a research base overnight.
Not that Professor Davies is against competition. ``There has been some debate
about whether the emphasis on selective funding of research based on quality
should be maintained. I believe it is essential for the country's good.''
Higher education investment is focusing on institutions with the greatest
research strengths and Professor Davies believes that the national policy of
allocating resources to selected centres of excellence should be practised
within the university.
At Liverpool University, he rewarded excellence and sought to use money
selectively to that end. He is a planner who leads from the front. He believes
in consultation but not consensus, which must mean that he will do what he
believes is best for the university, even if it might go against a vested
interest.
He paid tribute to his predecessor, Sir William, whose support during the
handover enabled him to ``hit the ground running''.
The Principal wants to build on the work which has been done to enhance the
university's research ratings since the last assessment exercise to strengthen
further an area which is central to a traditional university's purpose. ``I
would expect over the next three to five years to see our postgraduate activity
grow, particularly in taught masters courses. I would also see the straight
postgraduate base building as well,'' he said.
Professor Davies said Glasgow would have to ``work with the grain of the
community and social change'' to ensure that it had a role in the continuing
professional upgrading of graduates.
The Government's policy is to consolidate student numbers and Professor Davies
does not expect to see Glasgow's undergraduate body growing. He believes the
university has the necessary breadth and depth among its undergraduates,
continues to recruit students in the numbers, and of the calibre, it requires,
and has systems in place to monitor and maintain quality.
At a time of intense competition for scarce resources in the higher education
sector, the Principal argues that institutions should more than ever play to
their strengths and avoid being sidetracked by peripheral issues. Scotland
already boasts a participation rate in higher education of 40% among its young
people and if expansion is to come along again Professor Davies would like it
to be strategic, reflecting the different skills and aims of different
institutions.
That implies more of a planning role for the Scottish funding council,
something which it lacks and is sensitive about. Perhaps Professor Davies, the
former gamekeeper who jokes that his experience on that side of the fence might
make him a better poacher, knows something we don't.
</TEXT>
