<HEADLINE>US networks in bid for Dianorama</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356124</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALL major American television networks were yesterday competing in the auction
for rights to Panorama's interview with the Princess of Wales.
Although no deal has yet been struck, it seems likely the one-hour interview
will be seen by vast numbers around the world - with a potential audience of
200 million in the US alone.
``I think you can assume that all three networks are interested,'' an ABC
source said yesterday. ``We are in discussions and I am sure CBS and NBC are as
well.''
As soon as the programme, to be shown on BBC1 on Monday, was announced, BBC
Worldwide was inundated with calls from television stations around the globe.
A spokeswoman said yesterday: ``There was a lot of enthusiasm yesterday and now
we are getting down to the nitty gritty of negotiations. It's normal practice
to license a programme to just one broadcaster in each territory.''
The unprecedented interview is expected to break all the BBC's international
sales records for a single factual programme. Thatcher: The Downing Street
Years grossed $1m in overseas sales.
The BBC will also show the Panorama programme on its own international
satellite station BBC World, available to 43 million homes with dishes or cable
but it has not been decided when.
Palace officials fear the interview could have lasting consequences for the
monarchy. However, the text of the interview is being kept a closely-guarded
secret by the BBC.
