<HEADLINE>Anger as forestry sale goes ahead</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By MARGARET VAUGHAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356126</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXCLUSIVE
BRITAIN'S biggest sale of public forests is to go ahead near Sanquhar,
Dumfriesshire.
The four forests comprise 9000 acres of prime woodland in Upper Nithsdale, in
the constituency of Trade and Industry Secretary Ian Lang.
The Forestry Commission confirmed its decision to sell in a letter to Mr John
Davies, who, before he retired, was the Forestry Commission's Conservator for
the south and the west of Scotland.
Opponents say the sale of the forests, Euchanhead, Polskeoch, Shinnelhead, and
Cairnhead, will destroy a major source of jobs and recreational land in the
area and put at risk rare birds, including eagles and goshawks.
Mr Davies said the sale would make it impossible for the Forestry Commission to
guarantee continuity of supplies for the timber industry. ``What it amounts to
is that, in the last twinges of this Government, they will make it impossible
for the Forestry Commission ever to expand again. They are destroying its
core.''
He added: ``The Forestry Commission is a good viable industry in Scotland,
creating jobs and recreational activities. Now it is all being sold off. It is
simply privatisation by the back door.''
Mr Davies said he had been unable to get support from Mr Lang who had
``acquiesced'' in the sale of a source of jobs in an area where unemployment
was at 26%.
An attempt to get a public-access agreement in place before the sale is to be
made at a meeting of Dumfries and Galloway Regional Council's planning
committee.
Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson said last night: ``There is no doubt
that this is privatisation by the back door. Such huge sales in Ian Lang's
backyard smack of a scorched-earth sales policy in advance of the election.''
The Herald disclosed yesterday how only one woodland sold by the Forestry
Commision in Scotland was covered by a public-access agreement.
Since the Forestry Commission began selling off woodland in 1981, as part of
the Government's privatisation programme, 801 forests in Scotland have been
sold, covering around 180,000 acres.
</TEXT>
