<HEADLINE>Forsyth's vision for Scots Bid to thwart home rule lobby</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN McGREGOR,PARLIAMENTARY CORRESPONDENT  ROBBIE DINWOODIE,SCOTTISH POLITICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356127</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A TACTIC to steal the thunder of constitutional reformers will be used by
Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth when he takes on the home rule lobby by
setting out his own agenda for change on St Andrew's Day.
In tandem with the Government's policy proposals contained in the Queen's
Speech yesterday, Mr Forsyth announced that he would make his own speech on
November 30, the day on which the Scottish Constitutional Convention will
launch its plans for a parliament in Edinburgh.
His own vision for Scotland's future political structures will build on the
``taking stock'' process started by his predecessor, Mr Ian Lang.
It is understood that Mr Forsyth will propose that much more wide-ranging
legislative powers be given to the Scottish Grand Committee, reducing
Westminster's role in the passing of Scottish Bills. An enhanced role for
Scottish Questions is also understood to be under consideration.
Bringing more parliamentary sessions North of the Border is unlikely to satisfy
the demands of home rulers, however, and Mr Forsyth's plan to make his
announcement on November 30 brought derision last night from the convener of
the convention.
Canon Kenyon Wright said: ``This was entirely predictable. It is a kind of
compliment to the convention that everything Mr Forsyth says and does is a
reaction to our work.
``We will judge him on the single acid test: does he give further democratic
control to the Scottish people? The day he does that, I might say how wonderful
it is that he has changed.''
Mr George Robertson, Shadow Scottish Secretary, said of the idea that ``taking
stock'' might be extended: ``We have heard all this before and I don't think
the Scottish people will be impressed this time round. If he is recognising
that there is a demand for real change, then we will welcome that conversion,
but people want devolution and will not settle for anything less.''
Opposition parties condemned the Queen's Speech as the worst in living memory;
short on vision and representing the ``fag-end'' of an administration.
As he launched the Scottish sections of the Queen's Speech yesterday, Mr
Forsyth said: ``I will use the St Andrew's Day speech to spell out my
proposals, which will be new and workable. The Opposition, meanwhile, are
serving up the same cauld kale het up.''
He claimed that the one thing Labour could not say was that the Government had
run out of steam, because the Queen's Speech was ``bursting with Bills'' and
there was ``a good programme for Scotland''.
He claimed that most people would see a ``golden thread'' running through the
Government's proposals, which would give individuals more choice about their
own affairs, and would build on what the Tories had started in 1979.
A further hint of how Scottish legislation might be treated in future was given
in the Lords last night by the Government's senior spokesman in the Upper
House, Viscount Cranborne.
He referred to the treatment of the Children (Scotland) Bill in the last
session, which he said had benefited from from the taking of evidence in
Scotland before its detailed consideration in Parliament.
He told peers: ``If a Scottish Bill were to start in your Lordship's House in
this session, it might conceivably benefit from similar attention. I hope
therefore to discuss, with the usual channels in the first instance, whether it
might be desirable and practicable that, by way of an experiment, a Scottish
Bill might be committed to a committee with power to meet and take evidence in
Scotland.''
He said he would be interested in any general reaction from peers to the idea.
Central to Mr Forsyth's initiative will be a Bill to tighten control on raves,
which will be dealt with through the special committee procedure.
