<HEADLINE>Trial drug reduces heart risk</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN MacDERMID</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356129</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A DRUG pioneered by Scots can reduce the risk of heart attacks by one third,
doctors revealed yesterday.
More than 6500 middle-aged men have taken part in a seven-year experiment using
a cholesterol-lowering agent, pravastatin.
The long-awaited outcome - 31 lives saved and 70 heart attacks prevented - is
the clearest endorsement to date for the use of such drugs to prevent heart
disease.
The results of the trial - the West of Scotland Coronary Prevention Study
(Woscops) - were unveiled at the annual meeting of the American Heart
Association in Anaheim, California.
The announcement by Professor Jim Shepherd, professor of pathological chemistry
at Glasgow Royal Infirmary, was sent through a satellite link-up to his
colleagues at Glasgow University.
Half the subjects were assigned at random to receive the drug and the other
half were given a placebo. It is only recently - with the breaking of the code
so that the data could be assessed - that the participants - all aged 45 to 64
on recruitment - have learned which they were taking.
Woscops is the largest clinical trial so far of any drug in the statin group,
which inhibits an enzyme involved in cholesterol manufacture, and it is the
first trial of pravastatin on subjects who have never had a heart attack but
who, by virtue of their raised cholesterol levels, were at risk.
It also differs from previous trials in comparing not only deaths but other
events. Professor Shepherd said it reduced the risk of heart attack by 31%, the
risk of death from cardiovascular disease by 32%, and the need for heart
surgery or other specialist treatment by 37%.
Unlike some previous trials of cholesterol-lowering agents, deaths from all
causes were also lower - by 22%.
Over the five years in which the drug was being administered, at 40mg a day,
Professor Shepherd said that, for every 1000 men treated, 20 heart attacks,
seven deaths from coronary heart disease, two deaths from other causes, and 22
major heart operations had been prevented.
He added: ``We are in the process of calculating the financial savings which
would accrue from these savings in morbidity and mortality. We have shown that
people who have never had a heart attack can benefit from pravastatin''
The cost of the drug is about #20-#30 a month but Professor Ross Lorimer, a
member of the Woscops executive committee, said there was no question of the
general population in the trial age group taking pravastatin.
``There is no doubt that the basis of heart disease prevention will continue to
be lifestyle - smoking, diet and exercise - but a group of people for whom that
is not enough will benefit from this treatment.''
