<HEADLINE>Heseltine recovers after operation</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356130</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MICHAEL HESELTINE was recovering in a private clinic yesterday after a
successful operation to remove a kidney stone.
The Deputy Prime Minister will remain at the central London hospital until
later in the week while doctors monitor his progress.
He was said by aides to be ``in good heart and well on the road to recovery''
following surgery yesterday.
The Cabinet Office has given only the briefest details on Mr Heseltine's
condition and his stay in hospital.
A statement yesterday said: ``Mr Heseltine will be leaving hospital later this
week and intends to return to work on Monday November 20.''
It is assumed he will return to his Oxfordshire home to see out his period of
recuperation - probably in the company of ministerial red boxes - before
getting down to the business of government and parliamentary work next week.
</TEXT>
