<HEADLINE>Minister in clash over tendering</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES HORSBURGH Local Government Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356132</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Local Government Minister George Kynoch clashed again yesterday with
council leaders.
Mr Kynoch took councils to task over their alleged behaviour during a temporary
halt to compulsory competitive tendering.
He said allegations had been made that some authorities were exploiting the
moratorium on CCT during reorganisation to retain more work for their own
direct labour organisations at the expense of private contractors.
He threatened to reconsider the halt to tendering if abuses occurred.
But the Labour-led Convention of Scottish Local Authorities accused the
Minister of dealing once again in ``innuendo and unsubstantiated allegations''.
Cosla president Rosemary McKenna said that, if the Minister believed there were
improprieties taking place, then he had the powers to investigate them. ``Let
him do so,'' she said.
Mr Kynoch said tendering was suspended to allow councils to concentrate on the
reorganisation of local government.
``The suspension was not intended to provide the opportunity for councils to
bring work back in-house, to increase staff numbers, or to disregard
considerations such as value for money. Such behaviour is irresponsible,'' he
said.
Complaints from private contractors have apparently centred around road work
and building maintenance. It has been claimed that, as contracts expire, the
work is being returned to council staff.
CCT was suspended from March 1995, with the exception of construction work
worth more than #500,000.
Contracts are due to be up and running again by July 1997 for roads and
building maintenance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000145</DOCNO>
