<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356133</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S sheep farmers are still losing millions of pounds a year through lamb
losses and lameness, it was revealed at a national sheep conference at Malvern
in Worcestershire yesterday.
Up to a tenth of the 40 million-strong national sheep flock may be lame in any
given year, according to preliminary results of a new study unveiled at the
meeting.
In addition, lamb mortality is still estimated to be around 15%, although this
could be cut to under 10% if all the current knowledge was correctly applied on
the farm.
Farmers often bought in disease and complaints such as lameness, said Dr Mike
Johnston of the Royal Veterinary College at London University. ``There are a
tremendous number of units that do not follow quarantining rules on new
purchases for the flock.''
He warned delegates that the new animal welfare code for sheep would demand a
properly managed programme setting out health and husbandry activities.
Lameness would be a key concern.
Early findings of a Ministry of Agriculture-funded survey carried out by the
college showed that 92% of respondents reported lameness in their flocks, with
an average 9.7% incidence in the susceptible population. Extrapolated to the
national flock, this meant there were 3.9 million lame sheep during the survey
year.
Almost 90% of the causes were scald, footrot and soilballing in the hoof. The
majority of farmers used Formalin footbaths to control footrot. ``But this only
does half the job with the sheep trotting through more on a wing and a
prayer,'' Dr Johnston said, urging the adoption of zinc sulphate solutions.
He also accused farmers of being over-zealous in trimming sheeps' feet, almost
down to the main artery in some cases. He rejected the old maxim ``if you don't
draw blood, it's not properly trimmed''. The study is being continued.
Also speaking at the conference, which was organised by the National Sheep
Association and Ciba Animal Health, Dr Agnes Winter of Liverpool University's
Veterinary Field Station said lamb mortality remained far too high at 15%,
particularly as there were no new diseases to contend with.
``The majority of prime causes of death are down to factors which have been
known about for years and for which good preventative strategies are available,
or if prevention falls down, diagnosis and appropriate treatment can be
implemented. It is possible to keep lamb losses down to less than 10% if all
our current knowledge is correctly applied.''
It could also be worthwhile taking on extra labour at lambing time to cut down
on the vast losses. On average these are 170 to 200 dead lambs in a typical
1000-ewe hill flock with a lambing percentage of 110% and up to 300 on a
lowland flock of 1000 lambing at 180%.
``At even #1 per kilo potential, that is a huge financial loss, over #10,000 in
the latter example,'' she said.
Meanwhile, mobile sheep dipping contractors have reported increases of up to
70% in demand for dipping with organo-phosphorous dips, according to the
National Association of Agricultural Contractors.
The increase comes as opinion is hardening in support of those who advocate a
stricter approach to the control of scab.
An association spokesman said more farmers were learning by experience that
preventive treatments could free them of the anxiety of trying to control scab
once it had become clinically obvious in their flock.
``Well-organised protective plunge dipping at around 50p a head, done by a
contractor certificated to use organo-phosphorous dips, is often cheaper than
injected medication or DIY dipping,'' he added.
Contractor Ian Mowat of Dingwall said his purchase of scab dip this year was
50% up and several new customers had placed orders for work.
In Sussex one contractor found the number of sheep dipped fell from 100,000 a
year to 20,000 after compulsory dipping orders were relaxed. So far this year
he has dipped 35,000 sheep for farmers and new orders are still coming in.
elegates warned about strict new welfare code
Needless lamb losses
are costing millions
</TEXT>
