<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Maid appeal hits target</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356134</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN appeal for cash to save the Maid of the Loch paddle steamer has exceeded its
#200,000 target in less than a month.
Dumbarton district's Provost Patrick O'Neill said yesterday: ``We have exceeded
our target and more money is still coming in.''
The Loch Lomond paddle steamer has been laid up at Balloch Pier since 1981 and
restoration plans by a succession of owners failed.
Three years ago, Mr O'Neill convinced his council it should buy the Maid, the
motorship Countess Fiona, and a stretch of land at Balloch Pier for #55,000 and
make a last-ditch effort to restore the vessel.
Ownership of the Maid is to be transferred next month to the Maid of the Loch
Trust which, in turn, has formed the Loch Lomond Steamship Company, a
registered charity, which will pursue further funding. It is thought that the
final bill could be almost #2m.
A major drawback has been the fact the steamer has been pillaged of valuable
engine parts and equipment by scrap-metal thieves since being taken out of
service.
Trust member John Beveridge said yesterday the fact that the initial #200,000
had been raised in a matter of weeks gave the restoration project credibility.
He added: ``We also now have charitable status, which means we are in a
position to go back to those organisations which previously expressed an
interest and take them up on their offers of donations which will now qualify
for tax concessions. A lot of companies have approached us and it proves there
is a great deal of support for the vessel.''
Applications for funding will also be made to the National Lottery and the
European Union.
Mr Beveridge said: ``The ultimate aim is to get the Maid of the Loch sailing
again but this is only going to be possible through partnership.
``The whole thing is taking off now. It was slow to start with but it is
beginning to snowball.''
The trust hopes that the Maid will be back in service by the summer of 1998.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000147</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000147</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Security inquiry after paint attack</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356135</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SECURITY for politicians was under scrutiny last night after protesters threw
paint and flour at Tory Party chairman Brian Mawhinney - and were left free for
20 minutes before being arrested.
It took four 999 calls from Dr Mawhinney's parliamentary aide, Mr Alan Duncan,
before the first policeman arrived.
More than five hours later, an embarrassed Scotland Yard issued an apology for
the delay and announced an investigation into how it happened.
Three women aged between 18 and 20, thought to be from a group protesting at
plans for tighter immigration and asylum rules, were eventually arrested.
The attack, which left Dr Mawhinney clearly shaken, was staged soon after the
State Opening of Parliament.
As he walked towards temporary radio and TV studios in full view of TV cameras,
he was approached from behind and liberally daubed with paint and flour.
With the fluorescent orange paint splattered down his suit from head to toe, he
looked in apparent amazement at the way the protesters remained free from
arrest.
Mr Duncan made four attempts to summon police on his mobile phone. Minutes
later, seeing the demonstrators finally leaving, he ran after them and
threatened them with a citizen's arrest.
A crowd of media and onlookers grew as Mr Duncan held the group for several
minutes before police arrived to assist him.
Scotland Yard said later: ``The Metropolitan Police Service apologises to Dr
Brian Mawhinney and his colleagues for any further distress caused by the delay
in police attending the incident on Abingdon Green this afternoon.''
Dr Mawhinney, 55, whose hair was covered in paint which also penetrated through
his jacket to his shirt, resisted making any criticism of police.
``I don't have any personal knowledge of what the timing was,'' he said.
``Others will pursue those matters.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000148</DOCNO>
