<HEADLINE>Government accused on dumped munitions</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN McGREGOR Parliamentary Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356136</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government was accused last night of ``passing the buck'' over the dumping
of wartime munitions off the South-west coast of Scotland.
The issue was raised in a late-night Commons debate by Labour MP George
Foulkes, who said he and his colleagues were fed up being passed from one
department to another in what appeared to be a ministerial game of pass the
parcel.
What he wanted, he said, was a full survey of the area and the suspension of
all commercial activity until full clearance had been given.
With support from Mrs Ray Michie, Liberal Democrat MP for Argyll and Bute, Mr
Foulkes said meetings with Ministers had been a record of evasion.
He argued that the Ministry of Defence, the Scottish Office and the Department
of the Environment should co-ordinate their actions.
He told the House: ``We want this cleared up and sorted out.''
Liberal Democrat Mrs Ray Michie (Argyll and Bute) warned: ``Lessons must be
learned for the future, if anything more is to be dumped at sea, that we don't
necessarily know how they will react, how they will decompose and what will
come back to haunt us in 30-40 years' time.''
Replying for the Government, Armed Forces Minister Nicholas Soames said: ``This
is a matter which has led to some alarmist speculation.''
He insisted: ``There was never any secrecy about the dumping operations
undertaken at Beaufort's Dyke.''
An estimated one million tons were disposed of at the site. Surviving records
showed some 14,600 tons of five-inch artillery rockets filled with phosgene
were dumped there between July and October 1945.
``There is however no evidence to suggest that any munitions containing nerve
or biological warfare agents were dumped by the MoD in Beaufort's Dyke, the
Irish Sea or the North Channel, and nor did we dispose of radioactive waste in
these areas.''
Preliminary results of water samples taken at Beaufort's Dyke in the summer
showed no degradation in water quality, he said.
Mr Soames said his department had made considerable efforts to locate and
release any material about past sea dumping.
``There really truly are no grounds for accusations of secrecy, cover-ups, or
of complacency.''
Yesterday Defence Secretary Michael Portillo sent MPs a report on past
sea-dumping operations at Beaufort's Dyke.
The report includes a chronology of dumping operations from 1945 until
Beaufort's Dyke was last used in 1976, and an inventory of munitions known to
have been disposed of in the area.
Copies of his report have been placed in the Commons library.
</TEXT>
