<HEADLINE>The selling of Diana plc Dianorama: the commercial and constitutional fallout from a blonde and her bombshell</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM RUSSELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356137</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COULD she be the next Elizabeth Hurley - and much, much more besides? Freed
from the shackles of her royal responsibilities, the Princess of Wales would be
a highly marketable commodity, and, like her rugby-playing, one-time chum Will
Carling, could set herself up as her very own company, Diana Ltd.
She could sponsor sports equipment as tennis players and runners do, or, like
film stars, promote make-up and soaps.
She could augment her income by accepting free use of cars, giving Hello!
magazine access to her home, regularly wearing some designer's clothes, shoes
or hats, using somebody's handbags, although probably not a furrier's furs
because of the animal rights issue, and launch her own perfume. Like Lady
Thatcher and many more she could even give after dinner speeches - for a fee.
She could have her own celebrity newspaper column, like Janet Street-Porter in
the Observer, or Hillary Clinton in the Standard, and while Ms Street-Porter
writes her own words - she was a journalist once - the chances of Mrs Clinton
doing so are remote. The task would, therefore, not tax her command of the
English language since she could have it ghosted. The return from a column
would not be marvellous financially, although, for her name it would be in four
figures at least.
The real value would be in affording her a place from which to air her views on
the issues of the day. And then there would be her memoirs to sell, for which,
given the serialisation possibilities, the sky would be the limit.
The opportunities for the most famous woman in the world to earn a crust would
be limitless, although she would be breaking the royal rules if she dared. But
what is one more broken rule among so many? However, the likelihood is she and
we can only dream about her pot of gold. Although Diana Ltd is an intriguing
prospect, the House of Windsor would never allow her to get to that particular
end of the rainbow.
It will ensure she has no need to earn her living and, given that Prince
Charles has an annual income of around #2.8m a year, while the Queen is the
richest woman in the land, The Firm can afford to keep her in the style she has
become accustomed to.
Some measure of what she would be worth to a company or product she favoured
was assessed recently by Majesty Magazine. It monitored the coverage she was
given by the British tabloids over a two month period, and the amount of free
publicity the products she had used or mentioned received as a result. It came
to more than #1.8m. It is difficult to assess how valuable she is to a
magazine's circulation, but she is due to be on the cover of Harper's next
month and has twice been on the cover of Vogue. Magazines only put faces on
their covers which help sales, although Diana's picture alone is not as good as
Diana's picture and a story. But she invariably provides the latter, as she has
this week.
If there was a fee for an exclusive cover picture it would be in four to five
figures, again nobody will give commercial secrets away.
What Monday's Panorama programme - Dianorama? - will be worth to the BBC the
corporation refuses to say. Sales information was commercially sensitive and
confidential, it said. But it admited to having been in contact with other
television companies world-wide interested in buying the show and that the
details will be finalised over the next 24 hours.
I suggested it was likely to prove a pot of gold for the BBC. ``You might say
that, I could not possibly comment,'' was the reply. But it is possible to
gauge something of the likely return when one considers that the most
successful single programme sold by the BBC abroad was Thatcher: The Downing
Street Years. That brought in $1m and was made after the Iron Lady's fall from
power, whereas the Princess is still married, still in situ, still centre stage.
Mrs Thatcher had also been one of the more prominent talking heads on world
television, let alone on domestic British channels, for decades, whereas the
Princess has scarcity value. She has only twice before talked publicly on
television, as opposed to being shown making a public speech. The first time,
when she got engaged, was almost monosyllabic, and the second was when a film
was made about the Wales's family life at Highgrove.
The Dianorama, on scarcity value alone, must be worth many, many Thatcher
Years. The only programme which could exceed it would be The Queen Mother
Talks, since she has never been known, wisely, to pass an opinion on anything
in nearly seventy years of public life.
The Princess's one-time gym chum, Will, for instance, can earn up to #100,000 a
year from sponsorship deals. An experienced agent - the Princess would
certainly acquire one - can negotiate a contract worth between #50,000 and
#80,000 a year with a suitable company for a Rugby Union player, provided he
treated promotional work as his main occupation and got involved in the life of
the company, not just turned up at photographic sessions and functions in his
spare time. Will, however, has his own company, as Diana would, hence his
ability to earn more without tying himself down to the corporate life.
Personal appearances at the opening of a gas station or supermarket can net
anything from a four figure to a five figure fee, depending on whether you are
an A or B list celebrity.
The Princess would undoubtedly rate higher than the current queen of the
openings, Joanna Lumley, who allegedly can get around #35,000, or some refugee
from Coronation Street like Reg Holdsworth. Indeed, she would be on the A
double plus list. Then there would be pantomime appearances open to her - Di as
Cinderella or Goody Two Shoes? would be a bigger draw than some Australian from
Neighbours - where the fees are astronomical for two shows a day for four
weeks.
Asked recently whether they would feature a Windsor in one of their campaigns,
nine out of ten of the advertising industry's top ``creatives'' said their
clients might prefer it. Using a royal in a campaign would offer the ``ultimate
endorsement'', according to Mr Trevor Beattie, creative director at the agency
TBWA. ``If we had Di driving a Nissan Micra, we'd sell a million,'' he added,
rather cheekily proposing that she could replace the supermodel Eva Herzigova
in his own agency's ``Hello boys'' Wonderbra campaign.
Diana's potential selling power can be defined by looking at that of lesser
personalities. In May 1992, Sainsbury sold 30,000 cartons of creme fraiche. In
June 1992 it sold one million cartons after the starlet, Catherine Zeta-Jones,
was shown using the product to make fresh fruit brulee, while the tennis player
Sue Barker's turkey and apricot bake resulted in sales of 74 tonnes of turkey
strips in one week, 22 times the normal weekly sale.
Michael Jackson's links with Pepsi are well known. His contract was worth
millions of dollars. Over the past decade Pepsi sponsored three of his concert
tours while paying him $20m, during which time, the company picked up two
market share points on its arch-rival Coca Cola.
Nor would the Princess be slumming if she put herself to market. If a man who
became President of the United States could sell washing machines - General
Electric employed Ronald Reagan to that end - there is nothing to stop a woman
who will now probably never became Queen of Britain from doing the same.
Advisers to the Princess of Wales were left wondering last night where they
stand in future dealings with the ``go-it-alone'' royal, after her
extraordinary decision to talk publicly about her troubled life.
Senior aides have clearly been shocked by the Princess's decision not to
consult them.
Not even the Princess's private secretary, Patrick Jephson, or her press
secretary, Geoff Crawford, knew about her interview for BBC1's Panorama
programme, due to be screened on Monday.
Her solo tactic leaves her advisers now attempting to assess the possible
consequences of what she has to say.
Buckingham Palace does not intend to ask the BBC for a preview of the hour-long
interview.
The Princess agreed to talk to the current affairs programme about her family,
marriage break-up, and future plans.
She has chosen to air private thoughts on prime-time TV rather than address any
grievances privately within the royal family.
Despite the separation of the Prince and Princess of Wales, the Queen has
always kept an ``open door'' for her daughter-in-law.
The Princess, accused by commentators of seeking revenge against her estranged
husband, now risks not only further distancing herself from her staff but also
from senior royals.
Palace officials fear the interview could have lasting consequences for the
monarchy.
Everything depends on the exact text of the interview, which is being kept
secret by the BBC.
The Princess's decision has taken the royal family into uncharted waters and
officials are now trying to keep a steady course.
Major television networks across the Atlantic are lining up for the Panorama
programme. North America dwarfs all other media territories in terms of
audience sizes and money-spinning potential and Americans are fascinated by the
royal family.
``I think you can assume that all three networks are interested,'' an ABC
source said yesterday. ``We are in discussions, and I am sure CBS and NBC are
as well.''
CBS spokeswoman Sandy Genelius said: ``We have expressed an interest. There's
an appetite and curiosity over here about the royal family. Princess Diana
makes headlines here, too.''
As soon as the programme was announced, BBC Worldwide was inundated with calls
from television stations around the globe.
A spokeswoman said: ``There was a lot of enthusiasm and now we are getting down
to the nitty gritty of negotiations.
``It's normal practice to license a programme to just one broadcaster in each
territory.''
The unprecedented interview is expected to break all the BBC's international
sales records for a single factual programme.
Thatcher: The Downing Street Years grossed $1m in overseas sales.
The BBC will also show the programme on its own international satellite station
BBC World, available to 43 million homes with dishes or cable, but it has not
been decided when.
Constitutional expert Lord St John of Fawsley said yesterday the Princess would
be wise to remember that those who lived by the media eventually died by the
media.
She was embarking on a ``dangerous and risky'' strategy by giving the
interview, said the former Tory Cabinet Minister.
But she had a ``perfect right'' to make the broadcast, and he did not see it as
an act of revenge but as a desire on her part to put her case.
``An interview is now accepted as part of the normal currency of public life.
It really does depend on how the Princess handles it, what she says,'' he said.
``I do think, however, there is a responsibility on the BBC. There should in
these situations be a certain self-restraint, a certain self-censorship,
because this isn't just another married couple.
``I don't think the BBC should have refused it (the interview). What I am
calling for here is some self restraint in the questioning and some prudence in
the Princess.''
Lord Deedes, former editor of the Daily Telegraph, said the Princess's decision
to give a TV interview ``tells us a good deal about the qualities of the
Princess, and the qualities of the BBC''.
He said: ``The first question in my mind is how right it was in a sense to
exploit this by persuading the Princess to take part in this broadcast without
the Queen's knowledge?
``Secondly, in the long run, I fear this may have the very opposite effect of
what she (the Princess) hopes to do, because although I am sure there will be a
lot of people looking at it, in the long run the people whose respect she
desires to recruit will think the worse of her over this.''
</TEXT>
