<HEADLINE>Labour tells Government it's time to go, as it attacks `irrelevant' Tory measures Major denies he is running out of ideas</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By BENEDICT BROGAN Political Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356138</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE measures proposed in the Queen's Speech are commonsense policies designed
to confirm the Conservatives as the true one-nation party of Britain, Mr Major
declared yesterday.
Denying he had run out of ideas, Mr Major accused Labour leader Tony Blair of
indulging in juvenile point-scoring while backing policies that would destroy
the Union.
In the first day of debate on the 16 Bills contained in the Queen's Speech, Mr
Blair accused Mr Major of leading a ``tired, inept and incompetent''
Government. ``It is time for them to go,'' he said.
Mr Major accused Mr Blair of talking humbug and claimed 16 years of
Conservative rule had delivered low inflation and the most secure platform for
prosperity the country had known in generations.
He warned that Labour's response to the Queen's Speech would be a ``lithmus
test'' for its position on issues that matter to the electorate, confirming
suggestions that this year's legislative programme has an overt political
purpose to ``smoke out Labour''.
However, Mr Blair dismissed the contents of the Queen's Speech as irrelevant to
the true needs of the British people. The Tories had ``been there too long,
they have told too many lies, they have made too many mistakes, they have
nothing to offer the future of Britain.''
In reply, Mr Major compared Mr Blair to a political chameleon, who changed his
colour depending on the issue. His attacks on the Government's record were
``humbug at its very worst''.
Rejecting Mr Blair's appeal to one-nation Tories to back Labour, Mr Major
reasserted the Tories' claim to the title. ``There is only one party and it's
mine that is truly the one-nation party of this country,'' he said.
Labour's constitutional policies would split the country. ``You would start by
dividing up the UK and covering it with a rash of assemblies''. That, and
Labour's willingness to accept the European Social Chapter, would divide the
Union.
The Prime Minister positioned himself on the centre-right of politics, by
emphasising that he favoured neither laissez-faire economics nor the
nanny-state. He grew up dependent on schools, hospitals and welfare, he said.
``I'm not going to kick away the ladder that I climbed as a boy.''
Mr Major took a number of interventions from Labour MPs, who challenged him to
accept Mr Blair's suggestion that consideration of the Asylum Bill be handled
by a special standing committee, free of party politics.
He rejected the suggestion. Asylum abuse was a serious problem, he said.
To safeguard his slim majority of six, Mr Major announced to MPs that the
contentious clauses of the Domestic Violence Bill would be subject to a free
vote, after anti-divorce MPs tried to block the Bill's inclusion in the Queen's
Speech.
In his speech Mr Blair accused the Government of playing party politics with
the Queen's Speech which, he said, was thin on substance. ``The reaction of
most people would be `is this it?','' he said.
He backed the Government over its approach to Northern Ireland. However, for
the rest it was ``the programme of a party which has ceased to have any real
vision or purpose in Government at all. It is about the interests of the Tory
Party cobbling together any old bric-a-brac of legislation that can keep the
Conservative Party in one piece.''
Labour was unlikely to oppose some of the legislation contained in the Speech,
in particular the Broadcasting Bill and defence measures. But on others, such
as education, Mr Blair promised tough resistance.
On the Government's immigration proposals Mr Blair insisted: ``We oppose bogus
applications and fraud and we recognise the need for immigration controls.
However, race and imigration should not be a plaything of party politics.''
The Government was seeking to put Labour on the spot. ``It is a tawdry
demeaning low-life exercise in political tactics. It is everything about using
Government as a propaganda machine and it is nothing about the interests of
Britain as a country,'' he said.
Liberal Democrat leader Paddy Ashdown said the Speech was ``going through the
motions.
``This Government now has nothing further to say to this nation, except `please
vote for us because we are going to give you a tax cut'.'' He added: ``This is
a cut and run programme designed to be ditched at any time for an early
election.
``These are fag-end measures from a fag-end Government''
Labour's George Foulkes (Carrick, Cumnock and Doon Valley) said: ``This is a
Queen's Speech designed to try to cling onto power at the next election. It's
going to be a vain attempt.''
He protested that the nursery voucher scheme would take money out of the public
sector.
q.During the debate, Mr Michael Martin (Glasgow Springburn) protested about
``rigid'' formulas used by the Child Support Agency in assessing payments made
by absent parents.
Calling for a review to examine the agency's work in ``a humane fashion'', he
warned that the people who had been hardest hit were men and women trying to
keep up a relationship with their children.
THE proposed legislation in the Queen's Speech includes:
q Asylum and Immigration Bill - designed to crack down on bogus asylum seekers.
q Family law legislation - will end ``quickie'' divorces and introduce no fault
divorces after one year south of the Border.
q The Criminal Procedure and Investigations Bill - would introduce a statutory
scheme for disclosure of material prior to criminal trials to cut prosecution
information to defence lawyers.
q Security service legislation - to enable MI5 to tackle organised crime and
drug dealing.
q Nursery education legislation - to allow parents of every four-year-old to be
given a voucher to buy three terms of nursery education in either the state,
voluntary or private sectors
q Schools legislation - to lift the bar on grant-maintained schools borrowing
commercially
q Student loans legislation - to allow students to get their subsidised loans
from private suppliers rather than just the public sector Student Loans Company
q Channel Tunnel rail link Bill - to allow construction by a private sector
company of a high speed railway between the tunnel at Folkestone and London's
St Pancras station
q Broadcasting Bill - to loosen media rules to adapt to the technological
revolution and allow greater media cross ownership
q Housing and construction legislation - will give more tenants south of the
Border the right to buy their homes.
</TEXT>
