<HEADLINE>Official backs private finance</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES HORSBURGH Local Government        Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356139</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE new Labour-controlled City of Edinburgh Council could be the first in the
UK to put together a major package of projects involving a partnership between
the public and private sector under the Government's Private Finance Initiative.
Mr Tom Aitchison, chief executive of the new council, told members of Edinburgh
Chamber of Commerce and Enterprise yesterday that it would be impossible to
fund the proposed transportation projects from traditional public sector
sources.
The way forward, he said, was through the PFI. This was consistent with central
government policy and should lead to an increase in the availibility of
Government funding.
Financial consultants Morgan Grenfell had been acting as advisers to Lothian
Regional Council and key decisions on the projects package could be expected in
the spring. The new city council takes over on April l.
The most likely approach would be to set up an Unincorporated Joint Venture
(UJV) or partnership which would be in effect a new compnay involving public
and private sector interests.
Its policy would be set by the council and it would be charged with delivering
a package of projects.
While major construction work was undertaken by the private sector, the council
would act as regulator, setting standards.
Among the projects most likely to be undertaken would be the building of new
rail stations at Edinburgh Park and Gogar, city centre pedestrianisation and
traffic calming measures and the Greenways project to create dedicated road
space for public-sector transport vehicles.
</TEXT>
