<HEADLINE>New radium inquiry at Dalgety Bay beach</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER REEKIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356140</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN inquiry is under way into the radiological risk from radium contamination at
Dalgety Bay beach in Fife, the Scottish Office said yesterday.
It is an extension of surveys carried out by the National Radiological
Protection Board after radium contamination was discovered at the beach in 1990.
Those concluded that the radiological risk to the public was insignificant.
However, it was agreed that there should be a more detailed study.
A Scottish Office spokesman said Dalgety Bay Community Council had asked for
more to be done.
The new work is being carried out by Aberdeen University for the Industrial
Pollution Inspectorate.
A final report, which is expected to be available by April, will give findings
and recommendations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000153</DOCNO>
