<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Call for more rail spending</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ALISON DANIELS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356141</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SCOTTISH pressure group last night called for more spending on railways and
an end to the Scottish Office's apparent preference for road building.
The Scottish Association for Public Transport, responding to a demand from the
Confederation of British Industry for a national transport strategy, accused
the Scottish Office of pursuing an unbalanced and environmentally irresponsible
multi-million pound spending spree on roads.
The association's chairman, Dr John McCormick, also criticised the Scottish
CBI's support for high public spending on roads.
Instead, the association suggested improved urban and intercity rail freight
transport links, a light rail system in Edinburgh and Glasgow and better air
and ferry links from Scotland to the Continent.
Dr McCormick calculated that the cost of current and proposed road schemes came
to #887m while he said capital expenditure on rail improvements in Scotland was
zero.
He added that this month's fall in Glasgow Airport passenger numbers was a
symptom of bad transport planning.
``In England, the BAA and other airport and local authorities have invested in
rail links to airports. In contrast, Scottish planners are backing the #250m
10-lane M74 extention. The M74 is unlikely to escape public spending cuts and
will, if built, quickly be saturated by urban traffic as demonstrated by the
M25,'' he said.
The call came as protesters campaigning against the M74 motorway link, which
will cut through the south of Glasgow, dumped bags of so-called toxic waste
outside the City Chambers yesterday.
Dressed in boiler suits and green masks, members of the Residents Against the
M74 said the bags contained contaminated soil from areas in Rutherglen and
Cambuslang near to chromium waste sites.
Campaigner Rosie Kane renewed the group's demand for a public inquiry.
Ms Kane said residents were concerned about the health effects of the motorway
and the impact of construction on the chromium waste sites in the path of the
road.
</TEXT>
