<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000154</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000154</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Redwood call for action on crime</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356142</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TORY former leadership candidate John Redwood last night challenged the
Government in the Commons over law and order.
Mr Redwood, the former Welsh Secretary defeated by Mr Major in July's contest,
also reiterated his call for #5000m tax cuts during the Queen's Speech debate.
He said on the crime issue: ``The balance is still not right. Too many
criminals are still getting away without being detected, too many criminals
seem to be able to get through a trial when the evidence looks quite strong
against them.
``Home Secretary Michael Howard must again look at this balance.''
Mr Redwood (Wokingham) told the Commons the public backed the Government's
commitment to law and order, lower tax and a strong defence.
He said: ``There are measures in the Queen's Speech which tackle the issues of
crime and housing and education which only Conservatives can do.''
But he added: ``We do need more choice in the public services, higher quality
in the public services, stronger action on law and order.''
</TEXT>
