<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000155</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000155</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>W Lindsay Ross</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975356143</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
W Lindsay Ross, the treasurer of Queen's Park Football Club and a well-known
Motherwell solicitor, died on Tuesday morning after a short illness. He was 74
LINDSAY ROSS had been a partner for many years of the Motherwell solicitors
Messrs Marshall Ross and Munro, and at the time of his death still acted as
consultant to the firm. It is, however, in the world of association football
that Lindsay was better known.
He attended Hamilton Academy where he made his mark as an up-and-coming young
footballer. After wartime service with the Royal Air Force he joined Queen's
Park in 1947 and made his debut for the club on February 14, 1948, at Hampden
Park against Dundee. He played a total of 54 matches for the Queen's Park First
XI, concluding his career on April 26, 1955, a matter of days before his 34th
birthday.
Such was Lindsay's expertise in business and in football that he was invited by
the club to join the committee, going on to become president from 1968 to 1971.
After his term as president he was appointed treasurer, a position he still
held at the time of his death.
The burdens of a Queen's Park treasurer have always been onerous but never more
so than over the past few years with the advent of the Hampden redevelopment
plans.
As treasurer Lindsay Ross was very much to the fore in all negotiations
surrounding the new project and one of his greatest wishes, which will now be
denied him, was to witness for himself the totally refurbished Hampden Park
which he, along with other members of the committee, had strived so hard to
make a reality.
He will be remembered not only as a sound administrator with an eagle eye for
detail but also as a man of quiet dignity. Although football had changed
considerably since the days when Lindsay sported the famous black and white
hoops of Queen's Park, he never lost touch with the reality of present-day
football and his wise counsel was often requested and adhered to by modern-day
players.
He will be fondly remembered by the legal profession, especially in his native
Lanarkshire, but it is perhaps at Hampden where his loss will be most deeply
felt. Although his health had not been of the best in recent months, he still
found time to attend and contribute to the club board meetings, and only last
Saturday was in his regular place in the directors' box for the club's home
fixture against Caledonian Thistle.
Tomorrow he was due to be on the top table at the club's annual dinner but now
there will be one empty chair. Those, however, who will be attending together
with Lindsay's many other friends and colleagues, will remember fondly a man
who strived endlessly for the club that he loved and for whom nothing was too
much trouble. Lindsay, who lived in Bearsden, is survived by his wife Jean.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000156</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000156</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tenants for Tay House</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>99</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356144</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
After struggling for a couple of years to find tenants, Tay House at Glasgow's
Charing Cross has turned the corner.
Landlord Svenska Handelsbanken, represented by joint agents Richard Ellis and
Knight Frank &amp; Rutley, has leased the third floor of the 162,000 sq.ft building
to Barclays Bank plc.
Some 30,000 sq.ft (2,787 sq.m) has been acquired and the deal is based on a
20-year lease at an initial rent of #390,625 per annum.
The accommodation will be occupied by Barclays Stockbrokers who were attracted
by the building's large, column-free floorplates. The letting follows soon
after the 20,000 sq.ft letting to the Royal Bank of Scotland plc.
Craig Ritchie, of joint letting agents Richard Ellis, said: ``Discussions are
ongoing with potential occupiers for the remaining two floors which can provide
space from 5000 sq.ft up to a total of 40,000 sq ft.''
Barclays Property Holdings advised Barclays Bank plc throughout the
negotiations.
Tie Rack has also found new premises. It has relocated to 116 Princes Street in
Edinburgh, adjoining Debenhams department store.
The new unit has a frontage of 12ft 6ins, a ground floor net area of 328 sq.ft
and basement of 355 sq.ft and was acquired on the basis of a new 25-year lease
with five-year rent reviews incorporating mutual break options. A rent free
period was granted.
The landlords, GUS Property Management, were advised by Colliers Erdman Lewis
and Tie Rack by Chrystal Rooney.
On a back-to-back basis, Tie Rack negotiated the surrender of their existing
lease of 134B Princes Street. The surrender will allow the new landlord, ESN,
to undertake a refurbishment and integration of their larger premises at 134B &amp;
C, along with upper floor accommodation which has lain vacant for many years.
ESN was advised in the transaction by Richard Ellis and Tie Rack by Chrystal
Rooney.
</TEXT>
