<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000157</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000157</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Court rules on `time-share child'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356145</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SHERIFF yesterday ruled that a toddler must live with his grandparents, but
his mother should have access for five hours each day.
Miss Elaine Maxwell, 21, went to Falkirk Sheriff Court last week claiming that
her parents, Richard, 52, and Helen, 51, had snatched her 16-month-old son
Craig from her home.
Sheriff Albert Sheehan ordered that the child should be with his mother from
9am to 5pm, and then she had to hand him over to her parents.
Yesterday, however, after studying a social work report, he granted interim
custody of the boy to Mr and Mrs Maxwell, who live round the corner from their
daughter's home in Redding, Falkirk.
Sheriff Sheehan emphasised that the long-term aim was to reunite mother and
child permanently and he gave Miss Maxwell access to her son from noon till 5pm
every day.
The bitter battle started last month when Elaine's parents removed their
grandson from their daughter's home. They claimed they had looked after the boy
since his birth in June, 1994, and that their daughter was not fit to care for
him.
They told the court that her house was ``a haunt of drug addicts'', and said
her boyfriend Roy McKie, who lived there, was a drug addict and alcohol abuser
with ``four pages of criminal convictions''.
The sheriff said yesterday that the Reporter to the Children's Hearing ``at the
moment is satisfied that the child is in no immediate danger''.
He added that police reports showed there was ``some truth'' in the
grandparents' allegations about the state of their daughter's home and her
boyfriend's drugs and alcohol problems, but he said there had been
``considerable exaggeration''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000158</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000158</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wizard debut for teenager</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356146</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A TEENAGER is to give up his #50-a-week job stacking shelves in a supermarket
to take over the lead role in a #2m London West End musical.
Paul Keating, 19, from Romford, Essex, was chosen from 7000 to star with Gail
Easdale, of Glasgow, in The Who's musical Tommy, in which he plays the ``deaf,
dumb and blind kid who sure plays a mean pinball''.
He said: ``I haven't really played any pinball, so I will have to practice.
When I handed in my notice at Tesco's the manager was thrilled. He said I could
have my job back if it all falls through.''
Gail 23, who has previously appeared in tours of Evita and Cats, plays groupie
Sally Simpson. The show opens in March.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000159</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000159</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Unionists defiant over direction of Ulster talks</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356147</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
UNIONISTS yesterday issued a defiant warning that they would not accept any
moves towards a united Ireland.
Their comments came as, in the Commons, the Prime Minister warned Sinn Fein
that it must denounce punishment beatings and stop threatening a return to
violence if the peace process is to be unblocked.
At a joint news conference, Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble, Democratic
Unionist leader Ian Paisley and the independent Unionist MP Robert McCartney
underlined their entrenched opposition to the current direction of the Northern
Ireland peace process.
The conference in London was called to mark the tenth anniversary of the
UK-Irish Agreement, described by the three in a joint statement as an
``anathema'' to the majority of people in the Province.
``We will not be coerced to negotiate within its parameters or on the basis of
its latest manifestation - the joint framework document which we see as a
one-way street to a united Ireland,'' the statement said.
``That is a direction in which the people of Northern Ireland will not move.''
They rejected outright the current ``twin track'' strategy of the British and
Irish governments aimed at establishing an international commission to oversee
the decommissioning of paramilitary weapons while conducting preparatory talks
with the various parties.
Mr Trimble instead reiterated calls for an elected Northern Ireland assembly to
debate the Province's future -a proposal rejected by both Sinn Fein and the
nationalist SDLP.
He accused the SDLP leader John Hume of personally blocking the plan. ``There
is one obstacle. It is not so much the SDLP as John Hume who reacted without
considering the matter fully,'' he said.
In the Commons, Mr Major said: ``We cannot move forward at any price. We cannot
move forward with the gun held to our head.''
``Each assault, each threat, each so-called warning puts a question-mark in the
minds of reasonable people.''
He continued: ``If Sinn Fein are committed to exclusively peaceful methods, as
their leaders claim them to be, there can be no question of violence returning
and let them say that unequivocally.
``If their commitment is real, threats and thuggery should stop. Killing has
stopped. Much else has not.''
Giving examples of recent attacks, he said: ``That may not be murder, but it is
not peace.
``And it is not a way of behaviour that merits Sinn Fein's entry to the talks
until they have changed what they are doing.''
Mr Major said: ``I want to see Sinn Fein denounce such behaviour and stop it.''
Almost every day brought a fresh atrocity - 250 punishment beatings since the
ceasefire.
``Each assault, each threat, each so-called warning puts a question-mark in the
minds of reasonable people.
``I wish to move forward to negotiations involving all parties including Sinn
Fein. I believe that we can. I shall work for that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000160</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000160</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Urgent call for upgrading of 12 major Scottish roads</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356148</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND needs urgent upgrading on 12 major roads as the bare minimum to avoid
crippling traffic congestion and loss of business, the national Freight
Transport Association warned last night.
Speaking in Glasgow, FTA president Graham Miller urged the Government to
abandon ``easy option'' cuts to road building and improvement plans. This would
lead to ``economic and environmental pain,'' he said.
Programmes had already been cut by a third since 1989, when the Government's
own White Paper, Roads to Prosperity, had been regarded as a minimum
requirement. Now there was growing speculation that the axe was poised to fall
once more.
``If the Government is serious about stimulating growth in the economy, then it
cannot expect industry to deliver more goods on a failing infrastructure,'' he
added.
The roads targeted include the A96 Aberdeen to Inverness, the A1 Edinburgh to
Newcastle, the A9 Perth to Inverness, the A75 Stranraer to M74/M6 and the A82
Glasgow to Inverness.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000161</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000161</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Order of boot</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356149</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FISH factory worker who quit her job rather than wear rubber boots has been
awarded #369 compensation by an industrial tribunal in Aberdeen. Ms Jennifer
McIntosh, 24, said she did not want to transfer from the salmon department to
the filleting branch of A J Sutherland, Portsoy, Banffshire, which would have
meant wearing rubber boots, because she suffered from varicose veins. She
resigned instead. The tribunal ruled that by ordering her to make the move the
firm had breached a fundamental condition of the contract of employment and
ruled she was entitled to consider herself as being wrongfully constructively
dismissed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000162</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000162</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bodybuilder `went mad with ecstasy'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356150</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A BODYBUILDER told a court yesterday how ecstasy drove him ``mad''. Mr Brian
Smith admitted he used four or five ecstasy tablets a week in conjunction with
anabolic steroids to make his muscles look good for competitions.
Mr Smith, 30, of 2F Friendship Way, Renfrew, told the High Court in Glasgow the
practice was common among bodybuilders.
He said that taking steroids caused a fluid build-up. Ecstasy had a dehydrating
effect and was used as a counter-balance.
However, the combination of drugs took its toll and he told the court how he
had gone ``mad'' and had been admitted to Dykebar Hospital with severe mental
problems.
Mr Smith was giving evidence at the trial of Mr Steven Coan, 24, Mr James
MacLean, 20, and Mr John McDonald, 26, who deny that, in Glasgow's Marriott
Hotel in July, they were concerned in the supply of 5000 ecstasy tablets said
to have a street value of #100,000.
Earlier this week, Mr Smith's plea of not guilty to the same charge was
accepted.
He did, however, admit possessing ecstasy tablets at his home and will be
sentenced at the end of the trial.
Yesterday, he was called as a defence witness by Mr Coan's counsel, Mr Gordon
Jackson QC, to tell of the day he was arrested when he went for a drink with Mr
Coan at the Mariott Hotel.
He said he had no idea there was a drug deal going on. Cross-examined by Mr
McDonald's counsel, Mr Donald Findlay QC, Mr Smith denied he was a minder for
Mr Coan on the day of the alleged drug deal, and that he was to have been paid
in ecstasy tablets.
Police undercover officers had told the court of an intricate operation which
netted Mr Coan who, it was alleged, was asked by an undercover officer to bring
5000 ecstasy pills to the Marriott Hotel.
The trial continues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000163</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000163</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Inquiry told of councillors' hire and fire powers Claims over son of council leader</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356151</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALLEGATIONS that the son of Mr Jim Brooks, the Labour group leader on Monklands
District Council, saw his career benefit from being a councillor's son were
made at the Government inquiry into the council's employment practices.
It was also suggested that there was a perception that the council was run as a
jobs agency and that the more powerful a councillor was, the more he was able
to hire and fire.
The claims were made by Labour councillor, Mr Tommy Morgan, one of four
so-called rebel councillors whose original allegations of nepotism and
religious bias led to the current inquiry. It has already been established that
at least 48 of the 1500 or so people employed by Monklands District Council are
relatives of councillors.
The inquiry, under Queen's Counsel, Mr William Nimmo Smith, is attempting to
discover whether any criteria other than merit was used in appointments or
promotions.
Mr Brooks has already confirmed to Mr Nimmo Smith that his son Stephen,
daughter Angela, a sister-in-law, and his wife's brother-in-law are council
employees.
Giving evidence to the inquiry at Coatbridge Town Hall yesterday, Mr Morgan
said Mr Stephen Brooks started as an apprentice joiner and was later promoted
to assistant safety officer but claimed that the council leader's son was not
qualified properly for the job and that the post had not been advertised.
He also claimed that Mr Stephen Brooks had applied for his pay to be regraded
upwards and that the request had been approved by two councillors against the
advice of officials.
``Stephen Brooks' career development within Monklands District has benefited
from the fact he is the son of an elected member,'' he said.
He went on: ``Lobbying and pressure has taken place, by councillors on other
councillors. Outwith this chamber it is not unknown for Councillor Brooks to
threaten people who have spoken out on things that might embarrass the district
council.
``The perception is that there is a jobs agency in Monklands and the more
powerful the councillor, the more their right is to hire and fire.''
Another of the rebel councillors, Mr Jim Logue, spoke of an imbalance in
employment opportunities between Coatbridge and Airdrie, the two towns which
dominate the Monklands area.
Mr Logue, an Airdrie councillor, has spoken frequently of a spending bias
towards Coatbridge at the expense of Airdrie. He instanced the council's
caretaker scheme for multi-storey flats where, he claimed, 33 of the original
36 caretakers hired were from Coatbridge.
Scottish National Party councillor, Mr Neil Douglas, told the inquiry he had
investigated the appointment of the then Miss Fiona Loughlin, who, at the time,
was the fiance of Mr Stephen Brooks, to a clerical post.
He said he had raised the appointment with the chief administrative officer, Mr
Allan Clark, and that Mr Clark had told him he had been on holiday when the
appointment was made and that it would not have happened if he had been there.
When asked by Mr Nimmo Smith what action he took, Councillor Douglas said that
as she had already been appointed, there was very little that could be done.
Evidence will be given today by former staff of the local newspaper, the
Airdrie and Coatbridge Advertiser, which has run a lengthy campaign against
alleged council malpractice.
They will be followed tomorrow by the area's two Labour MPs, Mrs Helen Liddell
and Mr Tom Clarke.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000164</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000164</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>City option for Commonwealth</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LYNNE  ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356152</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SPECULATION was growing yesterday that Edinburgh would host the next meeting of
the Commonwealth Heads of Government in 1997.
Lothian and Borders Deputy Chief Constable, Mr Graham Power, is one of two
officers currently in Auckland looking at security arrangements at the most
recent conference in New Zealand earlier this month.
A spokeswoman for the force confirmed the police chief was on official business
in Auckland but added: ``No official confirmation has been given over the venue
for the conference.''
A spokesman for the Scottish Office said the Prime Minister had invited the
Commonwealth Ministers to meet in Britain in 1997.
``The city has not yet been decided. Edinburgh is certainly being considered as
the venue,'' he added.An announcement is likely later this month.
</TEXT>
