<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000165</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000165</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Operation Eagle is declared a success</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALISON DANIELS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356153</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OPERATION Eagle - the Strathclyde Police anti-drugs campaign due to finish at
the end of this month - has been declared a success, with more than 5000
arrests and a significant rise in the number of people reporting drug-related
crimes.
Yesterday, Chief Inspector Bob Renfrew said the main aim had been to get across
to the public that something could be done about drugs. He said that message
seemed to be getting across as calls to the confidential crime-stoppers line
had risen by 150%.
He said that, during the enforcement part of the campaign from the beginning of
September to the November 12, 3598 drug-related cases were reported and there
were 2411 arrests. Of those arrested, the majority were young men with 82
people under 16 and another 505 aged between 16 and 19.
Cannabis accounted for the largest part of drugs seized but there were also
significant recoveries of heroin, speed, and ecstasy.
The chief inspector said that, with the operation coming to an end and officers
assigned to the project going back to their previous duties, the force
continued to depend on the co-operation of local communities.
The police effort to crack down on drug dealers was welcomed by Mr David Bryce
of Glasgow's Calton Athletic drugs recovery group. He said the figures
highlighted what the group had been trying to bring to notice, that drug
dealers were operating in schools and targeting young people.
Mr Bryce said the campaign had sent out a clear message. ``There are too many
mixed messages about drugs. The police live in the real world and have to deal
with the problems. The campaign is taking dealers off the streets.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
