<HEADLINE>Firefighters save human fireball</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356154</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A WOMAN was seriously ill in a hospital burns unit yesterday after turning
herself into a human fireball in front of firefighters.
Mrs Annette Murray's daughter Nicki, 19, had called firefighters from Stirling
to her mothers' first-floor flat. She said her mother had poured turps and
paint stripper over herself and was threatening to set light to her clothing.
Fire and ambulance crews arrived at the scene at the moment she flicked a
cigarette lighter.
Firefighters wrapped her in a blanket and used water to put out the flames.
Mrs Murray, 37, was taken to Stirling Royal Infirmary before being transferred
to the burns unit of Glasgow Royal Infirmary.
Yesterday, she was ``serious but stable'' with third-degree burns to 30% of her
body.
Neighbours of Mrs Murray, in Graystale Road, St Ninians, Stirling, said she had
been depressed.
</TEXT>
