<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>`Kindly old gent' left a fortune</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356155</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BACHELOR Grahame McNaught, 82, gave no hint when he was alive that he was
almost a millionaire.
Mr McNaught, of Upper Sutherland Crescent, Helensburgh, Dunbartonshire, was
described by neighbours yesterday as ``a kindly old gent'' - often seen clad in
flat cap, tweeds, and open-necked shirt.
All were surprised to learn the retired accountant had left almost #1m in
bequests to hospitals and charities.
Lomond Healthcare NHS Trust which runs Vale of Leven Hospital in Alexandria was
left #150,000. Mr McNaught was twice operated on at the hospital before his
death, of a suspected heart attack, earlier this year.
Mr McNaught also willed similar sums to: the Beatson Institute for Cancer
Research in Glasgow; the Prince and Princess of Wales Hospice, Glasgow; the
Princess Louise Scottish Hospital for Ex-Service Personnel at Erskine,
Renfrewshire; The Royal National Lifeboat Institution, and the Marie Curie
Cancer Care Memorial Foundation.
</TEXT>
