<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Taking the sting out of swimming</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356177</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
French scientist Omar Legrini (above) has helped Govan-based Triogen take the
sting out of keeping swimming pools clean. Mr Legrini has been working with
Triogen for 18 months to develop a new method of sterilising swimming pool
water by filtering it through ultraviolet radiation instead of loading it with
chlorine which makes the eyes sting. He moved to Scotland to work full-time for
the company three months ago. Triogen, which has a staff of only 21, sells #2m
a year of water cleansing equipment in over 25 countries. The company was
founded in 1989 and uses oxygenation as well as ultraviolet rays to sterilise
drinking water as well as swimming pools.
</TEXT>
