<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356187</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Police drivers'
lesson wrecked
FOUR police officers were recovering yesterday in Borders General Hospital with
cuts and bruises, after a crash in which their patrol car was wrecked while on
an advanced driving course.
The four - an instructor and three students from the Scottish Police College,
Tulliallan - were parked at the side of a road near Greenlaw, Berwickshire,
when a lorry hit a farm crop sprayer and collided with the police Granada.
First snows
SKIERS were given a boost yesterday with the first real snowfall of the winter.
Nevis Range and the Cairngorms reported good snow cover after sub-zero
conditions and although there is still not enough for skiers to flock to the
mountains, a spokesman for Aviemore Meteorological Centre said more was on the
way.
Harbour airs
A SONG has been composed for the official opening of the #2.2m fishery harbour
at Brevig, Lewis, next Thursday, when 78-year-old Christina Macdonald, will
perform the opening ceremony. Mod winning choir Coisir Og a Bhac will sing
Cidhe Breighig.
Rape charge
A MAN was charged at Aberdeen Sheriff Court yesterday, with abducting a woman
in the city on Monday. Mr Allan Jones, 46, of Linksfield Place, Aberdeen, is
also alleged to have assaulted and raped her. He made no plea or declaration
and was committed for further examination and released on bail.
Indecency denied
POLICEMAN Brian Murphy, 24, of East Moulin Road, Pitlochry, entered a special
defence of alibi at Perth Sheriff Court yesterday, where he denied exposing
himself in a shameless manner in the presence of four children on various
occasions between last April 1 and May 18. He also denies alarming the same
children and two others by presenting himself to them while wearing pants and
bra. More than 20 witnesses are expected to give evidence at his trial, which
opens on November 30.
</TEXT>
