<HEADLINE>Land values back at pre-slump peak</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT ROSS, Farming Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356199</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE value of farmland has risen by an average of 50% since the 1992-93 slump,
bringing it back to levels which mark the peak of the market in 1989, according
to chartered surveying firm Knight Frank &amp; Rutley.
In some areas arable land has almost doubled in value, it says. The market is
being driven by farmers hungry for more land and is supported by some foreign
investment.
The uncertainty which prevailed in the early part of this decade as the UK
entered the recession - with high interest rates and the EU agricultural policy
facing dramatic reform - has given way to a period of buoyancy and optimism,
according to Tony Morris-Eyton, the firm's agricultural partner, in its outlook
briefing for 1996.
He points to a bullish future for farm profitability and, therefore, land
values. He cautions against complacency, however, as overhead costs in the last
12 months have risen by nearly 10% - more than double the retail price index.
Grain stocks have fallen and other essential commodities are no longer in
surplus. UK arable farmers are keen to take on extra acres to make up for land
compulsorily set aside and to spread costs.
``Many can afford to do so,'' Mr Morris-Eyton comments. ``CAP support payments
have been boosted dramatically by currency devaluation.
``At the same time world grain prices, having risen about #20 a tonne in the
last year, are now similar to EU prices. World wheat stocks are forecast at 93
million tonnes, the lowest since 1977-78 and the equivalent to 50 days supply.''
The potato sector, he says, has had record returns for a second year and
prospects also look good for next year.
Deregulation of the dairy industry has led to higher prices for milk and,
although livestock farmers are overshadowed by the threat to live exports, beef
and sheep producers have had better returns. ``Secure businesses are
expanding.''
The briefing highlights some wider influences including world population, which
is expected to increase by 56% over the next 35 years, creating greater demand
for food and good prospects for UK exports.
While harvests and world grain markets seem increasingly to be affected by
unpredictable weather patterns, it suggests the UK's more temperate climate may
be to its advantage.
The green pound - the EU currency used for agriculture - is expected to remain
stable at least until the end of the century, maintaining CAP support payments
for the foreseeable future.
``Although there will inevitably be short-term fluctuations, the future looks
most encouraging,'' Mr Morris-Eyton says.
``If world cereal prices remain stable at over #100 a tonne, as anticipated,
and the reduction of EU support is phased over a decade, the outlook is
extremely positive for UK agriculture and farmland values.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951116-000174</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951116-000174</DOCID>
<DATE>951116</DATE>
<HEADLINE>BBC Pensions in #7.7m deal</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By STEWART McINTOSH Property Corresponden</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>99</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975356200</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
t
A GLASGOW city centre office block has changed hands in a #7.75m deal. The BBC
Pension Trust Ltd has sold 225 Bath Street (right) to Roboscot Ltd, a wholly
owned subsidiary of the Royal Bank of Scotland.
The 88,160 sq.ft building has 37 car spaces and is let in its entirety to
Greater Glasgow Health Board with a tenant's break clause in 2001. The current
rent is #960,000 per annum.
The BBC Pension Trust Ltd was advised by Knight Frank &amp; Rutley in the
transaction, while the Royal Bank of Scotland was advised by Ryden.
In a significant Edinburgh deal, Merchant City Properties, a Glasgow-based
investment, development and management company, has purchased a portfolio of
eleven properties in the New Town from Dunedin Property for around #3m.
MCP is a joint venture between Sydney Freed (Holdings) of Bristol and
London-based European &amp; Pacific Limited. Encouraged by the prospects in
Scotland, the company has been stepping up its activity north of the Border. As
well as the new portfolio, MCP has substantial assets in Glasgow's Merchant
City, including two car parks in prime locations and some 65,000 sq.ft of
retail space. Construction work will start shortly on a seven storey mixed-use
building.
Frank Charnock, director of both MCP and European &amp; Pacific, said: ``MCP is
highly active in Scotland and the acquisition of this portfolio will further
enhance our presence in the region. It is our intention to generate income from
the buildings through creative management in which the firm already has a
proven track record. Nevertheless, disposal of individual properties is likely
over time.''
Dunedin, now part of ING Real Estate, disposed of the portfolio in order to
rationalise their holding in the Edinburgh New Town. Roun Barry, general
manager of ING Real Estate, said: ``The sale of this small proportion of our
Scottish investment portfolio is part of a restructuring exercise which has
been ongoing for almost three years now. Prior to the sale of these properties,
Dunedin was the second largest owner of Georgian New Town commercial properties
by         number.''
Jones Lang Wootton acted for Dunedin, while MCP was advised by Burns and
Partners.
</TEXT>
